# Compact AI enrichment for AP Psych Final Sprint


@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-a.independent-variables
def: Variable manipulated by researcher to cause an effect. / 研究者操控以产生效果的变量。
ex: Giving one group a drug and another a placebo; drug type is IV.
pit: Don’t confuse IV with the measured outcome (DV).
note: AP asks you to identify the IV in an experiment design.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-a.confounding-variables
def: Extra variables that unintentionally affect results. / 意外影响结果的额外变量。
ex: Participants’ age if not controlled, both groups differ in age.
pit: Confounds can threaten internal validity; not just any variable.
note: AP FRQ often asks you to identify or propose control for confounds.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-a.dependent-variables
def: Measured outcome that may change due to IV. / 因IV变化而测量的结果。
ex: In drug study, symptom score after treatment is DV.
pit: DV depends on IV, not the other way.
note: Know how to operationally define the DV.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-a.random-assignment
def: Placing participants into groups by chance to reduce bias. / 随机分组以减少偏差。
ex: Flipping a coin to assign subjects to control or treatment.
pit: Random assignment ≠ random sampling (sampling from population).
note: AP highlights random assignment controls for confounds.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-a.hypothesis
def: Testable prediction about relationship between variables. / 关于变量关系的可检验预测。
ex: “Students who study more will have higher test scores.”
pit: Hypothesis must be falsifiable and specific.
note: FRQ may ask you to write a hypothesis for an experiment.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-a.generalizability
def: Extent findings apply to wider population beyond sample. / 研究结果推广到更大人群的程度。
ex: If sample is all college students, results may not generalize to elderly.
pit: Generalizability depends on sampling method, not sample size alone.
note: AP often asks about external validity (generalizability).

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-a.quantitative-data
def: Numerical data that can be measured and analyzed statistically. / 可测量和统计分析的数值数据。
ex: Reaction time in milliseconds, test scores.
pit: Quantitative ≠ qualitative; count vs. description.
note: AP asks to identify type of data in studies.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-a.qualitative-data
def: Non-numerical descriptive data (words, images, etc.). / 非数值的描述性数据（文字、图像等）。
ex: Interview transcripts describing emotions after event.
pit: Qualitative is subjective and hard to quantify; often used in case studies.
note: AP distinguishes qualitative from quantitative in research methods.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-b.institutional-review
def: Review by IRB to ensure ethical standards in research. / 机构审查委员会审查以确保研究伦理。
ex: A university IRB approves or rejects a study proposal.
pit: IRB review occurs before data collection, not after.
note: AP ethics questions focus on IRB role in protecting participants.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-b.informed-consent
def: Participants agree to participate after being told risks/benefits. / 告知风险和利益后参与者同意。
ex: Signing a consent form before a psychology experiment.
pit: Consent must be voluntary and informed; deception requires debriefing.
note: AP tests understanding of exceptions (e.g., minimal risk, deception).

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-b.informed-assent
def: Agreement by a minor to participate in research after understanding procedures, in addition to parental consent / 未成年人同意参与研究，需理解程序并获得家长同意
ex: Asking a 12‑year‑old to sign an assent form before a study
pit: Confusing with informed consent (assent = minor, consent = guardian)
note: Required for minors; must be documented

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-b.protection-from-harm
def: Ensuring participants are not exposed to physical or psychological harm / 确保参与者不受身心伤害
ex: Stopping a study if a participant becomes distressed
pit: Harm includes psychological stress, not just physical
note: APA ethical guideline; must be followed

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-b.confidentiality
def: Keeping participants' data private and not revealing identities / 保密参与者数据，不泄露身份
ex: Using code numbers instead of names in data files
pit: Not the same as anonymity; confidentiality protects linked data, anonymity means no link
note: Must be promised and maintained throughout study

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-b.deception
def: Misleading participants about the true purpose of a study (allowed only if necessary and ethical) / 对参与者隐瞒研究真实目的（仅在必要且符合伦理时允许）
ex: Telling participants they are testing memory when actually studying reaction to stressful words
pit: Must be justified and followed by debriefing; cannot cause harm
note: Requires IRB approval and thorough debriefing

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-b.debriefing
def: Explaining the true purpose of a study to participants after completion, especially if deception was used / 研究结束后向参与者解释真实目的，尤其在使用欺骗后
ex: After a memory test deception, telling participants the real goal
pit: Debriefing should address any distress and educate; not just “thank you”
note: Mandatory after deception; good practice for all studies

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-c.central-tendency
def: A statistical measure that identifies a single score as representative of an entire distribution (mean, median, mode) / 代表整个数据集集中趋势的统计量（平均数、中数、众数）
ex: Describing class average on a test
pit: Not about spread; different from variation
note: Know the three types and when to use each

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-c.mean
def: Arithmetic average; sum of scores divided by number of scores / 算术平均数：总分除以个数
ex: Scores 80+90+70 = 240 → mean = 80
pit: Sensitive to extreme scores (outliers)
note: Use median if distribution is skewed

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-c.median
def: Middle score when data are ordered; 50th percentile / 中位数：排序后的中间分数
ex: Scores 70,80,90 → median = 80
pit: For even number of scores, average the two middle values
note: Best for skewed distributions (e.g., income)

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-c.mode
def: Most frequently occurring score / 众数：出现次数最多的分数
ex: Scores 70,80,80,90 → mode = 80
pit: Can have multiple modes or no mode (bimodal, multimodal)
note: Useful for nominal (categorical) data

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-c.variation
def: Measure of how spread out scores are in a distribution (e.g., range, standard deviation) / 数据分散程度的度量（如全距、标准差）
ex: High variation → scores differ widely; low variation → scores similar
pit: Variation does not indicate central tendency; same mean, different spread possible
note: Know range and standard deviation as key measures

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-c.percentile-rank
def: The percentage of scores in a distribution that fall below a given score / 百分位排名：某分数低于分布中其他分数的百分比。
ex: Scoring 85th percentile means you did better than 85% of test-takers.
pit: Confusing percentile rank with percentage correct; they are different.
note: AP often asks to interpret percentile rank in data analysis.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-c.range
def: The difference between the highest and lowest scores in a distribution / 全距：分布中最高分与最低分之差。
ex: Scores 2, 4, 6, 8 → range = 6.
pit: Range is highly influenced by outliers.
note: Know range vs. standard deviation; range is crude.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.normal-curve
def: A symmetric, bell-shaped curve that represents the distribution of many traits / 正态曲线：对称的钟形曲线，代表许多特质的分布。
ex: IQ scores are normally distributed with mean 100.
pit: Assuming all data is normal; many real-world distributions are not.
note: AP uses normal curve for z-scores and probability.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.bimodal-distribution
def: A distribution with two distinct peaks / 双峰分布：有两个明显峰值的分布。
ex: Heights of both men and women combined often show two peaks.
pit: Confusing bimodal with skewed; look for two separate clusters.
note: AP may ask to identify from graph or explain possible cause.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.standard-deviation
def: A measure of variability that indicates the average distance of scores from the mean / 标准差：衡量数据与均值平均偏离程度的指标。
ex: Small SD means scores cluster tightly; large SD means spread out.
pit: Misinterpreting SD as percentage; SD is in original units.
note: AP expects to know that ~68% within ±1 SD in normal curve.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.regression-toward-the-mean
def: The tendency for extreme scores to be followed by scores closer to the average / 回归均值：极端分数后通常出现更接近平均值的分数。
ex: A student who scores extremely high on one test will likely score lower on the next.
pit: Thinking regression is caused by something specific; it's statistical.
note: AP often tests this with research design or correlation.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.positive-skew
def: A distribution where the tail extends to the right (higher values) / 正偏态：分布尾部向右延伸（高数值方向）。
ex: Income distribution: most earn moderate but a few very high earners pull the mean right.
pit: Confusing skew direction: mean > median in positive skew.
note: AP identifies from graph: tail points to positive side.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.negative-skew
def: A distribution where the tail extends to the left (lower values) / 负偏态：分布尾部向左延伸（低数值方向）。
ex: Age at retirement: most retire around 65, but a few retire very early.
pit: Mean < median in negative skew; opposite of positive skew.
note: AP may compare with positive skew; know which measure is affected.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.scatterplot
def: A graph that shows the relationship between two variables using dots / 散点图：用点表示两个变量关系的图表。
ex: Plotting hours studied vs. test scores shows if they correlate.
pit: Assuming causation from correlation visible in scatterplot.
note: AP uses scatterplots to illustrate correlation direction and strength.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.correlation
def: A statistical measure that indicates the extent to which two variables are related / 相关：衡量两个变量之间关联程度的统计量。
ex: r = +0.8 indicates strong positive correlation; r = -0.3 weak negative.
pit: Correlation does not imply causation.
note: AP expects interpretation of r values and sign.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.positive-correlation
def: Two variables move in the same direction (both increase or decrease). / 两个变量同向变化（同增或同减）。
ex: As hours studied increase, test scores increase.
pit: Correlation does not imply causation; a positive correlation does not prove one variable causes the other.
note: AP exam may ask to identify direction from a scatterplot or data table.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.negative-correlation
def: Two variables move in opposite directions (one increases, the other decreases). / 两个变量反向变化（一增一减）。
ex: As anxiety increases, test performance decreases.
pit: Negative correlation ≠ no relationship; it shows a consistent inverse pattern.
note: Look for negative slope in scatterplot; coefficient near -1 indicates strong negative.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-d.correlation-coefficient
def: A numerical index (r) from -1.00 to +1.00 measuring the strength and direction of a linear relationship. / 数值指标（r），范围-1.00到+1.00，衡量线性关系的强度和方向。
ex: r = -0.85 indicates a strong negative correlation.
pit: Absolute value indicates strength; sign indicates direction. Perfect correlation (±1) is rare in real data.
note: AP FRQ often asks to interpret r value and distinguish from causation.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-e.population
def: The entire group of interest from which a sample is drawn. / 研究者感兴趣的全部群体，从中抽取样本。
ex: All high school students in the U.S.
pit: Population must be clearly defined; confusing population with sample leads to external validity errors.
note: AP asks: "What is the population in this study?" — answer must match the research question.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-e.sample
def: A subset of the population that actually participates in the study. / 实际参与研究的群体子集。
ex: 200 high school students from one school.
pit: A biased sample (e.g., only volunteers) may not represent the population.
note: AP exam tests generalizability: sample must represent population to apply findings.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-e.representative-sample
def: A sample that accurately reflects the characteristics of the population. / 准确反映总体特征的样本。
ex: Matching population’s gender ratio, age distribution, etc.
pit: Convenience samples are rarely representative; claiming representativeness without evidence is a trap.
note: Key for external validity; FRQ may ask "Is the sample representative? Why or why not?"

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-e.random-sampling
def: Every member of the population has an equal chance of being selected. / 总体中每个成员被选中的机会相等。
ex: Using a random number generator to pick participants from a list.
pit: Random sampling ≠ random assignment (assignment is for experiments). Random sampling increases generalizability.
note: AP distinguishes random sampling (selection) from random assignment (condition allocation).

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-e.convenience-sampling
def: Selecting participants who are easily accessible (e.g., nearby volunteers). / 选择容易接触的参与者（如附近的志愿者）。
ex: Using psychology class students for a study.
pit: Often leads to biased, non-representative samples; a common method but weak in external validity.
note: AP asks to identify sampling method; point out its limitation for generalization.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-e.representation-of-participants
def: How well the sample mirrors the population in key traits. / 样本在关键特征上反映总体的程度。
ex: If population is 50% female, sample should be ~50% female to have good representation.
pit: Overlooking representation leads to claims that don't apply to subgroups (e.g., gender, culture).
note: FRQ may ask to discuss representation when critiquing a study's generalizability.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-e.experimental-group
def: The group in an experiment that receives the treatment (the manipulated independent variable). / 实验中接受处理（操纵自变量）的组。
ex: In a drug trial, the group that gets the actual drug.
pit: Confusing experimental group with control group; both are essential for comparison.
note: AP asks to identify experimental group in a scenario; remember it's the condition where IV is applied.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-e.control-group
def: Group not receiving treatment; used for comparison / 对照组
ex: In drug trial, group gets placebo.
pit: Confusing with experimental group (which gets treatment).
note: Key for identifying cause-effect relationships.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-e.single-blind-study
def: Participants unaware of which condition they are in; researcher knows / 单盲实验
ex: Patients don't know if they got drug or placebo.
pit: Researcher bias still possible (expectations affect results).
note: Reduces participant demand characteristics.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-e.double-blind-study
def: Both participants and researchers unaware of condition assignment / 双盲实验
ex: Neither doctor nor patient knows who gets real drug.
pit: Confusing single-blind with double-blind.
note: Gold standard to minimize bias.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-f.operational-definition
def: Exact procedures used to measure or manipulate a variable / 操作定义
ex: “Aggression” defined as number of times a child hits a doll.
pit: Different definitions measure different constructs.
note: Essential for replicability of experiments.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-f.case-study
def: In-depth examination of one individual or small group / 案例研究
ex: Phineas Gage (personality change after brain injury).
pit: Cannot generalize findings to the wider population.
note: Useful for rare or unusual phenomena.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-f.meta-analysis
def: Statistical technique that combines results from multiple studies / 元分析
ex: Averaging effect sizes from 50 studies on therapy effectiveness.
pit: Not just a narrative literature review.
note: Increases statistical power and identifies overall trends.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-f.naturalistic-observation
def: Observing behavior in a natural setting without interference / 自然观察
ex: Watching children’s play interactions at a playground.
pit: Observer effect (reactivity) and lack of control.
note: High external validity; cannot determine cause-effect.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-f.structured-interviews
def: Interview using predetermined questions in a fixed order / 结构化访谈
ex: Job interview where all applicants answer same questions.
pit: Less flexible to explore unexpected topics.
note: Increases reliability and comparability across participants.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-f.likert-scale
def: Rating scale with options from strongly agree to strongly disagree / 李克特量表
ex: “I enjoy puzzles” rated on 1–5 scale.
pit: Central tendency bias (avoiding extremes).
note: Common in self-report surveys; yields ordinal data.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-f.effect-size
def: Measure of the strength of a relationship or magnitude of a difference / 效应量
ex: Cohen’s d = 0.8 indicates a large effect.
pit: Not the same as statistical significance (p-value).
note: Indicates practical importance, independent of sample size.

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-f.statistical-significance
def: A result is statistically significant if the probability of it occurring by chance is very low (typically p < .05) / 统计显著性指结果由偶然因素导致的概率极低（通常p<.05）
ex: A drug trial shows p = .03, indicating only 3% chance results are due to random variation / 药物试验p=0.03，表示结果由随机变异产生的概率仅3%
pit: Confusing significance with effect size; a tiny effect can be significant with large sample / 混淆显著性与效应量；大样本下微小效应也可能显著
note: FRQ may ask to interpret “statistically significant” in context – always check p-value threshold / 自由答题可能要求解释“统计显著性”，务必注意p值阈值

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-f.replication
def: Repeating a study using the same methods to see if results are consistent / 重复研究：用相同方法再次实验，检验结果是否一致
ex: A memory experiment finding “rehearsal improves recall” is repeated by another lab with new participants / 一个记忆实验发现“复述提高回忆”，另一实验室用新被试重复
pit: A failed replication does not always mean original was wrong; could be due to hidden variables / 重复失败不意味着原实验错误，可能由隐藏变量导致
note: AP emphasizes replication crisis – be ready to discuss why replication matters for validity / AP强调“重复危机”，需讨论重复对有效性的意义

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-f.peer-review
def: Evaluation of research by other experts in the same field before publication / 同行评审：同一领域其他专家在发表前对研究的评估
ex: A psychologist submits a paper to a journal; anonymous reviewers critique methodology, analysis, conclusions / 心理学家投稿期刊，匿名评审批评方法、分析、结论
pit: Peer review does not guarantee truth, only that the study meets basic standards / 同行评审不保证正确，仅确保符合基本标准
note: AP often asks why peer review is important for scientific integrity / AP常问同行评审为何对科学诚信重要

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.falsifiability-pertaining-to-hypotheses
def: A hypothesis must be able to be proven false by evidence / 可证伪性：假设必须能够被证据证明为假
ex: “All swans are white” is falsifiable; finding one black swan disproves it / “所有天鹅都是白的”可证伪；发现一只黑天鹅即可证伪
pit: Non‑falsifiable claims (e.g., “there is an invisible dragon in my garage”) cannot be tested scientifically / 不可证伪的断言（如“车库里有一只隐形龙”）无法科学检验
note: AP sometimes ties falsifiability to Popper and pseudoscience / AP有时将可证伪性与波普尔及伪科学联系起来

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.placebo
def: An inactive substance or condition used as a control in experiments / 安慰剂：实验中用作对照的无活性物质或条件
ex: In a painkiller trial, some participants receive a sugar pill (placebo) instead of the real drug / 止痛药试验中，部分被试服用糖丸（安慰剂）代替真药
pit: Placebo is not the same as placebo effect; placebo is the inert treatment / 安慰剂≠安慰剂效应；安慰剂是惰性处理
note: AP asks how placebo controls help rule out expectancy effects / AP问安慰剂对照如何排除预期效应

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.placebo-effect
def: Improvement resulting from a person's belief or expectation about a treatment, not from the treatment itself / 安慰剂效应：因对治疗的信念或期望产生的改善，非治疗本身所致
ex: Patients told a sugar pill is a pain reliever report less pain / 被告知糖丸是止痛药的患者报告疼痛减轻
pit: The placebo effect can occur even with real treatments – it's about psychological response / 安慰剂效应可能发生在真治疗中——它是心理反应
note: AP connects placebo effect to confounding variables in experiments / AP将安慰剂效应与实验中的混淆变量联系起来

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.overconfidence
def: The tendency to overestimate the accuracy of one’s knowledge, judgments, or abilities / 过度自信：高估自己知识、判断或能力准确性的倾向
ex: Students often predict they will score higher on an exam than they actually do / 学生常预测自己考试分数高于实际得分
pit: Overconfidence is not the same as self‑esteem; it's a cognitive bias about accuracy / 过度自信≠自尊；它是关于准确性的认知偏差
note: AP may cite overconfidence to explain why people make flawed decisions (e.g., investing) / AP可能引用过度自信解释人们为何做出错误决策（如投资）

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.directionality-problem-in-correlation
def: In a correlation, we cannot know which variable causes the other – direction of causation is unclear / 相关中的方向性问题：无法确定哪个变量导致另一个——因果方向不明确
ex: Ice cream sales and crime rate correlate: does ice cream cause crime, or crime cause ice cream buying? / 冰淇淋销量与犯罪率相关：冰淇淋导致犯罪，还是犯罪导致买冰淇淋？
pit: Students often assume correlation implies causation; directionality problem shows that's false / 学生常认为相关即因果；方向性问题表明这错误
note: AP FRQ often asks to identify directionality problem in a given correlation / AP自由答题常要求识别给定相关中的方向性问题

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.third-variable-problem-in-correlation
def: A third variable may be causing both correlated variables, producing a spurious correlation / 第三变量问题：第三个变量可能同时导致两个相关变量，产生伪相关
ex: Ice cream sales and drowning deaths correlate; the third variable is hot weather (more swimming) / 冰淇淋销量与溺水死亡相关；第三变量是炎热天气（更多游泳）
pit: Not the same as directionality problem; here a hidden variable explains the link / 不同于方向性问题；这里是隐藏变量解释关联
note: AP emphasizes that correlational studies cannot establish causation due to third variables / AP强调相关研究因第三变量无法确立因果

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.experimenter-bias
def: When a researcher’s expectations or preferences influence the study results (e.g., data recording, interpretation) / 实验者偏差：研究者的期望或偏好影响研究结果（如数据记录、解释）
ex: A researcher who expects a new drug to work may unconsciously notice more positive outcomes in the treatment group / 预期新药有效的研究者可能无意识地在治疗组注意到更多积极结果
pit: Experimenter bias can affect both human and animal subjects if the researcher interacts differently / 实验者偏差可能影响人类和动物被试，因为研究者互动方式不同
note: AP discusses double‑blind procedures as a way to reduce experimenter bias / AP讨论双盲程序是减少实验者偏差的方法

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.social-desirability-bias
def: Tendency to answer questions in a way that will be viewed favorably by others / 社会赞许性偏差：回答问题时倾向于给出被他人认可的回答
ex: Survey respondents overreport voting frequency / 受访者高报投票频率
pit: Confuse with self-report bias; social desirability is about wanting to look good / 易混淆：与自我报告偏差不同，它强调“讨好”他人
note: Common in self-report surveys; AP asks about its effect on validity / 常考：影响调查效度

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.cultural-norms
def: Shared expectations and rules of behavior within a group / 文化规范：群体内共享的行为期望和规则
ex: Bowing when greeting in Japan / 日本见面鞠躬
pit: Not the same as personal values; norms are external expectations / 易混：个人价值观不同，规范是外部期望
note: AP can ask how norms affect research generalizability / 常考：影响研究推广性

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.confirmation-bias
def: Tendency to search for, interpret, and recall information that confirms one’s preexisting beliefs / 证实偏差：倾向于寻找、解释和回忆支持自己已有信念的信息
ex: Only reading news that aligns with your political views / 只看符合自己政治观点的新闻
pit: Confuse with hindsight bias; confirmation bias is about seeking confirming evidence / 易混：后见偏差不同，它是“我早就知道”
note: Frequently tested in research methods and cognitive biases / 常考：研究方法与认知偏差

@@ ap-psychology.science-practices.set-g.hindsight-bias
def: Tendency to believe, after an event, that one “knew it all along” / 后见偏差：事后认为“我早就知道”
ex: After a stock market crash, saying “I knew that would happen” / 股灾后说“我早知道会这样”
pit: Confuse with overconfidence; hindsight is about post-event certainty / 易混：过度自信不同，这里强调事后聪明
note: Classic “I-knew-it-all-along” phenomenon; AP loves it in experiments / 经典“事后诸葛亮”，AP实验设计常考

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-1.heredity
def: Genetic transmission of traits from parents to offspring / 遗传：父母将特征通过基因传递给后代
ex: Eye color passed from mother to child / 母亲传给孩子眼睛颜色
pit: Heredity ≠ genetics entirely; heredity is the process of passing genes / 易混：遗传是传递过程，不完全是基因本身
note: Foundation for nature vs nurture debate / 先天后天辩论基础

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-1.nature
def: The influence of genetic inheritance on behavior and mental processes / 天性：基因遗传对行为和心理过程的影响
ex: Identical twins having similar temperaments / 同卵双生儿气质相似
pit: Nature is not just biology; it includes evolutionary predispositions / 易混：天性不仅是生物，还包括进化倾向
note: Compare with nurture in AP essays / AP论文中常与教养对比

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-1.nurture
def: Environmental influences shaping behavior and mental processes / 教养：环境因素对行为和心理过程的塑造
ex: A child learning language from caregivers / 孩子从看护者那里学语言
pit: Nurture includes all experience, not just parenting / 易混：教养包括所有经验，不止养育
note: Interaction with nature is key; not either/or / 关键是与天性相互作用

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-1.genetic-predisposition
def: Increased likelihood of developing a trait or disorder based on genetic makeup / 遗传易感性：基于基因构成而更可能发展出某种特质或障碍
ex: Family history of depression increases risk / 抑郁家族史增加风险
pit: Not destiny; environment can trigger or prevent expression / 易混：非注定，环境可触发或阻止表达
note: AP often links to diathesis-stress model / 常联系“素质-压力模型”

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-1.evolutionary-perspective
def: Approach that explains behavior by how it promotes survival and reproduction / 进化视角：从促进生存和繁殖的角度解释行为
ex: Fear of snakes helps avoid danger / 怕蛇有助于避开危险
pit: Not the same as natural selection; this perspective applies evolution to psychology / 易混：不是自然选择本身，而是其心理学应用
note: Used to explain universal behaviors like mate preferences / 解释普遍行为如择偶偏好

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-1.natural-selection
def: Process by which traits that enhance survival and reproduction are passed on more frequently / 自然选择：增强生存与繁殖的特征更频繁传递的过程
ex: Antibiotic resistance in bacteria / 细菌的抗生素耐药性
pit: Confuse with “survival of the fittest” oversimplification; “fittest” means best adapted / 易混：“适者生存”过于简化，适者指适应良好
note: Basis for evolutionary perspective in psychology / 进化视角的基础

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-1.eugenics
def: The belief that human traits can be improved through selective breeding / 通过选择性繁殖改善人类特质的观点
ex: Historical forced sterilization of "unfit" individuals in early 20th century US
pit: Often confused with genetics; eugenics is a social/political movement, not genetics itself
note: AP Psychology typically tests eugenics as a historical misuse of genetic concepts, not as accepted science.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-1.twin-studies
def: Research method comparing identical (monozygotic) and fraternal (dizygotic) twins to estimate genetic vs environmental influence / 通过比较同卵和异卵双生子来估计遗传与环境影响的研究方法
ex: If identical twins show higher concordance for IQ than fraternal twins, it suggests genetic influence
pit: Assumes identical twins share equal environment; critics point to "equal environments assumption"
note: AP cue: Twin studies provide key evidence for heritability estimates.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-1.family-studies
def: Research examining how traits run in families to infer genetic influence / 研究特质在家族中如何传递以推断遗传影响的方法
ex: Children of depressed parents are more likely to be depressed, but this could be due to shared environment or genetics
pit: Cannot separate genetic from environmental influences (confound of shared environment)
note: AP cue: Family studies are correlational; they suggest but do not prove genetic links.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-1.adoption-studies
def: Comparing adopted children to biological and adoptive parents to separate genetic and environmental effects / 比较被收养孩子与生父母及养父母，以分离遗传与环境影响
ex: Adopted child's IQ correlates more with biological parents' IQ than adoptive parents' IQ → supports genetic influence
pit: Adoption may not be random; selective placement can confound results
note: AP cue: Adoption studies provide stronger evidence than family studies for genetic influences.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-2.central-nervous-system-brain-and-spinal-cord
def: The brain and spinal cord; the body's decision-making and command center / 大脑和脊髓；身体的决策和指挥中枢
ex: Reflexes like pulling hand from hot stove are processed in spinal cord without brain
pit: Confusing CNS with PNS; CNS only includes brain and spinal cord, not nerves
note: AP cue: CNS is the core; spinal cord handles simple reflexes.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-2.peripheral-nervous-system
def: All nerves outside the brain and spinal cord; connects CNS to limbs and organs / 大脑和脊髓之外的所有神经；连接中枢神经系统与四肢和器官
ex: Nerves in your arm that sense pain and move muscles
pit: Students often think PNS only includes sensory nerves; it also includes motor nerves
note: AP cue: PNS has two divisions: somatic and autonomic.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-2.autonomic-nervous-system
def: Division of PNS that controls involuntary functions (heartbeat, digestion, glands) / 自主神经系统：控制心跳、消化、腺体等不随意功能的PNS分支
ex: Your heart rate increases during exercise automatically
pit: Called "autonomic" not because it works on its own, but because it regulates self-governing body functions
note: AP cue: Autonomic = automatic; consists of sympathetic and parasympathetic branches.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-2.sympathetic-nervous-system
def: Part of ANS that arouses the body for "fight or flight" responses / 交感神经系统：引起身体“战斗或逃跑”反应
ex: Dilates pupils, accelerates heart rate, inhibits digestion when scared
pit: Not the same as central nervous system; it's a branch of ANS in PNS
note: AP cue: Sympathetic = arousing; prepares body for stress.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-2.parasympathetic-nervous-system
def: Part of ANS that calms the body, promoting "rest and digest" functions / 副交感神经系统：使身体平静，促进“休息和消化”
ex: Slows heart rate, stimulates digestion after a meal
pit: Often confused as the opposite of sympathetic; it's actually the antagonist for homeostasis
note: AP cue: Parasympathetic = calming; conserves energy.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-2.somatic-nervous-system
def: Division of PNS that controls voluntary movements and transmits sensory information / 躯体神经系统：控制随意运动并传递感觉信息的PNS分支
ex: You consciously decide to wave your hand; motor neurons carry the signal
pit: Students sometimes think "somatic" means body (like automatic), but it's voluntary
note: AP cue: Somatic = sensory and motor neurons; under conscious control.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.neurons
def: Nerve cells that receive, process, and transmit electrochemical information / 神经元：接收、处理并传递电化学信息的神经细胞
ex: A sensory neuron in your finger sends a signal to your brain when you touch a hot stove
pit: Students often confuse neurons with glial cells; neurons are the primary communicators, glia support them
note: AP loves asking about neuron structure (dendrites, axon, cell body) and function in the nervous system

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.glial-cells
def: Support cells that nourish, insulate, and protect neurons; also involved in learning and memory / 神经胶质细胞：滋养、绝缘和保护神经元的支持细胞，也参与学习和记忆
ex: Oligodendrocytes produce myelin sheath in the CNS
pit: Don't think glial cells only provide "glue"; they also speed up neural transmission via myelination
note: Myelination by glial cells is a key FRQ concept for action potential speed

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.reflex-arc
def: A simple, automatic response to a stimulus involving sensory, interneuron, and motor neurons; bypasses the brain / 反射弧：对刺激的简单自动反应，涉及感觉神经元、中间神经元和运动神经元，绕过大脑
ex: Knee-jerk reflex: tap patellar tendon → sensory neuron → spinal cord → motor neuron → leg kicks
pit: Reflex arcs still involve interneurons in the spinal cord; not just two neurons
note: Often tested as an example of the spinal cord's role without brain involvement

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.sensory-neurons
def: Afferent neurons that carry incoming information from sensory receptors to the CNS / 感觉神经元：传入神经元，将来自感受器的信息传入中枢神经系统
ex: Photoreceptors in the eye activate sensory neurons that send visual info to the brain
pit: Sensory neurons are afferent (arrive at CNS); motor neurons are efferent (exit CNS)
note: Key term: "afferent" → feels like "arrive"

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.motor-neurons
def: Efferent neurons that carry outgoing commands from the CNS to muscles and glands / 运动神经元：传出神经元，将中枢神经系统的指令传给肌肉和腺体
ex: Motor neurons cause your biceps to contract when you lift a cup
pit: Do not confuse with interneurons; motor neurons directly activate effectors
note: Efferent = exit CNS; opposite of afferent/sensory

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.interneurons
def: Neurons within the CNS that connect sensory and motor neurons; involved in processing and reflexes / 中间神经元：中枢神经系统内连接感觉和运动神经元的神经元，参与处理和反射
ex: In the spinal cord, an interneuron relays the signal from sensory to motor neuron in a reflex arc
pit: Interneurons are only in the CNS (brain and spinal cord), not in peripheral nerves
note: They outnumber sensory and motor neurons; critical for complex neural networks

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.neural-transmission
def: The process by which an electrical signal travels along a neuron and across a synapse via neurotransmitters / 神经传导：电信号沿神经元传播并通过突触以神经递质传递的过程
ex: When you decide to move your hand, neural transmission occurs from brain to hand muscles
pit: Sometimes students think transmission is purely electrical; it switches to chemical at the synapse
note: Know the steps: action potential → synaptic vesicle release → neurotransmitter binding

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.action-potential
def: A brief electrical impulse that travels down the axon, triggered by depolarization past threshold / 动作电位：由去极化超过阈值触发的、沿轴突传播的短暂电脉冲
ex: When a neuron fires, the action potential "all-or-nothing" message is sent down the axon
pit: Action potentials are not "stronger" with stronger stimuli; they are all-or-nothing (but frequency can vary)
note: Typically tested with the "all-or-nothing principle" and ion movement (Na+ in, K+ out)

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.all-or-nothing-principle
def: The principle that a neuron fires an action potential at full strength or not at all, depending on whether threshold is reached / 全或无原则：神经元要么以全强度发射动作电位，要么不发射，取决于是否达到阈值
ex: Like a gun: slight pull may not fire, but once you pull past the threshold, the bullet is always shot with same force
pit: Stimuli above threshold do not produce bigger action potentials, but can increase firing rate
note: Multiple choice: "Which principle explains why a strong pinch and a light touch both create an action potential in one neuron?" → All-or-nothing

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.depolarization
def: The shift in membrane potential from negative to positive, usually caused by sodium ions entering the cell / 去极化：膜电位从负向正的转变，通常由钠离子内流引起
ex: When a stimulus opens Na+ channels, the inside of the neuron becomes less negative, leading to depolarization
pit: Depolarization is NOT the same as action potential; it is the initial phase that leads to it if threshold is reached
note: Know the three phases: depolarization (Na+ in), repolarization (K+ out), hyperpolarization (more negative)

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.refractory-period
def: A brief period after an action potential when the neuron cannot fire again / 不应期：动作电位后神经元无法再次放电的短暂时期
ex: After a neuron fires, it pauses ~1-2 ms before it can fire again // 神经元放电后暂停约1-2毫秒才能再次放电
pit: Students confuse it with resting potential; refractory period is the *post-firing* reset, not the resting state // 易混淆为静息电位，不应期是放电后重置期
note: AP tip: refractory period ensures action potentials travel one direction and limit firing rate // 确保动作电位单向传导并限制放电频率

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.resting-potential
def: The stable, negative charge of a neuron when it is not firing (typically -70 mV) / 静息电位：神经元未放电时的稳定负电荷（约-70毫伏）
ex: Inside of axon is more negative than outside at rest // 静息时轴突内部比外部更负
pit: Don't think it's zero; it's negative due to more K⁺ inside, Na⁺ outside // 不是零，因内部钾离子多、外部钠离子多而呈负性
note: AP key: resting potential is maintained by sodium-potassium pump // 由钠钾泵维持

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.reuptake
def: Process by which neurotransmitters are reabsorbed into the presynaptic neuron after release / 再摄取：神经递质释放后被突触前神经元重新吸收的过程
ex: SSRIs block serotonin reuptake to increase mood // SSRIs阻断5-羟色胺再摄取以提升情绪
pit: Students think reuptake happens *in* the synapse; it happens *into* the presynaptic terminal // 误以为在突触内发生，实际是再摄入突触前末梢
note: AP exam: drugs that block reuptake (like cocaine, SSRIs) increase neurotransmitter in synapse // 阻断再摄取的药物（可卡因、SSRIs）增加突触递质浓度

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.threshold
def: The minimum level of stimulation needed to trigger an action potential (typically -55 mV) / 阈值：触发动作电位所需的最低刺激水平（约-55毫伏）
ex: If a neuron's voltage reaches threshold, it fires; below, it does not // 若电压达阈值则放电，否则不放电
pit: All-or-none principle: threshold must be met; partial stimulation does not produce smaller impulse // 全或无原则：必须达到阈值，部分刺激不产生较小脉冲
note: AP cue: threshold is the tipping point for action potential // 阈值是动作电位的临界点

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.multiple-sclerosis
def: An autoimmune disease where the myelin sheath is destroyed, slowing neural impulses / 多发性硬化：自体免疫病破坏髓鞘，减缓神经冲动传导
ex: Symptoms include numbness, vision loss, fatigue // 症状包括麻木、视力丧失、疲劳
pit: Confuse with myasthenia gravis; MS affects *myelin* (insulation), not the synapse // 易与重症肌无力混淆，MS影响髓鞘（绝缘层），而非突触
note: AP tip: illustrates importance of myelin sheath for speed // 说明髓鞘对传导速度的重要性

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.myasthenia-gravis
def: A chronic autoimmune disorder causing muscle weakness due to blocked acetylcholine receptors / 重症肌无力：慢性自体免疫病，因乙酰胆碱受体受阻导致肌肉无力
ex: Drooping eyelids, difficulty swallowing // 眼睑下垂，吞咽困难
pit: Differentiate from multiple sclerosis: MG affects *receptors* at neuromuscular junction; MS affects *myelin* // 与MS区别：MG影响神经肌肉接头受体，MS影响髓鞘
note: AP: treatment often includes drugs that inhibit acetylcholinesterase // 治疗常用抑制乙酰胆碱酯酶药物

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.dopamine
def: A neurotransmitter involved in movement, reward, and pleasure / 多巴胺：参与运动、奖赏和愉悦的神经递质
ex: Parkinson’s disease results from dopamine deficiency; addiction linked to dopamine surges // 帕金森病因多巴胺不足成瘾与多巴胺激增有关
pit: Oversimplify as "pleasure chemical"; it’s more about *anticipation* and motivation // 勿简化成“快乐化学物”，更多与预期和动机相关
note: AP common: dopamine pathways in schizophrenia (excess) and addiction // 精神分裂症（过度）和成瘾中的多巴胺通路

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.excitatory-neurotransmitters
def: Neurotransmitters that increase the likelihood of the postsynaptic neuron firing / 兴奋性神经递质：增加突触后神经元放电可能性的递质
ex: Acetylcholine at neuromuscular junctions causes muscle contraction // 神经肌肉接头处乙酰胆碱引起肌肉收缩
pit: Some neurotransmitters (e.g., acetylcholine) can be excitatory *or* inhibitory depending on receptor // 某些递质（如乙酰胆碱）根据受体不同可兴奋或抑制
note: AP: important for understanding EPSPs (excitatory postsynaptic potentials) // 理解兴奋性突触后电位（EPSP）的基础

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.inhibitory-neurotransmitters
def: Neurotransmitters that decrease the likelihood of the postsynaptic neuron firing / 抑制性神经递质：降低突触后神经元放电可能性的递质
ex: GABA reduces neural activity, calming anxiety // GABA降低神经活动，缓解焦虑
pit: Don't think "inhibitory" means always slow; they regulate balance // 勿以为“抑制”总是减慢，它们调节平衡
note: AP cue: hyperpolarization makes neuron less likely to fire // 超极化使神经元更难放电

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.serotonin
def: A neurotransmitter that regulates mood, sleep, appetite, and pain / 5-羟色胺（血清素）：调节情绪、睡眠、食欲和疼痛的神经递质
ex: Low serotonin linked to depression; SSRIs increase serotonin levels // 低血清素与抑郁相关，SSRIs提高血清素水平
pit: Serotonin is not only about happiness; it affects many functions // 不仅关乎快乐，还影响多种功能
note: AP: often tested with antidepressants mechanism // 常与抗抑郁药机制一起考查

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.norepinephrine
def: A neurotransmitter that increases arousal, alertness, and triggers fight-or-flight response / 一种提高警觉、唤醒并触发“战斗或逃跑”反应的神经递质
ex: During a sudden loud noise, Norepinephrine surges to prepare for action / 突然听到巨响时，去甲肾上腺素激增以准备行动
pit: Do not confuse with epinephrine (adrenaline) — norepinephrine is a neurotransmitter, while adrenaline is a hormone in the bloodstream / 勿与肾上腺素混淆——去甲肾上腺素是神经递质，而肾上腺素是血液中的激素
note: AP often tests Norepinephrine as the "alertness" neurotransmitter / AP考试常测试去甲肾上腺素作为“警觉”神经递质

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.glutamate
def: The major excitatory neurotransmitter; involved in learning and memory / 主要的兴奋性神经递质，参与学习和记忆过程
ex: Excessive glutamate release after a stroke can overstimulate neurons and cause damage / 中风后过量的谷氨酸释放会过度刺激神经元导致损伤
pit: Confuse with GABA — remember glutamate excites, GABA inhibits / 易与GABA混淆——记住谷氨酸兴奋，GABA抑制
note: AP may ask which neurotransmitter is excitatory, leading to glutamate / AP可能问哪种神经递质是兴奋性的，答案是谷氨酸

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.gaba
def: The major inhibitory neurotransmitter; reduces neural activity and calms the brain / 主要的抑制性神经递质，降低神经活动，使大脑平静
ex: Anti-anxiety drugs like Valium work by enhancing GABA's effects / 如安定等抗焦虑药物通过增强GABA的作用起效
pit: Think of GABA as the brain's "brake" — its deficiency is linked to anxiety / 将GABA想象为大脑的“刹车”——其缺乏与焦虑相关
note: AP often contrasts GABA (inhibitory) with glutamate (excitatory) / AP常对比GABA（抑制）与谷氨酸（兴奋）

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.endorphins
def: Natural painkillers produced by the body; also produce feelings of pleasure / 身体产生的天然止痛剂，同时产生愉悦感
ex: Endorphins cause "runner's high" after prolonged exercise / 内啡肽在长时间运动后引起“跑者高潮”
pit: Do not confuse with exogenous opioids like morphine — endorphins are endogenous / 勿与外源性阿片类药物（如吗啡）混淆——内啡肽是内源性
note: AP may link endorphins to pain reduction and reward pathways / AP可能将内啡肽与减痛及奖赏通路联系起来

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.substance-p
def: A neurotransmitter involved in transmitting pain signals to the brain / 一种参与将疼痛信号传递到大脑的神经递质
ex: Substance P levels increase when you touch a hot stove, intensifying pain perception / 触摸热炉时P物质水平升高，增强痛觉感知
pit: Substance P amplifies pain — opposite effect of endorphins / P物质放大疼痛——作用与内啡肽相反
note: AP may test Substance P in pain pathways as the "pain" neurotransmitter / AP可能在疼痛通路中测试P物质作为“痛觉”神经递质

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.acetylcholine
def: A neurotransmitter that enables muscle contraction, memory, and arousal / 一种促进肌肉收缩、记忆和唤醒的神经递质
ex: Botox blocks acetylcholine release, causing temporary muscle paralysis / 肉毒杆菌素阻断乙酰胆碱释放，导致暂时性肌肉麻痹
pit: Alzheimer's disease is associated with acetylcholine deficiency — not dopamine / 阿尔茨海默病与乙酰胆碱缺乏有关——而非多巴胺
note: AP often tests acetylcholine for both motor (PNS) and memory (CNS) roles / AP常测试乙酰胆碱在运动（外周）和记忆（中枢）中的双重作用

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.hormones
def: Chemical messengers secreted by endocrine glands into the bloodstream; act slower but longer than neurotransmitters / 由内分泌腺分泌到血液中的化学信使；比神经递质作用慢但持久
ex: Cortisol, a stress hormone, is released from the adrenal cortex / 皮质醇是一种压力激素，由肾上腺皮质释放
pit: Compare with neurotransmitters — hormones travel via blood, neurotransmitters cross synapses / 与神经递质比较——激素通过血液运输，神经递质穿越突触
note: AP often asks to distinguish endocrine system (hormones) from nervous system (neurotransmitters) / AP常要求区分内分泌系统（激素）与神经系统（神经递质）

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.adrenaline
def: A hormone (also called epinephrine) released by the adrenal medulla; triggers fight-or-flight response / 由肾上腺髓质释放的激素（也称肾上腺素）；触发“战斗或逃跑”反应
ex: Adrenaline increases heart rate and blood sugar when you are frightened / 害怕时肾上腺素提高心率和血糖
pit: Note that adrenaline acts as a hormone in the blood, but can also function as a neurotransmitter in some contexts / 注意肾上腺素在血液中是激素，但在某些情境下也可作为神经递质
note: AP often tests adrenaline as the classic stress hormone / AP常测试肾上腺素作为经典压力激素

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.leptin
def: A hormone secreted by fat cells that signals the brain to reduce appetite / 由脂肪细胞分泌的激素，向大脑发出减少食欲的信号
ex: High leptin levels indicate fullness; leptin resistance can lead to obesity / 瘦素水平高表示饱足；瘦素抵抗可导致肥胖
pit: Do not confuse with ghrelin — leptin signals satiety, ghrelin signals hunger / 勿与饥饿素混淆——瘦素提示饱足，饥饿素提示饥饿
note: AP links leptin to biological bases of eating behavior and obesity / AP将瘦素与进食行为和肥胖的生物学基础联系起来

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.ghrelin
def: A hormone released by the stomach that stimulates hunger / 由胃释放的激素，刺激饥饿感
ex: Ghrelin levels rise before meals and drop after eating / 饥饿素水平在餐前升高，餐后下降
pit: Remember: "ghrelin" sounds like "gremlin" — a gremlin makes you hungry / 记忆技巧：“ghrelin”发音像“gremlin”（小精灵）——小精灵让你感到饿
note: AP often pairs ghrelin and leptin as opposing hunger-regulating hormones / AP常将饥饿素与瘦素作为调节饥饿的对抗激素

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.melatonin
def: A hormone that regulates sleep-wake cycles / 调节睡眠-觉醒周期的激素
ex: Pineal gland releases melatonin at night to promote sleep / 松果体在夜间释放褪黑素促进入睡
pit: Confused with serotonin – melatonin is derived from serotonin but function different / 易与血清素混淆，褪黑素由血清素转化但功能不同
note: Often tested as part of circadian rhythms / 常作为昼夜节律的一部分考查

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.oxytocin
def: Hormone and neurotransmitter involved in social bonding, trust, and childbirth / 参与社交联结、信任和分娩的激素与神经递质
ex: Released during hugging or breastfeeding to strengthen parent-child bond / 拥抱或哺乳时释放，增强亲子纽带
pit: Called “love hormone” but effects vary by context (e.g., can increase in-group bias) / 被称为“爱情激素”，但效果因情境而异（如可能增强内群体偏见）
note: May be linked to prosocial behavior in FRQs / 自由回答题可能联系到亲社会行为

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.psychoactive-drugs
def: Chemicals that alter brain function, perception, mood, or behavior / 改变大脑功能、感知、情绪或行为的化学物质
ex: Alcohol, caffeine, LSD, cocaine / 酒精、咖啡因、LSD、可卡因
pit: Not all psychoactive drugs are illegal – e.g., caffeine and alcohol are legal / 并非所有精神活性药物都非法，如咖啡因和酒精合法
note: Classified by effect: stimulants, depressants, hallucinogens / 按效果分类：兴奋剂、抑制剂、致幻剂

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.agonists
def: Drugs that mimic or enhance the effect of a neurotransmitter / 模拟或增强神经递质效果的药物
ex: Morphine acts as an agonist for endorphins, reducing pain / 吗啡是内啡肽的激动剂，减轻疼痛
pit: Confused with antagonists – agonists increase effect, antagonists block / 与拮抗剂混淆：激动剂增强效果，拮抗剂阻断
note: Common FRQ: identify drug as agonist or antagonist / 常见自由回答题：判断药物是激动剂还是拮抗剂

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.antagonists
def: Drugs that block or reduce the effect of a neurotransmitter / 阻断或减少神经递质效果的药物
ex: Naloxone blocks opioid receptors to reverse overdose / 纳洛酮阻断阿片受体以逆转过量
pit: Think “anti” = against; opposite of agonist / 用“anti”记忆意为对抗，与激动剂相反
note: Often paired with agonists in test items / 测试中常与激动剂成对出现

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.reuptake-inhibitors
def: Drugs that block reuptake, increasing neurotransmitter level in synapse / 阻断再摄取，增加突触中神经递质水平的药物
ex: SSRIs (e.g., Prozac) block serotonin reuptake to treat depression / 选择性5-羟色胺再摄取抑制剂（如百忧解）阻断血清素再摄取治疗抑郁
pit: They do NOT increase release, just keep more in synapse / 并非增加释放，只是让突触中停留更多递质
note: Key for understanding antidepressant mechanism / 理解抗抑郁药机制的关键

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.stimulants
def: Drugs that increase neural activity and bodily functions / 增加神经活动和身体功能的药物
ex: Caffeine, cocaine, amphetamines / 咖啡因、可卡因、安非他命
pit: They can be both legal (caffeine) and illegal (cocaine) / 既有合法（咖啡因）也有非法（可卡因）
note: Side effects include anxiety, insomnia, increased heart rate / 副作用包括焦虑、失眠、心率加快

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.caffeine
def: A stimulant that blocks adenosine receptors, reducing drowsiness / 阻断腺苷受体的兴奋剂，减少困倦感
ex: Coffee or tea helps you stay awake / 咖啡或茶有助于保持清醒
pit: Not a depressant – it stimulates CNS despite being widely used / 不是抑制剂——虽然广泛使用，但刺激中枢神经系统
note: Often used as an example of a psychoactive drug in everyday life / 常作为日常精神活性药物的例子

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.cocaine
def: A powerful stimulant that blocks reuptake of dopamine, causing euphoria / 强效兴奋剂，阻断多巴胺再摄取，产生欣快感
ex: Snorting cocaine produces a short, intense high / 吸食可卡因产生短暂强烈的快感
pit: It is an indirect agonist (increases dopamine by blocking reuptake) / 是间接激动剂（通过阻断再摄取增加多巴胺）
note: High addiction potential – often in FRQs about reward pathway / 高度成瘾性，常出现在奖励通路相关自由回答题

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.depressants
def: Drugs that reduce neural activity and slow bodily functions / 减少神经活动、减缓身体功能的药物
ex: Alcohol, benzodiazepines (Xanax), barbiturates / 酒精、苯二氮䓬类（赞安诺）、巴比妥类
pit: “Depress” here means reduce CNS activity, not necessarily cause depression / 此处的“抑制”指降低中枢神经系统活动，不一定会导致抑郁
note: Can cause slowed breathing, impaired motor coordination, and sedation / 可导致呼吸减慢、运动协调受损和镇静

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.alcohol
def: A depressant that slows neural activity and impairs judgment / 抑制剂，减慢神经活动，损害判断
ex: Slurred speech after drinking
pit: Assume it’s a stimulant because it lowers inhibition
note: AP cue – know it’s a GABA agonist

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.hallucinogens
def: Drugs that distort perceptions and evoke sensory images without external input / 致幻剂，扭曲感知，产生无外部输入的感官体验
ex: LSD causing visual trails
pit: Confuse with stimulants; hallucinogens do not consistently increase energy
note: AP cue – effect on serotonin receptors (e.g., LSD)

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.marijuana
def: A mild hallucinogen that amplifies sensations and impairs memory; active ingredient THC / 轻度致幻剂，放大感觉并损害记忆；活性成分为THC
ex: Feeling time slows down after smoking
pit: Think it works only as a depressant; it’s actually hallucinogenic
note: AP cue – disrupts short-term memory via cannabinoid receptors

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.opioids
def: Depressant drugs that reduce pain and produce euphoria, including heroin and morphine / 抑制剂，减痛并产生欣快感，包括海洛因和吗啡
ex: Morphine used for post-surgery pain
pit: Not all opioids are illegal; many are prescribed
note: AP cue – act on endorphin receptors; high addiction risk

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.heroin
def: An opioid that powerfully reduces pain and produces intense euphoria; highly addictive / 阿片类药物，强力减痛并产生强烈欣快感；高度成瘾
ex: Injection leads to a rush followed by drowsiness
pit: Mistake it for a stimulant because of initial rush
note: AP cue – classic example of addiction and withdrawal

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.tolerance
def: Need for larger doses to achieve same effect, due to neuroadaptation / 需要更大剂量才能达到相同效果，因神经适应
ex: Regular coffee drinker needs more cups to feel alert
pit: Confuse tolerance with addiction; tolerance can occur without addiction
note: AP cue – linked to receptor down-regulation

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.addiction
def: Compulsive drug craving and use despite negative consequences / 强迫性渴望和使用药物，不顾负面后果
ex: Continuing to smoke cigarettes despite lung problems
pit: Assume it’s purely physical; includes psychological dependence
note: AP cue – dopamine reward pathway involvement

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-3.withdrawal
def: Discomfort and distress after stopping a drug, opposite of drug’s effects / 停药后的不适和痛苦，与药效相反
ex: Shaking after quitting alcohol
pit: Think withdrawal only happens with illegal drugs; occurs with caffeine, nicotine too
note: AP cue – body’s attempt to regain homeostasis

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.brain-stem
def: Oldest and innermost region; controls basic survival functions like breathing and heartbeat / 最古老、最内层区域；控制呼吸、心跳等基本生存功能
ex: Damage leads to coma or death
pit: Confuse with cerebellum; brainstem is lower, more automatic
note: AP cue – where spinal cord enters skull; includes medulla, pons, reticular formation

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.medulla
def: Part of brainstem controlling heartbeat and breathing / 脑干的一部分，控制心跳和呼吸
ex: Swallowing reflex also regulated here
pit: Think it handles all automatic functions; actually focuses on vital life support
note: AP cue – located at base of brainstem; damage = fatal

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.reticular-activating-system-ras
def: Network of neurons that filters incoming sensory info and regulates arousal / 网状激活系统：过滤感觉信息并调节唤醒水平的神经元网络
ex: Helps you wake up when alarm rings; filters out background noise when focusing
pit: Not the same as the reticular formation—RAS includes only arousal-related parts
note: Key for sleep-wake cycles and attention; often tested with coma/consciousness

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.reward-center
def: Brain regions (mainly nucleus accumbens, VTA) that reinforce pleasurable behaviors via dopamine / 奖赏中枢：通过多巴胺强化愉悦行为的脑区（主要为伏隔核、腹侧被盖区）
ex: Feeling pleasure from eating chocolate activates reward center
pit: Not just for pleasure—also drives motivation and learning
note: Link to addiction (drugs hijack this system) & operant conditioning

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.cerebellum
def: Hindbrain structure controlling balance, coordination, and fine motor skills / 小脑：控制平衡、协调和精细运动的脑结构
ex: Helps you walk a straight line or catch a ball
pit: Does NOT initiate movement—it coordinates and refines
note: Also involved in some cognitive functions (e.g., timing, classical conditioning of eyeblink)

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.cerebral-cortex
def: Outer layer of forebrain; site of higher-order thinking, language, sensation, and voluntary movement / 大脑皮层：前脑外层；负责高级思维、语言、感觉和随意运动
ex: Solving a math problem uses cerebral cortex
pit: Not a single lobe—has frontal, parietal, temporal, occipital
note: Most tested in AP: localization of functions (e.g., motor cortex, sensory cortex, association areas)

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.limbic-system
def: Neural system (including amygdala, hippocampus, hypothalamus) for emotion, memory, and motivation / 边缘系统：包括杏仁核、海马、下丘脑，处理情绪、记忆和动机
ex: Feeling fear when seeing a snake involves limbic system
pit: Not a strictly defined anatomical structure—more a functional concept
note: Often paired with “emotional brain”; key for aggression, fear, memory consolidation

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.thalamus
def: Sensory relay station; directs sensory info (except smell) to appropriate cortex areas / 丘脑：感觉中继站，将感觉信息（除嗅觉）传递至相应皮层
ex: Visual signals go through thalamus to occipital lobe
pit: Processes all senses EXCEPT smell (olfaction bypasses thalamus)
note: Often called “the switchboard”; tested with sensory pathways

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.hypothalamus
def: Brain region regulating homeostasis: hunger, thirst, body temperature, and drives / 下丘脑：调节稳态：饥饿、渴、体温及本能驱力
ex: When you're cold, hypothalamus triggers shivering
pit: Controls the pituitary gland but is NOT the pituitary itself
note: Also involved in emotion/aggression; “four F’s”: fighting, feeding, fleeing, mating

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.pituitary-gland
def: “Master gland” of endocrine system; releases hormones that control other glands / 垂体：内分泌系统“主腺”；释放激素调控其他腺体
ex: Growth hormone released by pituitary affects body growth
pit: Controlled by hypothalamus (not independent); not part of brain but attached
note: Link between nervous & endocrine systems; tested with stress response (ACTH) or growth

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.hippocampus
def: Limbic structure critical for forming new explicit (declarative) memories / 海马：边缘系统结构，对新外显（陈述性）记忆形成至关重要
ex: You need hippocampus to remember facts for AP exam
pit: Not the permanent storage location – consolidates memories to cortex; old memories survive if hippocampus is damaged
note: Distinguished from amygdala (emotional memory); key for amnesia cases (e.g., H.M.)

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.amygdala
def: Almond-shaped limbic structure processing fear, aggression, and emotional memories / 杏仁核：杏仁状边缘结构，处理恐惧、攻击及情绪记忆
ex: Feeling fear when seeing a spider activates amygdala
pit: Does NOT store all memories – only emotional significance of memories
note: Often paired with “fight-or-flight” response; tested with fear conditioning & aggression

@@ corpus-callosum
def: Neural bridge connecting left & right hemispheres / 连接左右半球的神经桥
ex: Split-brain patients can’t name objects in left visual field (word in left hand, can’t say it)
pit: Not a lobe; it’s white matter fiber bundle
note: Key for split‑brain experiments (Sperry)

@@ occipital-lobes
def: Primary visual processing area at back of brain / 枕叶：视觉处理核心区
ex: Damage here causes blindness in part of visual field
pit: Visual perception ≠ occipital alone (needs temporal/parietal for “what” & “where”)
note: Often tested with visual agnosia or cortical blindness

@@ temporal-lobes
def: Auditory processing, language comprehension (Wernicke’s area), and memory / 颞叶：听觉、语言理解（韦尼克区）、记忆
ex: Wernicke’s aphasia → fluent but meaningless speech
pit: Hearing is temporal, but sound localization involves parietal
note: Wernicke’s area on left; also houses hippocampus (memory)

@@ parietal-lobes
def: Somatosensory & spatial perception (touch, temperature, body position) / 顶叶：躯体感觉与空间感知
ex: Damage can cause neglect syndrome (ignore left side of body)
pit: Sensory strip is parietal, but motor strip is frontal
note: Contains somatosensory cortex; associated with math & spatial reasoning

@@ association-areas
def: Integrate sensory, motor, and cognitive info for complex thought / 联合区：整合多模态信息进行高级思维
ex: Your frontal association area helps you plan a route using maps
pit: Not a single lobe—spread across frontal/parietal/temporal/occipital
note: AP asks: “What part of brain allows higher‑order thinking?” → association areas

@@ somatosensory-cortex
def: Strip in parietal lobe processing touch, pressure, pain, temperature, body position / 躯体感觉皮层（顶叶）处理触、压、痛、温、本体感
ex: Homunculus map shows more area for sensitive parts (fingertips, lips)
pit: Don’t confuse with motor cortex (frontal lobe)
note: Located in postcentral gyrus; test with sensory homunculus

@@ frontal-lobes
def: Motor control, reasoning, planning, personality, language production (Broca’s area) / 额叶：运动、推理、计划、人格、语言产生（布罗卡区）
ex: Phineas Gage → frontal damage caused personality change
pit: Not just “thinking”—also voluntary movement & inhibition
note: Broca’s area (left frontal) = speech production; executive functions here

@@ linguistic-processing
def: Brain’s handling of language (word recognition, comprehension, production) / 语言处理：大脑对语言的识别、理解与生成
ex: Reading a sentence activates left temporal (meaning) & frontal (grammar)
pit: Language is mostly left hemisphere, but also right for prosody/emotion
note: AP might ask “Which areas are involved in language?” → Broca, Wernicke, angular gyrus

@@ higher-order-thinking
def: Complex cognitive processes (problem‑solving, analysis, creativity) / 高级思维：复杂认知过程（解决问题、分析、创造）
ex: Designing a science experiment uses frontal association areas
pit: Not a specific brain region—relies on prefrontal cortex & association areas
note: Often contrasted with automatic/reflexive processing; AP tests with executive function

@@ executive-functioning
def: Cognitive control skills (goal‑setting, impulse control, working memory, flexibility) / 执行功能：认知控制能力（目标设定、冲动抑制、工作记忆、灵活切换）
ex: Planning a week’s schedule & sticking to it
pit: Is not memory per se; involves prefrontal cortex
note: Damage to prefrontal cortex → lack of inhibition, poor judgment (e.g., Phineas Gage)

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.prefrontal-cortex
def: Brain region responsible for executive functions, planning, decision-making, and personality. / 负责执行功能、规划、决策和人格的大脑区域。
ex: Phineas Gage’s injury led to personality changes. / 菲尼亚斯·盖奇的损伤导致性格改变。
pit: Not the same as frontal lobe; it’s the frontmost part. / 不同于整个额叶，仅为最前部。
note: AP FRQ often links to judgment and impulse control. / AP自由回答常联系判断与冲动控制。

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.motor-cortex
def: Rear of frontal lobe that controls voluntary movement; contralateral. / 额叶后部控制随意运动；对侧控制。
ex: Right motor cortex controls left body movement. / 右侧运动皮层控制左侧身体运动。
pit: Confusing with somatosensory cortex (sensory homunculus). / 易与体感皮层混淆（感觉侏儒图）。
note: Know homunculus map for fine motor areas. / 掌握精细运动区域的侏儒图。

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.split-brain-research
def: Study of patients with severed corpus callosum to examine hemispheric functions. / 研究胼胝体切断患者以探究半球功能。
ex: Patient cannot verbally name object seen in left visual field. / 患者无法说出左视野看到的物体名称。
pit: Assume each hemisphere works in isolation; they still communicate via subcortical pathways. / 误以为半球完全独立；仍经皮层下通路交流。
note: Classic Sperry and Gazzaniga studies appear on multiple-choice. / 经典Sperry与Gazzaniga研究常出现于选择题。

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.hemispheric-specialization
def: Tendency for each brain hemisphere to excel at certain functions (left: language; right: spatial). / 各半球擅长特定功能（左：语言；右：空间）。
ex: Left hemisphere controls speech; right hemisphere processes facial recognition. / 左半球控制言语；右半球处理面部识别。
pit: Oversimplifying as “left brain/right brain” personality types. / 过度简化为“左脑/右脑”人格类型。
note: AP emphasizes that both hemispheres cooperate. / AP强调两半球协同工作。

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.broca-s-area
def: Left frontal lobe region involved in speech production. / 左额叶中参与言语产生的区域。
ex: Damage causes non-fluent aphasia – can understand but not form words. / 损伤导致不流畅失语症——能理解但无法组织词语。
pit: Confusing with Wernicke’s area; Broca’s is production, not comprehension. / 与韦尼克区混淆；布罗卡区负责产生，非理解。
note: Located in left hemisphere for most people. / 多数人位于左半球。

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.wernicke-s-area
def: Left temporal lobe region involved in language comprehension. / 左颞叶中参与语言理解的区域。
ex: Damage causes fluent aphasia – speaks nonsense but with normal rhythm. / 损伤导致流畅失语症——说话无意义但节奏正常。
pit: Think it’s only for hearing language; also involved in reading comprehension. / 误以为仅处理听觉语言；也参与阅读理解。
note: Pair with Broca’s area for aphasia questions. / 与布罗卡区配对用于失语症题目。

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.aphasia-broca-s-and-wernicke-s
def: Language impairment due to brain damage; Broca’s (non-fluent) vs Wernicke’s (fluent). / 脑损伤导致的语言障碍；布罗卡型（不流畅）对韦尼克型（流畅）。
ex: Broca’s: “want… food”; Wernicke’s: “The happy cloudy ate the car.” / 布罗卡型：“想…食物”；韦尼克型：“快乐的多云吃了汽车。”
pit: Assuming comprehension is always intact in Broca’s; subtle comprehension deficits may exist. / 以为布罗卡型理解完全完好；可能存在轻微理解缺陷。
note: AP may ask to identify type from symptoms. / AP可能要求根据症状识别类型。

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.contralateral-hemispheric-organization
def: Each hemisphere controls the opposite side of the body. / 每侧半球控制身体对侧。
ex: Left brain moves right hand; right brain senses touch on left arm. / 左脑控制右手；右脑感受左臂触觉。
pit: Forgetting that sensory and motor pathways both cross. / 忘记感觉和运动通路均交叉。
note: Key for understanding split-brain findings. / 理解裂脑研究的关键。

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.plasticity
def: Brain’s ability to reorganize and form new neural connections after damage or experience. / 脑在损伤或经验后重组并形成新神经连接的能力。
ex: Blind person’s visual cortex may process touch or sound. / 盲人的视觉皮层可能处理触觉或声音。
pit: Thinking plasticity only occurs in children; adults also show plasticity. / 认为可塑性仅存在于儿童；成人也有可塑性。
note: AP FRQ often uses examples from stroke recovery. / AP自由回答常以中风康复为例。

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.eeg
def: Electroencephalogram – records electrical activity of the brain via scalp electrodes. / 脑电图——通过头皮电极记录脑电活动。
ex: Used to detect sleep stages or seizure activity. / 用于检测睡眠阶段或癫痫活动。
pit: Confusing with MRI/fMRI; EEG measures electrical activity, not blood flow. / 与MRI/fMRI混淆；EEG测量电活动，非血流。
note: AP asks about its high temporal resolution but low spatial resolution. / AP考查其高时间分辨率但低空间分辨率。

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.fmri
def: Functional magnetic resonance imaging; measures brain activity by detecting blood flow changes / 功能性磁共振成像；通过检测血流变化测量脑活动
ex: fMRI reveals which brain regions activate during a memory task / fMRI显示记忆任务中激活的脑区
pit: fMRI shows correlation, not causation; don't confuse with structural MRI / fMRI显示相关性，非因果；勿与结构性MRI混淆
note: AP asks: fMRI = "where" activity happens; EEG = "when" / AP考点：fMRI=活动“位置”，EEG=活动“时间”

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-4.lesioning
def: Deliberately damaging brain tissue to study its function / 故意损毁脑组织以研究其功能
ex: Lesioning the hypothalamus in rats reduces eating / 损毁大鼠下丘脑减少进食
pit: Lesioning is done in animals, not humans for ethical reasons / 损毁用于动物，非人类（伦理）
note: AP: natural lesions (stroke) also studied; lesioning helps identify necessary brain regions / AP：自然病变（中风）也可研究；损毁帮助识别必要脑区

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.consciousness
def: Our subjective awareness of ourselves and our environment / 对自我和环境的觉知
ex: Being aware of your thoughts while solving a math problem / 解题时意识到自己的思考
pit: Consciousness is not just wakefulness; can be conscious during dreaming / 意识≠清醒；做梦时也有意识
note: AP: consciousness changes with sleep, hypnosis, drugs / AP考点：意识随睡眠、催眠、药物改变

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.circadian-rhythm-sleep-wake-cycle
def: Internal biological clock regulating sleep-wake cycle over about 24 hours / 约24小时的生理节律调节睡眠-觉醒周期
ex: Feeling sleepy at night and alert in morning / 晚上困倦，早晨清醒
pit: Circadian rhythm can be reset by light; not exactly 24h for everyone / 周期可被光重置；并非每人精确24小时
note: AP: suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) in hypothalamus controls it / AP：下丘脑视交叉上核控制

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.jet-lag
def: Mismatch between internal circadian rhythm and external time due to rapid travel across time zones / 因跨时区旅行导致内在节律与外部时间不匹配
ex: Flying from NYC to London causes difficulty sleeping at local night / 纽约飞伦敦导致当地夜晚难入睡
pit: Jet lag is worse traveling east (losing time) than west / 向东（时间减少）比向西更严重
note: AP: light exposure helps adjust circadian rhythm / AP考点：光照帮助调整节律

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.shift-work
def: Working during times when body expects sleep, disrupting circadian rhythm / 在身体预期睡眠时工作，扰乱昼夜节律
ex: Nurses working 12-hour night shifts / 护士上12小时夜班
pit: Shift work increases risk of health problems (e.g., accidents, depression) / 夜班增加健康风险（如事故、抑郁）
note: AP: rotating shifts harder than fixed night shifts / AP：轮班比固定夜班更难适应

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.nrem-stage-1
def: Light sleep; theta waves; easily awakened; hypnagogic sensations / 浅睡；θ波；易唤醒；入睡幻觉
ex: Drifting off while watching TV, then jerking awake / 看电视时打盹，然后突然惊醒
pit: Stage 1 is not deep sleep; lasts only a few minutes / 阶段1非深睡，仅持续几分钟
note: AP: first stage after falling asleep / AP考点：入睡后第一时相

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.hypnagogic-sensations
def: Vivid sensory experiences (floating, falling, or hearing voices) just before sleep / 入睡前生动的感觉（漂浮、下落或听到声音）
ex: Feeling like you are falling and then jerking awake / 感觉下落然后惊醒
pit: Not dreams; occur in NREM stage 1 / 非梦境；出现于NREM阶段1
note: AP: associated with myoclonic jerks / AP考点：与肌阵挛抽搐相关

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.nrem-stage-2
def: Deeper sleep; sleep spindles and K-complexes on EEG; less responsive / 更深睡眠；EEG出现睡眠纺锤波和K复合波；较难唤醒
ex: Sleeping through moderate noises like a door closing / 对关门声等中等噪声无反应
pit: Stage 2 takes up ~50% of total sleep / 阶段2约占睡眠总时间的50%
note: AP: sleep spindles help memory consolidation / AP考点：睡眠纺锤波帮助记忆巩固

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.nrem-stage-3
def: Deep sleep; delta waves; difficult to awaken; sleepwalking/talking occur / 深睡眠；δ波；难唤醒；梦游/梦话发生
ex: Not waking up even to loud alarm / 闹钟大声也不醒
pit: Stage 3 is also called slow-wave sleep; alcohol suppresses it / 阶段3也称慢波睡眠；酒精抑制此阶段
note: AP: restorative sleep; growth hormone released / AP考点：恢复性睡眠；释放生长激素

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.rem-sleep
def: A sleep stage with rapid eye movements, high brain activity, and vivid dreams / 快速眼动睡眠阶段，脑活动高，梦境生动
ex: Most dreams occur during REM sleep
pit: Confusing REM with deep sleep; REM is light sleep
note: Ask "REM cycles every 90 min; increases as night goes on"

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.rem-rebound
def: Increased REM sleep after deprivation; body tries to catch up / 缺乏REM后出现的补偿性增多
ex: Pulling an all‑nighter leads to extra REM next sleep
pit: Think only total sleep matters; REM rebound shows specific need
note: Frq: “Explain REM rebound after sleep deprivation”

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.activation-synthesis-dreams
def: Dreams result from brain’s attempt to make sense of random neural signals / 大脑随机信号被解释成故事
ex: Being in a dream feels real because cortex synthesizes signals
pit: Believing dreams have hidden meanings; activation‑synthesis says no
note: Opposite of Freud’s wish‑fulfillment; known as “random activation”

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.consolidation-theory-dreams
def: Dreams help process and store memories from the day / 梦帮助巩固白天记忆
ex: Studying before sleep improves recall due to consolidation during REM
pit: Confusing with activation‑synthesis; consolidation focuses on memory
note: Tie to “memory consolidation” in learning unit

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.restoration-of-resources
def: Sleep restores body and brain, replenishes energy / 睡眠恢复身体和脑力，补充能量
ex: After exercise, deep sleep increases for physical repair
pit: Thinking only REM matters; restoration primarily involves NREM deep sleep
note: Often paired with “repair” hypothesis

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.insomnia
def: Difficulty falling or staying asleep / 难以入睡或保持睡眠
ex: Worry about exams keeps a student awake for hours
pit: Believing insomnia is always psychological; can be medical
note: Most common sleep disorder; linked to anxiety/depression

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.narcolepsy
def: Sudden daytime sleep attacks, often with cataplexy / 突然白天嗜睡，常伴肌肉无力
ex: A person collapses laughing after a joke due to cataplexy
pit: Mixing with sleep apnea; narcolepsy is brain’s failure to regulate sleep‑wake
note: Entering REM directly from awake; classic AP example

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.rem-sleep-behavior-disorder
def: Acting out dreams physically during REM (muscles not paralyzed) / REM期肌肉未麻痹，梦游或动手动脚
ex: A person punches while dreaming of fighting
pit: Confusing with sleepwalking (somnambulism, NREM); RSBD is REM
note: Associated with Parkinson’s disease risk

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.sleep-apnea
def: Breathing repeatedly stops during sleep, causing snoring/gasping / 睡眠中呼吸反复暂停，打鼾、憋气
ex: Obese person has loud snoring and wakes up tired
pit: Thinking it’s just snoring; key is oxygen drop
note: Linked to hypertension, memory problems

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-5.somnambulism
def: Sleepwalking; occurs in NREM deep sleep / 梦游，发生在NREM深睡期
ex: A child walks downstairs without waking up
pit: Believing somnambulists are acting out dreams (they are not)
note: Common in children; no memory of episode

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.sensation
def: Detection of physical energy by sense organs / 感觉：感官对物理能量的检测
ex: Feeling cold air on your skin
pit: Not same as perception (interpreting sensation)
note: Bottom-up processing starts here

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.transduction
def: Conversion of stimulus energy into neural signals / 换能：刺激能量转为神经信号
ex: Light waves become electrical signals in retina
pit: Often confused with transmission; transduction is the conversion step
note: Key for all senses; AP asks "what process converts light to neural signals?"

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.absolute-threshold
def: Minimum stimulus energy needed to detect a stimulus 50% of the time / 绝对阈限：50%概率检测到的最小刺激
ex: Hearing a watch ticking from 20 feet away in quiet room
pit: Not "zero" detection; it's probabilistic (50%)
note: Often tested with signal detection theory context

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.just-noticeable-difference
def: Minimum difference between two stimuli required for detection 50% of the time / 最小可觉差：50%概率察觉的最小差异
ex: Adding one candle to 100 candles vs. adding one candle to 1 candle (different JND)
pit: JND is proportional to original stimulus (Weber's law), not constant
note: Also called difference threshold

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.sensory-adaptation
def: Diminished sensitivity due to constant stimulation / 感觉适应：持续刺激导致敏感度下降
ex: Entering a pool – water feels cold at first, then becomes neutral
pit: Not habituation (habituation is cognitive); adaptation is physiological
note: Helps focus on change, not constant input

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.weber-s-law
def: For a difference to be noticeable, it must be a constant proportion of the original stimulus / 韦伯定律：最小可觉差与原始刺激的比例恒定
ex: Adding 1 lb to 50 lb is noticeable; adding 1 lb to 100 lb is not – need 2 lb
pit: Proportion differs by sense (e.g., taste ~20%, vision ~8%)
note: Often paired with JND; memorize formula: ΔI/I = k

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.sensory-interaction
def: One sense can influence another sense / 感觉交互：一种感觉影响另一种感觉
ex: Smell of food enhances taste (flavor)
pit: Not synesthesia; normal cross-modal influence
note: Example: visual cues affect perceived sound location (McGurk effect)

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.synesthesia
def: Condition where one sense triggers another sense simultaneously / 联觉：一种感觉自动触发另一种感觉
ex: Seeing colors when hearing music
pit: Not just imagination; genuine perceptual experience
note: Rare, often tested as "cross-sensory blending"

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.retina
def: Light-sensitive inner surface at back of eye; contains receptors (rods and cones) / 视网膜：眼后部感光内层，含视杆和视锥细胞
ex: Where light is transduced into neural signals
pit: Not the same as fovea (fovea is part of retina with only cones)
note: Retina is part of CNS; AP asks about layers (ganglion, bipolar, receptor cells)

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.blind-spot
def: Point where optic nerve leaves the eye; no receptor cells / 盲点：视神经离开眼球处，无感光细胞
ex: You can't see objects in your peripheral vision if they fall exactly on your blind spot (e.g., when covering one eye)
pit: Brain fills in blind spot, so you don't normally notice it
note: Use the test with a dot and cross to demonstrate; AP may ask why we don't see a gap

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.visual-nerve
def: Nerve that carries visual info from retina to brain / 将视觉信息从视网膜传至大脑的神经
ex: Signals from rods and cones travel via optic nerve / 视杆和视锥信号经视神经传递
pit: Confusing with optic chiasm; nerve is before chiasm / 易混淆视交叉；视神经在交叉前
note: AP cue: part of transduction pathway / AP提示：是转换通路的一部分

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.lens
def: Transparent structure that focuses light onto retina / 聚焦光线到视网膜的透明结构
ex: Lens changes shape to focus on near/far objects / 晶状体改变形状以聚焦远近物体
pit: Think it is the cornea; cornea does initial bending / 误认为是角膜；角膜负责初次折射
note: AP cue: related to accommodation / AP提示：与调节作用相关

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.accommodation
def: Process where lens changes shape to focus on objects at different distances / 晶状体改变形状以聚焦不同距离物体的过程
ex: Lens bulges to read a book, flattens to see a distant mountain / 看书时晶状体变凸，看远山时变扁
pit: Confusing with pupil dilation; accommodation is lens shape change / 混淆瞳孔缩放；调节指晶状体形状变化
note: AP cue: common on visual perception questions / AP提示：视觉感知题常见

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.nearsightedness
def: Difficulty seeing distant objects; light focuses in front of retina / 看不清远处物体；光线聚焦在视网膜前方
ex: Can read a book clearly but not a blackboard / 能看清书本但看不清黑板
pit: Think it’s opposite; nearsighted = can see near / 易记反；近视=能看清近处
note: AP cue: corrected with concave lens / AP提示：用凹透镜矫正

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.farsightedness
def: Difficulty seeing close objects; light focuses behind retina / 看不清近处物体；光线聚焦在视网膜后方
ex: Can see road signs clearly but struggles with a smartphone screen / 能看清路标但看不清手机屏幕
pit: Confusing with presbyopia; farsightedness is usually genetic / 混淆老花眼；远视通常先天
note: AP cue: corrected with convex lens / AP提示：用凸透镜矫正

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.photoreceptors
def: Light-sensitive cells in retina that convert light into neural signals / 视网膜内将光转换为神经信号的感光细胞
ex: Rods and cones are the two types / 视杆细胞和视锥细胞是两种类型
pit: Thinking only cones exist in fovea; rods are in periphery / 以为中央凹只有视锥；视杆在周边
note: AP cue: foundation for transduction / AP提示：转换的基础

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.rods
def: Photoreceptors sensitive to low light; perceive black/white/gray / 对弱光敏感的黑白灰感知感光细胞
ex: Enable vision in dimly lit room / 能在昏暗房间中视物
pit: Thinking rods detect color; they do not / 误认为视杆能感知颜色；不能
note: AP cue: responsible for peripheral vision / AP提示：负责周边视觉

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.cones-blue-green-red
def: Photoreceptors that detect fine detail and color (three types: blue, green, red) / 检测细节和颜色的感光细胞（蓝、绿、红三种）
ex: Cones allow you to read a colorful menu / 视锥细胞让你看清彩色菜单
pit: Thinking there are more than three types; only three / 以为有更多类型；只有三种
note: AP cue: trichromatic theory built on cones / AP提示：三色理论基于视锥细胞

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.trichromatic-theory
def: Theory that color vision arises from three types of cones (blue, green, red) / 颜色视觉源于三种视锥细胞（蓝绿红）的理论
ex: Mixing green and red cones activation yields yellow perception / 绿和红视锥激活混合产生黄色感觉
pit: Confusing with opponent-process; trichromatic works at receptor level / 混淆对立过程理论；三色在感受器水平
note: AP cue: supported by color mixing & color blindness / AP提示：由颜色混合和色盲支持

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.opponent-process-theory
def: Theory that color vision is processed by opposing pairs (red-green, blue-yellow, black-white) / 颜色视觉由对立颜色对（红-绿、蓝-黄、黑-白）处理的理论
ex: Staring at red then looking at white paper sees green afterimage / 盯红色后看白纸出现绿色后像
pit: Thinking it replaces trichromatic; they work at different levels / 以为取代三色理论；两者在不同层级工作
note: AP cue: explains afterimages and contrast effects / AP提示：解释后像和对比效应

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.afterimages
def: Visual images that persist after stimulus is removed, often in complementary colors (opponent-process theory). / 后像：刺激移除后仍残留的视觉影像，常呈互补色（对立过程理论）。
ex: Staring at a green dot then seeing a red afterimage.
pit: Confusing afterimages with iconic memory (sensory memory lasts <1 sec; afterimages last longer due to neural fatigue).
note: AP tie-in to opponent-process theory (Herring) – afterimages often appear on FRQ about color vision.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.ganglion-cells
def: Neurons in the retina whose axons form the optic nerve; they receive input from bipolar cells and have center-surround receptive fields. / 视网膜神经节细胞：轴突构成视神经的神经元，接收双极细胞输入，具有中心－周边感受野。
ex: Ganglion cells detect edges and contrast, not individual photons.
pit: Students think ganglion cells are where rods/cones are; actually they are the third layer of retinal neurons.
note: AP key: ganglion cells are the only retinal cells with axons that leave the eye – that’s why blind spot exists.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.dichromatism
def: Color blindness where one cone type is missing; only two primary colors can be distinguished (usually red-green or blue-yellow). / 二色视觉：缺失一种视锥细胞的色盲，仅能区分两种原色（通常红绿或蓝黄色盲）。
ex: A person with red-green dichromatism sees red and green as similar shades.
pit: Confusing with monochromatism; dichromatism still has some color vision.
note: AP asks “which cone is missing?” – common for red-green (missing L or M cones).

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.monochromatism
def: Complete color blindness; only perceives brightness and shade, often due to missing two or all cone types (rod monochromats). / 全色盲：完全缺乏色彩视觉，仅感知明暗，常因缺失两类或全部视锥细胞（杆体全色盲）。
ex: Seeing the world in shades of gray like a black-and-white movie.
pit: Students think it’s the same as rod vision – close but note: rod monochromats have low acuity.
note: AP can test “what type of cell is malfunctioning?” – cones.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.prosopagnosia
def: Inability to recognize faces despite intact vision; caused by damage to fusiform face area in temporal lobe. / 面孔失认症：无法识别面部，尽管视觉正常；由颞叶梭状回面孔区受损引起。
ex: A patient sees a friend’s face but cannot tell who it is, uses voice or clothing to recognize.
pit: Not amnesia; it's a perceptual disorder, not memory loss for people.
note: AP link to “top-down processing” – prosopagnosia disrupts holistic face perception.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.blindsight
def: Ability to respond to visual stimuli without conscious awareness; occurs after damage to primary visual cortex (V1). / 盲视：无意识觉察下对视觉刺激做出反应的能力；见于初级视觉皮层（V1）损伤后。
ex: A blind person can accurately guess the direction of a moving light but says they see nothing.
pit: Not “seeing” – it’s unconscious processing via subcortical pathways (e.g., superior colliculus).
note: AP example of “dual processing” (conscious vs. unconscious visual paths).

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.wavelength
def: Distance between successive peaks of a light or sound wave; determines hue (color) for light. / 波长：光波或声波连续波峰间的距离；决定光的色相（颜色）。
ex: Long wavelength ~700 nm appears red; short wavelength ~400 nm appears violet.
pit: Confusing wavelength with amplitude – wavelength changes color, amplitude changes brightness/loudness.
note: AP must distinguish hue (wavelength), brightness (amplitude), saturation (purity).

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.pitch
def: Perception of how high or low a sound is; determined by frequency (wavelength) of sound wave. / 音高：声音高低的感觉；由声波频率（波长）决定。
ex: A flute produces high pitch (short wavelength), a tuba low pitch (long wavelength).
pit: Pitch is psychological, frequency is physical – exam uses “pitch” for the sensation.
note: AP may pair with place theory vs. frequency theory for pitch perception.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.amplitude
def: Height of a wave; determines intensity (brightness of light / loudness of sound). / 振幅：波的高度；决定强度（光的亮度/声音的响度）。
ex: A large amplitude light wave appears bright; small amplitude dim.
pit: Amplitude is not the same as wavelength – they are independent properties.
note: AP use: amplitude affects loudness (sound) and brightness (light), but not hue/pitch.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.loudness
def: Perception of sound intensity (volume); determined by amplitude of sound wave, measured in decibels. / 响度：声音强度（音量）的感知；由声波振幅决定，单位分贝。
ex: A whisper has low loudness (~20 dB), a jet engine high loudness (~130 dB).
pit: Loudness ≠ pitch; students mix amplitude (loudness) with frequency (pitch).
note: AP question: “What physical property corresponds to loudness?” – amplitude.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.pitch-perception
def: The process by which the auditory system interprets the frequency of sound waves as pitch / 听觉系统将声波频率解读为音高的过程
ex: A high-pitched whistle vs. a low-pitched bass drum
pit: Confusing pitch with loudness; pitch is frequency, not amplitude
note: AP often tests pitch perception as part of auditory processing

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.place-theory
def: Theory that different frequencies stimulate specific locations on the cochlea's basilar membrane, determining pitch / 不同频率在耳蜗基底膜特定位置产生最大刺激，从而决定音高的理论
ex: High-pitched sounds activate hair cells near the oval window; low-pitched sounds activate cells farther away
pit: Misapplying place theory to all pitches; it works best for high frequencies
note: AP emphasis: place theory for high frequencies, frequency theory for low

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.volley-theory
def: Theory that groups of auditory neurons fire in alternating volleys to encode frequencies too fast for a single neuron / 一组听觉神经元交替发放来编码单个神经元无法跟随的高频（通常为400-5000 Hz）
ex: Neurons take turns firing to track a 4000 Hz tone, each firing at a fraction of the rate
pit: Assuming volley theory replaces place theory; both are used for mid-range pitches
note: AP less common but tests understanding of neural coding limits

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.frequency-theory
def: Theory that pitch is determined by the rate at which auditory nerve fibers fire / 音高由听神经纤维的发放频率决定（适用于低频声音）
ex: A 100 Hz tone causes neurons to fire 100 times per second
pit: Frequency theory alone cannot account for high-frequency perception (neural limit ~1000 Hz)
note: AP tests frequency theory for low pitches, place theory for high

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.sound-localization
def: The ability to locate sound sources using interaural time and intensity differences / 通过双耳时间差和强度差定位声源的能力
ex: Hearing a car horn from the left side; sound reaches left ear slightly earlier and louder
pit: Confusing sound localization with echolocation; localization relies on two ears
note: AP examines role of brain (superior olive) in processing binaural cues

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.conduction-deafness
def: Hearing loss due to damage of the middle ear structures (eardrum, ossicles) preventing sound from reaching the cochlea / 中耳结构（鼓膜、听小骨）受损，声音无法传到耳蜗导致的听力损失
ex: A ruptured eardrum from an infection reduces sound transmission
pit: Mistaking conduction deafness for sensorineural; conduction can often be treated surgically
note: AP distinguishes conduction vs. sensorineural deafness

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.sensorineural-deafness
def: Hearing loss due to damage of the cochlea, hair cells, or auditory nerve / 耳蜗、毛细胞或听神经受损导致的听力损失
ex: Prolonged exposure to loud music destroys hair cells, causing permanent high-frequency hearing loss
pit: Assuming sensorineural deafness is always total; often partial and frequency-specific
note: AP emphasizes that sensorineural is more common and usually permanent

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.olfactory-system
def: The sensory system responsible for smell; odor molecules bind to receptors in the nasal cavity / 负责嗅觉的感觉系统；气味分子与鼻腔中的受体结合
ex: Smelling freshly baked bread; molecules trigger olfactory receptors
pit: Confusing olfactory with gustatory (taste); they are distinct but interact for flavor
note: AP tests that olfactory is the only sense not routed through the thalamus before cortex

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.thalamus
def: The brain's sensory relay station; processes and transmits most sensory information (except smell) to the cortex / 大脑感觉中继站；处理并传递除嗅觉外的大多数感觉信息到皮层
ex: Visual signals from retina pass through thalamus to occipital lobe
pit: Thinking thalamus processes all senses; olfaction bypasses it
note: AP: thalamus is key for routing sensory input; exception = smell

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.pheromones
def: Chemical signals released by an animal that affect behavior or physiology of others of the same species / 动物释放的化学信号，影响同种其他个体的行为或生理
ex: Moths release pheromones to attract mates from miles away
pit: Assuming humans respond strongly to pheromones; evidence is debated and subtle
note: AP: pheromones are not typically a human sensory system; mentioned in animal behavior context

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.gustation
def: The sense of taste / 味觉
ex: Tasting chocolate, lemon, or salt.
pit: Do not confuse with olfaction; both contribute to flavor but are distinct senses.
note: Often paired with smell on the exam; gate-control theory is for pain, not taste.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.sweet-sour-salty-bitter-umami-oleogustus
def: Five primary taste qualities: sweet (sugar), sour (acid), salty (sodium), bitter (alkaloids), umami (savory, glutamate), and oleogustus (fat taste) / 甜、酸、咸、苦、鲜（鲜味）、脂肪味
ex: Umami from soy sauce; oleogustus from fatty foods.
pit: Oleogustus is a newer addition; AP may test only five traditional tastes.
note: Know that taste receptors are distributed across tongue but specialized areas are a myth.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.taste-receptors
def: Sensory cells in taste buds on the tongue, throat, and roof of mouth that detect taste molecules / 味蕾中的味觉感受器，分布于舌头、喉咙和口腔上部
ex: Each taste bud contains about 50–100 receptor cells.
pit: Taste receptors are not limited to the tongue; they also exist in the throat.
note: AP may ask about transduction: molecules bind to receptors → signal to brain.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.supertasters
def: People with a higher density of taste buds (especially fungiform papillae), causing heightened sensitivity to bitter and other tastes / 超级味觉者：拥有更高密度味蕾的人，对苦味等特别敏感
ex: They find broccoli or dark chocolate extremely bitter.
pit: Supertasters are not necessarily "better" tasters; they often avoid bitter foods.
note: Genetic variation in taste receptors (e.g., TAS2R38) is a classic AP example.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.medium-tasters
def: People with an average number of taste buds, typical taste sensitivity / 一般味觉者：具有平均数量的味蕾，味觉敏感度正常
ex: Most of the population (about 50%) are medium tasters.
pit: Not all medium tasters have identical sensitivity; it's a continuum.
note: AP rarely tests medium tasters directly; differentiate from supertasters and nontasters.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.nontasters
def: People with fewer taste buds, especially less sensitive to bitter and strong flavors / 非味觉者：味蕾较少，尤其对苦味和浓味不敏感
ex: They can eat bitter foods like Brussels sprouts without complaint.
pit: Nontasters still perceive all basic tastes, just less intensely.
note: AP may ask about genetic basis: nontasters are often homozygous recessive for PTC tasting.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.warm-cold-receptors
def: Sensory receptors in the skin sensitive to temperature changes (warm and cold spots) / 皮肤中感知温度变化的感受器（温点和冷点）
ex: Cold receptors activate below body temp; warm receptors activate above.
pit: There is no single "pain receptor" for extreme temperature; extreme heat/cold can activate nociceptors.
note: AP may link to Gate Control Theory for pain modulation.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.gate-control-theory
def: Theory that the spinal cord contains a neurological "gate" that can block or allow pain signals to the brain / 闸门控制理论：脊髓中存在神经“闸门”，可阻断或允许疼痛信号传至大脑
ex: Rubbing a sore arm activates touch fibers, closing the gate and reducing pain.
pit: The gate is not a physical structure but a neural mechanism; distraction or attention also affect pain perception.
note: AP often asks for an example of how the gate can be closed (e.g., massage, acupuncture).

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.phantom-limb
def: Sensation that an amputated limb (or other body part) still exists and may feel pain, tingling, or movement / 幻肢感：截肢后仍感觉该肢体存在并伴有疼痛、麻木或运动感
ex: A person with a missing arm feels itching in the "phantom" hand.
pit: Phantom pain is real; it is not a sign of mental illness but a result of brain reorganization.
note: AP may relate to sensory homunculus in the somatosensory cortex; brain maps remain for amputated limbs.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.vestibular-sense
def: The sense of balance, body position, and movement, detected by the inner ear (semicircular canals and otolith organs) / 平衡觉：感知身体平衡、位置和运动，由内耳（半规管和前庭）检测
ex: Spinning and feeling dizzy after a carnival ride.
pit: Vestibular sense is not the same as proprioception (position of limbs); it's about head movement and gravity.
note: AP may compare to kinesthesia; vestibular is about equilibrium, kinesthesia is limb position.

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.semicircular-canals
def: Three fluid-filled canals in the inner ear that detect rotational movement / 内耳中三个充满液体的管道，用于检测旋转运动
ex: Spinning in a chair and feeling dizzy afterwards
pit: Confusing with cochlea (hearing) or otolith organs (linear acceleration); semicircular canals are for rotation only
note: AP FRQ likely tests differentiating vestibular sense components (semicircular canals vs. otolith organs)

@@ ap-psychology.u1.t1-6.kinesthesis
def: Sense of body position and movement of limbs / 身体位置和肢体运动的感知
ex: Touching your nose with eyes closed
pit: Confusing with proprioception (often synonymous in AP, but kinesthesis emphasizes movement)
note: Often paired with vestibular sense; testable in sensation/perception FRQ

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.bottom-up-processing
def: Analysis that starts with sensory receptors and works up to the brain's integration / 从感觉受体开始向上到大脑整合的分析
ex: Seeing individual letters before recognizing a word
pit: Confusing with top-down: remember bottom-up = data-driven, starts from raw sensory input
note: AP loves comparing bottom-up vs top-down in perception questions

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.top-down-processing
def: Analysis guided by higher-level mental processes, using prior experiences and expectations / 受高层次心理过程引导的分析，利用先前经验和预期
ex: Reading a word by guessing from context despite missing letters
pit: Confusing with bottom-up: top-down = concept-driven, uses schemas
note: Often tested with ambiguous figures (e.g., old/young woman) to show how expectations shape perception

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.schema
def: A mental framework that organizes and interprets information / 组织并解释信息的心理框架
ex: A child's "dog" schema may include four legs, fur, tail
pit: Schemas can cause stereotypes or perceptual errors (e.g., seeing a gun when it's a wallet)
note: AP connects schemas to top-down processing and memory (e.g., constructive memory)

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.perceptual-set
def: A readiness to perceive stimuli in a particular way based on expectations / 基于预期以特定方式感知刺激的准备状态
ex: Hearing "milk" instead of "mint" in a sentence about dairy
pit: Confusing with schema (schema is broader knowledge structure; perceptual set is momentary expectation)
note: AP uses ambiguous figures or words in noise to illustrate perceptual set

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.gestalt-psychology
def: Psychological approach emphasizing that the whole is different from the sum of its parts / 强调整体不同于部分之和的心理学方法
ex: Seeing a face in a pattern of dots (not just dots)
pit: Not just "the whole is greater": Gestalt principles describe how we organize sensory input
note: AP tests specific Gestalt principles (closure, proximity, similarity, etc.) in visual perception

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.closure
def: Gestalt principle: we fill in gaps to perceive complete objects / 格式塔原则：我们填补缺口以感知完整物体
ex: Seeing a circle even when there are gaps in the outline
pit: Confusing with proximity (closeness) or similarity (likeness)
note: AP uses incomplete figures to test closure (e.g., a broken triangle appears as a triangle)

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.figure-and-ground
def: Gestalt principle: we separate visual field into a focal object (figure) and its background (ground) / 格式塔原则：我们将视野分为焦点物体（图形）和背景
ex: The famous vase/faces illusion
pit: Figure-ground can reverse, but it's different from ambiguous figures (which can have multiple stable perceptions)
note: AP often uses reversible figure-ground images to test this concept

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.proximity
def: Gestalt principle: we group nearby objects together as a unit / 格式塔原则：我们将邻近的物体归为一组
ex: Three dots close together appear as a group, separate from a distant dot
pit: Confusing with similarity (grouping by appearance) or continuity (smooth lines)
note: AP uses dot patterns or shapes to test Gestalt principles; proximity is one of the most tested

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.similarity
def: Perceptual grouping principle where items that look alike are seen as a group / 相似性原则：外观相似的物体被知觉为一个整体
ex: In a crowd of dots, red ones are seen as a separate group from blue ones
pit: Confuse with proximity (closeness) vs. similarity (look alike)
note: FRQ often tests Gestalt principles; pair with proximity, closure

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.attention
def: The focusing of awareness on a specific stimulus or task / 注意力：对特定刺激或任务的意识集中
ex: Focusing on a teacher’s voice in a noisy classroom
pit: Attention is not the same as consciousness; you can attend without full awareness
note: Foundation for selective attention, divided attention experiments

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.selective-attention
def: Focusing on one stimulus while ignoring others / 选择性注意：集中注意一个刺激而忽略其他
ex: Listening to one person in a crowded party
pit: Think it means “choosing” attention; it’s actually filtering out distractions
note: Classic dichotic listening task (Cherry, 1953)

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.cocktail-party-effect
def: Ability to focus on one conversation while filtering out others, yet hear your name across the room / 鸡尾酒会效应：在嘈杂中专注一个对话，但仍能听到远处自己的名字
ex: At a party, you ignore other chatter but notice when someone says your name
pit: Not just selective attention; the name breaks through the filter (breakthrough effect)
note: Demonstrates selective attention’s limits; often tested with Broadbent’s filter model

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.inattentional-blindness
def: Failing to see a visible object when attention is elsewhere / 非注意盲视：因注意力分散而看不到明显物体
ex: In Simons & Chabris’s gorilla video, observers counting passes miss a person in a gorilla suit
pit: Don’t confuse with change blindness (need before/after comparison)
note: Classic “invisible gorilla” study; FRQ asks for real-world example

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.change-blindness
def: Failing to notice a change in a visual scene due to a distraction or brief interruption / 变化盲视：因干扰或短暂中断而未能察觉场景变化
ex: In a video cut, a person’s scarf color changes but you don’t notice
pit: Requires a change; inattentional blindness is missing a stimulus, not a change
note: Often tested with flicker paradigm; also used in false memory research

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.binocular-depth-cues
def: Depth cues that require both eyes to perceive distance / 双眼深度线索：需用双眼感知距离的线索
ex: Holding a finger close to your nose and seeing it double (cues: retinal disparity, convergence)
pit: Monocular cues (one eye) vs. binocular (two) – remember “bi-” = two
note: Includes retinal disparity and convergence; FRQ: compare to monocular cues

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.retinal-disparity
def: The slight difference between images from each eye, used for depth perception / 视网膜视差：两眼成像的微小差异，用于深度知觉
ex: Close one eye, then the other; a nearby object shifts position against the background
pit: Don’t confuse with convergence (eye turning); disparity is image difference, convergence is muscle movement
note: Key for stereopsis (3D vision); tested in binocular cue questions

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.convergence
def: The inward turning of eyes when focusing on a close object / 辐辏：看近物时眼睛向内转动
ex: When you bring a finger toward your nose, your eyes cross slightly
pit: Retinal disparity is passive image difference; convergence is active muscle movement
note: Another binocular cue; works best for close objects (<10 meters)

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-1.monocular-depth-cues
def: Depth cues that can be perceived with one eye alone / 单眼深度线索：只用一只眼就能感知的深度线索
ex: Relative size (bigger = closer), linear perspective (parallel lines converge), texture gradient
pit: Not all monocular cues work at all distances; many overlap with pictorial cues
note: Seven main cues: relative size, interposition, linear perspective, texture gradient, shading, motion parallax, accommodation (muscle); cover in FRQ examples

@@ relative-clarity
def: Monocular cue; clearer objects are perceived as closer / 相对清晰度：清晰的物体被认为更近
ex: Hazy mountains appear far, sharp details near
pit: Often confused with atmospheric perspective (same concept)
note: AP exam asks for monocular depth cues

@@ relative-size
def: Monocular cue; if two objects are similar size, the smaller one is perceived as farther / 相对大小：同样大小的物体，小的看起来远
ex: Distant car looks tiny compared to nearby car
pit: Assumes objects are known to be equal size
note: Frequently paired with relative clarity on tests

@@ texture-gradient
def: Monocular cue; texture density increases with distance / 纹理梯度：远处纹理更密集
ex: A field of grass; distant blades blend into a solid texture
pit: May be confused with linear perspective (lines vs texture)
note: Common monocular cue tested in perception

@@ linear-perspective
def: Monocular cue; parallel lines appear to converge in the distance / 线性透视：平行线在远处交会
ex: Railroad tracks meeting at a vanishing point
pit: Confused with relative size (both monocular)
note: Classic test item for depth perception

@@ interposition
def: Monocular cue; overlapping objects: nearer object blocks the farther one / 重叠：前面的物体遮挡后面的
ex: A hand in front of your face covers the background
pit: Not a binocular cue (no two eyes needed)
note: Also called "occlusion" on some exams

@@ apparent-movement
def: Perceived motion from rapid static image changes / 似动现象：静态图像变化产生运动错觉
ex: Phi phenomenon — blinking lights seem to move
pit: Confused with real motion or induced motion
note: Gestalt principle; common in perception questions

@@ prototypes
def: The most typical example of a category / 原型：类别的典型代表
ex: Robin as the prototype for "bird"
pit: Confused with "exemplar" (specific remembered instance)
note: Influences judgments and stereotyping; AP cognitive

@@ assimilation
def: Interpreting new information within existing schemas / 同化：用现有图式理解新信息
ex: Calling all four-legged animals "dog"
pit: Must distinguish from accommodation (adjusting schema)
note: Piaget's cognitive development; AP asks comparisons

@@ accommodation
def: Adjusting schemas to fit new information / 顺应：调整图式以适应新信息
ex: Learning "cat" as a separate category from dog
pit: Opposite of assimilation; can be confused when contexts overlap
note: Crucial for Piaget's stage theory; exam contrasts both

@@ algorithms
def: Step-by-step problem-solving method that guarantees a solution / 算法：保证找到答案的逐步方法
ex: Using a math formula to solve an equation
pit: Confused with heuristics (mental shortcuts, faster but riskier)
note: AP tests recognition of algorithm vs heuristic in problem-solving

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.heuristics
def: Mental shortcuts that allow quick decisions / 心理捷径，快速决策
ex: Using "expensive = good" to judge product quality
pit: Can lead to systematic biases; often tested as fast but error-prone
note: FRQ term; contrast with algorithms

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.representativeness-heuristic
def: Judging probability based on how much something matches a prototype / 根据典型特征判断概率
ex: Assuming a quiet, bookish person is a librarian
pit: Ignores base rates; common trap is the Linda problem
note: Know base rate fallacy

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.availability-heuristic
def: Estimating likelihood based on how easily examples come to mind / 根据信息易得性判断频率
ex: Overestimating shark attacks because news coverage is vivid
pit: Vividness bias; recent events feel more likely
note: Often paired with representativeness

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.mental-set
def: Tendency to use past problem-solving approaches in fixed ways / 思维惯性，固着于已有方法
ex: Using a complex formula that worked before when a simpler one exists
pit: Hinders creativity; functional fixedness is a subtype
note: Can block insight

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.priming
def: Activating associations in memory to influence later thoughts or behavior / 启动效应
ex: Showing the word "yellow" makes you notice bananas faster
pit: Can occur unconsciously; often tested with word fragments
note: Links memory and perception

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.framing
def: The way an issue is presented influences decisions / 框架效应，表达方式影响选择
ex: "90% survival" vs "10% mortality" produce different choices
pit: Same information, different wording
note: AP favorite; appears in risk/benefit contexts

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.gambler-s-fallacy
def: Mistaken belief that past random events affect future independent outcomes / 赌徒谬误
ex: After five coin-flip heads, thinking tails is "due"
pit: Applies only to independent events; not the law of averages
note: Common in probability judgment

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.sunk-cost-fallacy
def: Continuing a venture because of past investment, even when irrational / 沉没成本谬误
ex: Staying in a bad movie because you already paid for the ticket
pit: Ignore sunk costs; focus on future value
note: Often appears in economics/business scenarios

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.executive-functions
def: Cognitive control processes that manage goal-directed behavior / 执行功能（抑制、工作记忆、认知灵活性）
ex: Planning a trip requires inhibiting distractions and updating plans
pit: Frontal lobe damage impairs executive functions
note: Includes inhibition, shifting, updating

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.creativity
def: The ability to produce novel and useful ideas / 创造力
ex: Inventing a new solution to an old problem
pit: Divergent thinking (multiple ideas) is key, not convergent
note: Often measured by divergent thinking tests

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.divergent-thinking
def: Generating multiple unique solutions or ideas / 发散思维：产生多个独特解决方案或创意
ex: Brainstorming many uses for a paperclip
pit: Often confused with creativity; divergent thinking is a component of creativity
note: FRQ cue – contrast with convergent thinking

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.convergent-thinking
def: Finding a single correct solution / 聚合思维：寻找唯一正确答案
ex: Solving a multiple‑choice math problem
pit: Students mix it up with divergent thinking; convergent narrows, divergent expands
note: Often paired with divergent thinking on FRQ

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-2.functional-fixedness
def: Inability to see an object’s alternative uses due to its typical function / 功能固着：因习惯功能而看不到物品的其他用途
ex: Using a coin only as money, not to tighten a screw
pit: Confused with mental set (general problem‑solving rigidity); functional fixedness is specifically about object use
note: FRQ tip – give an example of overcoming it (e.g., using a hammer as a paperweight)

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.explicit-memory
def: Conscious, intentional recall of facts and experiences / 外显记忆：有意识地回忆事实和经历
ex: Recalling the date of your birthday
pit: Often confused with implicit memory; explicit is deliberate, implicit is automatic
note: MC cue – also called declarative memory; split into episodic and semantic

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.episodic-memory
def: Memory of specific personal events / 情景记忆：个人具体事件的记忆
ex: Remembering your first day of school
pit: Students confuse with semantic memory; episodic has time/place context
note: FRQ – distinguish from semantic memory: episodic = what/when/where

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.semantic-memory
def: Memory of general knowledge and facts / 语义记忆：一般知识和事实的记忆
ex: Knowing that Paris is the capital of France
pit: Not tied to personal experience; often mixed with episodic
note: AP cue – part of explicit memory; no personal context

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.implicit-memory
def: Unconscious, automatic memory of skills and conditioned responses / 内隐记忆：无意识的技能和条件反应记忆
ex: Riding a bike without thinking about the steps
pit: Confused with explicit; implicit includes procedural and priming
note: FRQ – example of classical conditioning (e.g., fear of dentist) is also implicit

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.procedural-memory
def: Memory of how to perform motor skills and procedures / 程序记忆：如何做动作和程序的记忆
ex: Tying your shoes or playing an instrument
pit: A subtype of implicit memory; students forget it is not consciously recalled
note: AP cue – think “knowing how” vs. “knowing that”

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.prospective-memory
def: Remembering to perform a planned action in the future / 前瞻记忆：记住将来执行预定行动
ex: Remembering to take medication at 8 PM
pit: Often tested as “remembering to remember”; confused with episodic
note: FRQ – can be time‑based (take pill) or event‑based (pass store → buy milk)

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.long-term-potentiation
def: Long‑lasting increase in synaptic strength after repeated stimulation / 长时程增强：重复刺激后突触连接的持久增强
ex: Studying vocabulary multiple times strengthens neural connections
pit: Students think it is a type of memory; it is a neural mechanism that supports memory formation
note: AP cue – correlate with memory consolidation; often paired with Hebb’s rule

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.working-memory-model
def: A model of short-term memory as an active processor of auditory and visual-spatial information, coordinated by a central executive / 工作记忆模型：将短期记忆视为由中央执行系统协调的主动处理听觉和视觉空间信息的模型
ex: Solving a math problem in your head while ignoring background noise / 在脑中解数学题同时忽略背景噪音
pit: Don't confuse with the multi-store model; working memory emphasizes active manipulation, not just storage / 不要与多存储模型混淆；工作记忆强调主动操作，而不仅仅是存储
note: AP often asks how the central executive delegates tasks to subsystems / AP常考中央执行如何分配任务给子系统

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.primary-memory-system
def: (Outdated term) The immediate, conscious memory system; roughly equivalent to short-term memory / 原始记忆系统：即时、有意识的记忆系统，大致相当于短期记忆
ex: Remembering a phone number for a few seconds before dialing / 拨号前记住一个电话号码几秒钟
pit: On AP exams, "primary memory" is rarely used; prefer "short-term memory" or "working memory" / AP考试中很少用“原始记忆”；优先使用“短期记忆”或“工作记忆”
note: Historical term from William James; not a key tested concept / 来自威廉·詹姆斯的历史术语，非考试重点

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.central-executive
def: The component of working memory that directs attention, coordinates the phonological loop and visuospatial sketchpad / 工作记忆的组成部分，负责引导注意力，协调语音回路和视觉空间画板
ex: Choosing to focus on a conversation instead of the TV in the background / 选择专注于对话而不是背景电视
pit: It does not store information; it only manages / 它不储存信息，只负责管理
note: AP often tests its role in dividing attention / AP常考其在分配注意力中的作用

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.phonological-loop
def: The part of working memory that processes and briefly stores auditory (sound) information / 工作记忆中处理和短暂存储听觉（声音）信息的部分
ex: Repeating a new friend's name in your head to remember it / 在心里重复一个新朋友的名字来记住它
pit: It's for sound, not meaning; meaning goes to the central executive / 它处理声音而非意义；意义由中央执行处理
note: AP may ask about the "phonological similarity effect" / AP可能考“语音相似效应”

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.visuospatial-sketchpad
def: The part of working memory that processes and briefly stores visual and spatial information / 工作记忆中处理和短暂存储视觉和空间信息的部分
ex: Mentally picturing your route to a friend's house / 在脑中想象去朋友家的路线
pit: It handles both what things look like and where they are / 它既处理物体外观也处理位置信息
note: Often contrasted with the phonological loop in split‑attention tasks / 常在分心任务中与语音回路对比

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.long-term-memory
def: The permanent, relatively limitless store of information – facts, experiences, skills – outside conscious awareness unless retrieved / 长期记忆：永久、相对无限的存储系统，存储事实、经验、技能，除非被提取否则不在意识中
ex: Knowing your own birthday or how to ride a bike / 知道自己的生日或如何骑自行车
pit: It is not a component of working memory; it's a separate store / 它不是工作记忆的一部分，而是独立的存储
note: AP distinguishes between explicit (declarative) and implicit (nondeclarative) LTM / AP区分外显（陈述性）和内隐（非陈述性）长期记忆

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.multi-store-model
def: Atkinson‑Shiffrin model: sensory memory → short‑term memory → long‑term memory, with rehearsal as a key transfer mechanism / 多存储模型（Atkinson‑Shiffrin模型）：感觉记忆→短期记忆→长期记忆，复述是关键传递机制
ex: Seeing a flash (sensory), saying the image in mind (STM), then remembering it later (LTM) / 看到闪光（感觉记忆），脑中复述图像（短期记忆），之后记住（长期记忆）
pit: It is linear and oversimplified; working memory model is more dynamic / 它是线性的且过于简化；工作记忆模型更动态
note: AP loves comparing this to the working memory model / AP喜欢将此与工作记忆模型比较

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.sensory-memory
def: The briefest memory stage; holds sensory information for a fraction of a second (iconic ~0.3s, echoic ~3‑4s) / 最短暂的记忆阶段；保持感觉信息几分之一秒（图像记忆约0.3秒，回声记忆约3-4秒）
ex: Seeing a sparkler's trail after it moves / 看到烟火移动后的轨迹
pit: If attention is not paid, information decays; it's not "stored" consciously / 若未注意，信息会消退；它不是有意识储存的
note: AP often tests duration differences between iconic and echoic / AP常考图像记忆和回声记忆的时长差异

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.iconic-memory
def: A type of sensory memory for visual information; lasts about 0.3–0.5 seconds / 视觉信息的感觉记忆；持续约0.3-0.5秒
ex: The brief afterimage you see after a camera flash / 相机闪光后看到的短暂余像
pit: It's not the same as an "afterimage" in the retina; it's a mental persistence / 它不是视网膜上的“余像”，而是心理持续
note: Sperling's partial‑report experiment measured iconic memory capacity / Sperling的部分报告实验测量了图像记忆容量

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.echoic-memory
def: A type of sensory memory for auditory information; lasts about 3–4 seconds / 听觉信息的感觉记忆；持续约3-4秒
ex: Hearing the last few words of a sentence after someone stops speaking / 某人停止说话后仍听到句子的最后几个词
pit: It's longer than iconic memory, allowing you to "replay" sounds / 它比图像记忆长，允许你“回放”声音
note: AP may ask: which sensory memory lasts longer? Answer: echoic / AP可能问：哪种感觉记忆持续时间更长？答案：回声记忆

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.automatic-processing
def: Unconscious, effortless encoding of information like time, space, frequency / 无意识、不费力的信息编码，如时间、空间、频率
ex: Remembering the route you walked without actively trying to memorize it.
pit: Confusing automatic processing with implicit memory – automatic processing is a type of encoding, not storage.
note: Often tested as contrast to effortful processing in memory models.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.effortful-processing
def: Conscious, deliberate encoding of information requiring attention and effort / 有意识、需注意和努力的编码过程
ex: Repeating a phone number to memorize it.
pit: Students may forget that rehearsal is a form of effortful processing.
note: Key distinction from automatic processing; linked to the serial position effect.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.storage
def: Retention of encoded information over time / 编码信息在时间上的保留
ex: Keeping a memory of your first day of school.
pit: Storage is often confused with retrieval; storage is the process of maintaining, not accessing.
note: One of three basic memory processes (encoding, storage, retrieval).

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.levels-of-processing-model
def: Craik & Lockhart’s theory that deeper processing leads to better memory retention / 克雷克和洛克哈特的理论：加工越深，记忆保留越好
ex: Understanding a word’s meaning (deep) leads to better recall than focusing on its font (shallow).
pit: Not a model about storage types (sensory, short-term, long-term); it’s about depth.
note: Often contrasted with the multi-store model; answer questions focusing on “how” not “where”.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.shallow-encoding
def: Processing based on surface features like appearance or sound / 基于表面特征（如外观或声音）的加工
ex: Noticing a word is written in uppercase letters.
pit: Shallow encoding does not mean “forgetting quickly” – it means less meaningful processing.
note: Typically includes structural and phonemic encoding.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.deep-encoding
def: Processing based on meaning, associations, or personal relevance / 基于意义、联想或个人相关性的加工
ex: Thinking about how a word relates to your own life.
pit: Deep encoding is not the same as elaboration – elaboration is a technique, deep encoding is a level.
note: Yields best memory retention; often tested with semantic encoding.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-3.structural-phonemic-semantic
def: Three levels of processing: structural (appearance), phonemic (sound), semantic (meaning) / 三种加工水平：结构（外观）、语音（声音）、语义（意义）
ex: “DOG” – structural: letters D/O/G; phonemic: rhymes with “frog”; semantic: a four-legged pet.
pit: These are often presented as sequential steps, but they are independent levels.
note: Semantic is deepest; phonemic is intermediate; structural is shallowest.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.encoding
def: The process of converting sensory input into a form that can be stored in memory / 将感官输入转化为可存储的记忆形式的过程
ex: Seeing a face and remembering it later – encoding that visual information.
pit: Encoding is not the same as storage; it’s the first step.
note: Include automatic vs. effortful, and types like visual, acoustic, semantic.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.mnemonic-devices
def: Memory aids that use vivid imagery, organization, or associations to improve encoding / 使用生动图像、组织或联想来改善编码的记忆辅助工具
ex: “ROY G. BIV” for rainbow colors.
pit: Mnemonic devices are not a memory type but a technique – they don’t create new storage.
note: AP often asks for examples; apply to encoding strategies.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.method-of-loci
def: A mnemonic that associates items with specific physical locations / 将项目与特定物理位置关联的记忆术
ex: To remember a grocery list, imagine bread on your doorstep, milk in the kitchen.
pit: Confusing with peg-word method – loci uses spatial location, peg-word uses numbers/rhymes.
note: Known as “memory palace”; tested as an ancient but effective mnemonic.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.chunking
def: Organizing information into manageable units (chunks) to aid short-term memory. / 将信息组织成有意义的单元（组块）以辅助短期记忆。
ex: Remembering a phone number as 520-1314 instead of 5201314. / 将电话号码记成520-1314而不是5201314。
pit: Chunking is not just grouping; groups must be meaningful to you. / 组块不是随意分组，必须对你有意义。
note: Often tested with digit span tasks—expect to explain why chunking boosts capacity. / 常与数字广度任务结合考查——需解释为何组块能提升容量。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.categories-as-they-pertain-to-grouping
def: Mental groupings of similar items; using categories to organize information for encoding. / 对相似项目的心理分类；利用类别组织信息以便编码。
ex: Sorting fruits into "tropical" and "berries" when memorizing a grocery list. / 记忆购物清单时将水果分为“热带水果”和“浆果”。
pit: Do not confuse categories (broad groups) with chunks (specific meaningful units). / 不要将类别（宽泛）与组块（具体有意义的单元）混淆。
note: Categories support hierarchical organization—AP may ask how they help retrieval. / 类别支持层级组织—AP可能问它们如何帮助提取。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.hierarchies-as-they-pertain-to-grouping
def: Arranging categories from broad to specific, forming a tree-like structure for encoding. / 将类别从宽泛到具体排列，形成树状结构以辅助编码。
ex: Animal → Mammal → Dog → Poodle. / 动物 → 哺乳动物 → 狗 → 贵宾犬。
pit: Hierarchies require remembering the structure, not just categories alone. / 层级需要记住结构本身，而非仅类别。
note: Often paired with categories; shows deep processing (semantic). / 常与类别配对；体现深层加工（语义）。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.spacing-effect
def: Better long-term memory when learning sessions are spread out over time. / 分散学习时间比集中学习更有利于长期记忆。
ex: Studying 1 hour each day for 5 days vs. 5 hours in one day. / 每天学1小时共5天 vs. 一天学5小时。
pit: Spacing effect is about the timing of study, not the total hours. / 间隔效应关乎学习时间安排，而非总时长。
note: Classic AP finding—Ebbinghaus curve related. / AP经典知识点—与艾宾浩斯曲线相关。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.memory-consolidation
def: The neural process where short-term memories are stabilized into long-term memories. / 短期记忆转化为长期记忆的神经稳定过程。
ex: Sleeping after studying helps consolidation. / 学习后睡觉有助于巩固。
pit: Consolidation takes time; it is not instant. / 巩固需要时间，非即时完成。
note: Often linked to sleep and hippocampus role. / 常与睡眠和海马体功能关联。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.massed-practice
def: Cramming—studying large amounts of material in a single, continuous session. / 集中突击——在一次连续学习中钻研大量材料。
ex: Pulling an all-nighter before an exam. / 考试前通宵复习。
pit: Massed practice leads to short-term recall but poor long-term retention. / 集中练习短期回忆好，长期保持差。
note: Contrast with distributed practice; AP may ask which is better for exams. / 与分散练习对比；AP可能问哪种对考试更优。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.distributed-practice
def: Spreading out study sessions over time to enhance memory (same as spacing effect). / 将学习时间分散以增强记忆（即间隔效应）。
ex: Reviewing notes for 20 minutes each day for a week. / 一周内每天复习笔记20分钟。
pit: Do not confuse with interleaving (mixing topics). / 不要与交错练习（混合主题）混淆。
note: AP loves this—promote spaced study over cramming. / AP喜欢这个—提倡分散学习而非突击。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.serial-position-effect
def: Better recall for items at the beginning and end of a list than for the middle. / 对列表开头和末尾项目的回忆优于中间项目。
ex: If shown 10 words, best recall for first 2 and last 2. / 展示10个词时，头2个和最后2个回忆最佳。
pit: The effect includes both primacy and recency; do not pick only one. / 该效应包含首因和近因，不要只选其一。
note: Classic memory experiment—often shown with word lists. / 经典记忆实验—常用词表呈现。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.primacy-effect
def: Better recall of the first items in a list due to rehearsal in long-term memory. / 列表首项回忆更佳，因在长期记忆中复述。
ex: Remembering "apple" from a list because you repeated it silently. / 因无声复述而记住列表中的“苹果”。
pit: Primacy is for early items; recency for late items. / 首因针对开头项目，近因针对末尾。
note: Caused by more rehearsal of early items. / 由对早期项目更多复述引起。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-4.recency-effect
def: Better recall of the last items in a list because they are still in short-term memory. / 列表末尾项目回忆更佳，因它们仍在短期记忆中。
ex: Easily recalling the last word "zebra" on a list. / 轻松回忆列表最后一个词“斑马”。
pit: Distraction after list (e.g., counting backward) eliminates recency effect. / 列表后干扰（如倒数）会消除近因效应。
note: Shows short-term memory capacity; primacy shows long-term. / 体现短期记忆容量；首因体现长期记忆。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.sensory-memory
def: Brief storage of sensory information, lasting fractions of a second / 感觉信息的短暂存储，持续几分之一秒
ex: Seeing a trail of light when someone waves a sparkler in the dark / 黑暗中挥动烟花棒时看到的光迹
pit: Confusing iconic (visual) and echoic (auditory) memory durations – iconic <1 sec, echoic 3-4 sec / 混淆图像记忆和回声记忆的持续时间
note: AP loves asking capacity/duration; sensory memory is high capacity but very short duration / 高频考点：容量大但持续时间极短

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.short-term-memory
def: Temporary storage of information (about 20-30 seconds) with limited capacity (7±2 items) / 信息的临时存储（约20-30秒），容量有限（7±2个组块）
ex: Remembering a phone number just long enough to dial it / 记住一个电话号码直到拨完
pit: Students often think short-term memory capacity is fixed at 7 items; it's actually 7±2 chunks / 常误以为容量固定为7项，实际是7±2个组块
note: Miller’s Magic Number 7±2 is a classic AP concept / 米勒的魔数7±2是经典考点

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.working-memory
def: An active processing system that manipulates information in short-term memory (Baddeley’s model) / 主动处理系统，对短时记忆中的信息进行操纵（巴德利模型）
ex: Solving a math problem in your head while holding the numbers / 在脑中解题的同时记住数字
pit: Don't equate working memory with simple storage; it involves central executive, phonological loop, visuospatial sketchpad / 不要将工作记忆与简单存储等同；包含中央执行、语音环路、视觉空间画板
note: AP may ask to distinguish working memory from short-term memory; working memory emphasizes active manipulation / 注意区分工作记忆与短时记忆：工作记忆强调主动加工

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.long-term-memory
def: Relatively permanent storage of information with unlimited capacity / 相对永久的信息存储，容量无限
ex: Remembering your first day of elementary school / 记住小学第一天
pit: Long-term memory is not a single store; it includes explicit (semantic, episodic) and implicit (procedural) / 长期记忆并非单一存储；包含外显（语义、情景）和内隐（程序）
note: Long-term potentiation (LTP) is the neural basis – increase in synaptic strength / 长期增强作用是其神经基础——突触强度增加

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.maintenance-rehearsal
def: Repeating information over and over to keep it in short-term memory / 反复重复信息以保持在短时记忆中
ex: Repeating a phone number under your breath until you dial / 低声重复电话号码直到拨号
pit: Maintenance rehearsal alone rarely transfers info to long-term memory; elaborative rehearsal is needed / 仅靠机械重复很难将信息转入长期记忆，需要精细复述
note: AP often contrasts with elaborative rehearsal / 常与精细复述对比出现

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.elaborative-rehearsal
def: Connecting new information to existing knowledge to encode into long-term memory / 将新信息与已有知识联系以编码进入长期记忆
ex: Remembering “1492” by associating with “Columbus sailed the ocean blue” / 将“1492”与“哥伦布远航”关联记忆
pit: Students confuse it with maintenance rehearsal; elaborative is deeper processing (Craik & Lockhart levels of processing) / 与机械复述混淆；精细复述是更深层加工（克雷克和洛克哈特加工水平）
note: Levels-of-processing theory is a common AP essay topic / 加工水平理论是常见论述题考点

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.memory-retention
def: The ability to preserve information over time; measured by recall, recognition, and relearning / 随时间保持信息的能力；通过回忆、再认和再学习测量
ex: Being able to name all state capitals years after studying them / 学习多年后仍能说出所有州首府
pit: Retention ≠ recall; you can retain info (recognition) even if you can’t freely recall it / 保持≠回忆；即使不能自由回忆，仍可能再认（保持）
note: AP may test different retention measures – recognition is easier than recall / 不同保持测量方式——再认比回忆容易

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.retrograde-amnesia
def: Loss of memories formed before the amnesia-causing event / 对导致失忆事件之前形成的记忆的丧失
ex: After a car accident, a person doesn’t remember their wedding from last year / 车祸后不记得去年的婚礼
pit: Retrograde amnesia often spares implicit memories / 逆行性遗忘通常保留内隐记忆
note: AP distinguishes from anterograde amnesia; both can co-occur / 注意与顺行性遗忘区分；两者可能共存

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.autobiographical-memory
def: Memory for specific events and personal experiences from one’s own life (type of episodic memory) / 对个人生活中特定事件和经历的记忆（情景记忆的一种）
ex: Recalling your 10th birthday party / 回忆十岁生日派对
pit: Autobiographical memories are often distorted by time and emotion; they are not perfect recordings / 自传体记忆常被时间和情感扭曲，并非完美记录
note: AP may connect to flashbulb memories (vivid, but often inaccurate) / 可能联系闪光灯记忆（生动但常不准确）

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.anterograde-amnesia
def: Inability to form new memories after an amnesia-causing event / 无法在导致失忆事件后形成新记忆
ex: After brain injury, a person can’t remember a new acquaintance they met minutes ago / 脑损伤后无法记住几分钟前刚认识的人
pit: Often caused by hippocampus damage; procedural memory (how to do things) may still be intact / 常由海马损伤引起；程序性记忆（如何做）可能完好
note: Famous case H.M. – classic AP example of anterograde amnesia / 著名案例H.M.——AP经典顺行性遗忘例子

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.alzheimer-s-disease
def: A progressive neurodegenerative disease causing severe memory loss, cognitive decline, and personality changes / 一种进行性神经退行性疾病，导致严重记忆丧失、认知衰退和人格变化
ex: A patient forgets recent conversations or familiar faces / 患者忘记刚说过的话或熟悉的面孔
pit: Confusing normal age-related forgetfulness with Alzheimer's / 易混淆为正常衰老遗忘
note: Often linked to hippocampus damage on FRQ / FRQ常联系海马损伤

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-5.infantile-amnesia
def: The inability to recall autobiographical memories from early childhood (before age ~3-4) / 无法回忆婴幼儿期（约3-4岁前）的自传体记忆
ex: No one remembers their first birthday party / 无人记得自己的一岁生日派对
pit: Mistaken as mere language deficit; caused by hippocampal immaturity / 误以为是语言缺乏，实因海马未成熟
note: Key point: not repression, but brain development / 关键：非压抑，而是大脑发育

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-6.retrieval
def: The process of accessing and bringing stored memories into conscious awareness / 从记忆库中提取信息到意识层面的过程
ex: Answering a question on a test / 考试中回答问题
pit: Confusing retrieval with encoding or storage / 易混淆提取与编码或存储
note: One of the three memory processes (encoding, storage, retrieval) / 记忆三过程之一（编码、存储、提取）

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-6.recall
def: Retrieving memories without external cues (e.g., essay question) / 无需外部线索提取记忆（如论述题）
ex: Fill-in-the-blank questions / 填空题
pit: Easier than recall? No, recall is harder than recognition / 注意：回忆比再认更难
note: Measures active retrieval / 测量主动提取能力

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-6.recognition
def: Identifying previously learned information from a set of options (e.g., multiple choice) / 从选项中识别先前学习的信息（如选择题）
ex: Picking the correct answer on a multiple‑choice test / 做选择题时选出正确选项
pit: Thinking recall and recognition are equally easy / 误以为回忆与再认同样容易
note: Easier than recall; uses familiarity / 比回忆容易，依赖熟悉感

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-6.retrieval-cues
def: Stimuli (internal or external) that help trigger the recall of stored memories / 帮助触发提取存储记忆的线索（内部或外部）
ex: A song from high school brings back memories / 高中时的一首歌唤起回忆
pit: Only thinking of external cues; mood and context also serve as cues / 只想到外部线索，情绪和情境也是线索
note: Essential for “forgetting” explanations / 解释“遗忘”时必不可少

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-6.context-dependent-memory
def: Better memory recall when the external environment at retrieval matches that during encoding / 提取时的外部环境与编码时一致，记忆效果更好
ex: Studying in the same room as the exam improves performance / 在考试同房间学习能提高成绩
pit: Confusing with state-dependent memory / 易混淆为状态依赖性记忆
note: Focus on physical surroundings / 重点在物理环境

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-6.mood-congruent-memory
def: The tendency to recall information that matches one’s current emotional state / 回忆与当前情绪状态一致的信息的倾向
ex: Feeling sad brings back sad memories more easily / 心情低落时更容易想起悲伤往事
pit: Mistaking it for state-dependent memory (mood is a type of state, but specific to emotion) / 误认为是状态依赖性记忆（情绪是一种状态，但特指情感）
note: Emotional valence matches / 情感效价一致

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-6.state-dependent-memory
def: Better memory recall when the internal physiological or psychological state at retrieval matches that at encoding / 提取时的内在生理或心理状态与编码时一致，记忆效果更好
ex: Information learned while drunk is recalled better when drunk again / 醉酒时学的内容再次醉酒时回忆更好
pit: Confusing with context-dependent (external) or mood-congruent (emotional content) / 易与环境依赖（外部）或情绪一致（内容情感）混淆
note: Includes drug state, arousal level, etc. / 包括药物状态、觉醒水平等

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-6.testing-effect
def: Enhanced long‑term memory from repeated retrieval practice (self‑testing) compared to passive restudying / 通过重复提取练习（自我测试）比被动复习更能增强长期记忆
ex: Using flashcards instead of just re‑reading notes / 用抽认卡而非单纯重读笔记
pit: Assuming all repetition is equal; testing is active retrieval / 误以为所有重复效果相同；测试是主动提取
note: High‑yield AP concept – often in FRQs about study strategies / AP高频考点，FRQ常用于学习策略题

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-6.metacognition
def: Awareness and understanding of one's own thought processes and memory strategies. / 元认知：对自身思维过程和记忆策略的认知与理解。
ex: Realizing that you remember names better when you repeat them aloud. / 意识到自己大声重复名字更容易记住。
pit: Confusing metacognition with mere self-awareness; it involves monitoring and controlling cognition. / 将元认知与单纯的自我意识混淆；它涉及监控和调节认知。
note: MC often tests metacognition as part of retrieval strategies—e.g., using mnemonic devices. / 选择题常考元认知作为提取策略的一部分，如使用助记法。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-7.forgetting-curve
def: Graph showing how memory retention declines over time; rapid drop then leveling (Ebbinghaus). / 遗忘曲线：展示记忆保留随时间下降的曲线；快速下降后趋于平稳（艾宾浩斯）。
ex: After learning a list, you forget most within the first hour. / 学习列表后，第一小时内忘记大部分。
pit: Thinking forgetting is linear; it's actually exponential decay. / 认为遗忘是线性的；实际上是指数衰减。
note: FRQ often asks to apply forgetting curve to study schedules (spacing effect). / 自由问答题常要求将遗忘曲线应用于学习计划（间隔效应）。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-7.encoding-failure
def: Inability to recall information because it was never stored in long-term memory. / 编码失败：由于信息从未存入长时记忆而无法回忆。
ex: Forgetting where you placed your keys because you weren't paying attention. / 忘记钥匙放哪是因为没注意。
pit: Confusing with retrieval failure; encoding failure means info never entered memory. / 与提取失败混淆；编码失败指信息从未进入记忆。
note: Common MC question: "Which forgetting error occurs when info is not encoded?" / 常见选择题："哪种遗忘错误发生在信息未编码时？"

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-7.proactive-interference
def: Old information disrupts recall of new information. / 前摄干扰：旧信息干扰新信息的回忆。
ex: You keep calling your new girlfriend by your ex's name. / 总是用前任的名字叫新女友。
pit: Reverse with retroactive interference (old vs. new). / 与倒摄干扰（新干扰旧）相混淆。
note: AP likes asking which type of interference is at play. / 常考哪种干扰在起作用。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-7.retroactive-interference
def: New information disrupts recall of old information. / 倒摄干扰：新信息干扰旧信息的回忆。
ex: After learning Spanish, you forget some French vocabulary. / 学西班牙语后忘记部分法语词汇。
pit: Often confused with proactive interference; remember "retro" = backward, new hurts old. / 常与前摄干扰混淆；记住"retro"=向后，新伤旧。
note: FRQ scenario: "Which interference explains why studying Spanish after French hurts French recall?" / 自由问答题：学生学法语后再学西班牙语为什么影响法语回忆？

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-7.tip-of-the-tongue-phenomenon
def: Feeling that you know a word or name but cannot retrieve it; retrieval failure. / 舌尖现象：感觉知道但无法提取；提取失败。
ex: You know the actor's face but can't say his name. / 知道演员的脸但说不出名字。
pit: Not encoding failure; it's stored but inaccessible temporarily. / 不是编码失败；已存储但暂时无法访问。
note: Associated with retrieval cues; partial recall often reported. / 与提取线索相关；常报告部分回忆。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-7.repression-psychodynamic
def: Motivated forgetting of painful or traumatic memories (Freudian defense mechanism). / 压抑：主动忘记痛苦或创伤记忆（弗洛伊德防御机制）。
ex: Forgetting a childhood abuse event due to its emotional pain. / 因童年创伤性情感而忘记虐待事件。
pit: Not simply distraction; unconscious blocking of memories. / 不是简单的分心；无意识封锁记忆。
note: Controversial concept; AP may mention as a psychodynamic perspective. / 有争议的概念；AP可能作为精神动力学视角提及。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-7.misinformation-effect
def: Incorporating misleading information into a memory after an event (Loftus). / 错误信息效应：事后将误导信息融入记忆（洛夫特斯）。
ex: After hearing "smashed" vs "hit," witnesses recall broken glass more with "smashed." / 听到"撞碎"比"碰撞"的证人更容易回忆有碎玻璃。
pit: Not the same as source amnesia; it's about altering memory content. / 与源头遗忘不同；它涉及改变记忆内容。
note: Classic AP topic; often tested with eyewitness testimony. / 经典AP话题；常与目击者证词一起考。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-7.source-amnesia
def: Remembering information but forgetting where or how you learned it. / 源头遗忘：记住信息但忘记从何或如何学得。
ex: You recall a fact but can't remember if you read it or heard it. / 记得事实但不记得是读到的还是听到的。
pit: Often confused with misinformation effect; source amnesia is about misattributing source. / 常与错误信息效应混淆；源头遗忘是错误归因来源。
note: Part of constructive memory; source monitoring errors. / 属于建构性记忆；源头监控错误。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-7.constructive-memory
def: Memory that is actively built and modified based on experiences, expectations, and schemas. / 建构性记忆：基于经验、期望和图示积极构建和修改的记忆。
ex: Recalling a childhood event differently each time due to family stories. / 因家庭故事而每次回忆童年事件不同。
pit: Not just false memory; it's the normal process of memory construction. / 不仅仅是虚假记忆；这是记忆建构的正常过程。
note: AP context: eyewitness testimony unreliability, schema influence. / AP语境：目击证词不可靠性，图示影响。

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-7.imagination-inflation
def: Increased confidence in a false memory due to repeatedly imagining it / 因反复想象而增强对虚假记忆的信心
ex: Imagining breaking a window as a child makes you more likely to believe it happened
pit: Confuses with source monitoring error – both involve misattribution, but imagination inflation specifically requires imagining
note: AP asks how imagination can create false memories; often paired with Loftus studies

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.intelligence
def: The ability to acquire knowledge, reason abstractly, adapt to novel situations, and learn from experience / 获取知识、抽象推理、适应新环境和从经验中学习的能力
ex: Solving a never-before-seen puzzle
pit: Not just school smarts – includes practical and creative aspects
note: AP may ask for definitions of intelligence theories (Spearman, Gardner, Sternberg)

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.g-general-intelligence
def: A single general factor underlying all mental abilities, proposed by Spearman / Spearman提出的影响所有心理能力的单一一般因素
ex: People who do well in math also tend to do well in reading comprehension
pit: g ≠ total IQ score; g is a statistical factor; multiple intelligences challenge it
note: AP contrast with Gardner’s multiple intelligences and Sternberg’s triarchic theory

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.intelligence-quotient-iq
def: A numerical score derived from standardized intelligence tests, originally (mental age / chronological age) × 100 / 源自标准化智力测验的分数，原计算公式：(心理年龄/实足年龄)×100
ex: Mental age 12, chronological age 10 → IQ = 120
pit: Modern IQ is not calculated that way; uses deviation scores based on normal distribution
note: AP may test historical vs. modern calculation; mean = 100, SD = 15

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.mental-age
def: The level of intellectual performance typical for a given chronological age / 特定实足年龄对应的典型智力表现水平
ex: A 8-year-old performing at a 10-year-old level has mental age 10
pit: Only meaningful when compared to chronological age; not used alone in modern IQ
note: Historical concept from Binet; AP may ask for formula IQ = MA/CA × 100

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.chronological-age
def: The actual age in years since birth / 自出生起的实际年龄（岁）
ex: A child born in 2010 has chronological age 14 in 2024
pit: Not the same as mental age; both needed for original IQ
note: AP use in IQ formula; also know “ratio IQ” vs. “deviation IQ”

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.standardization
def: Establishing uniform procedures for administering and scoring a test, and creating norms from a representative sample / 建立统一的施测和评分程序，并根据代表性样本制定常模
ex: The WAIS-IV has standard instructions for how to give the test
pit: Standardization ≠ norming; both are part of test construction but norming creates score comparisons
note: AP focus: standard + norm = meaningful comparison; also needed for reliability/validity

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.validity
def: The extent to which a test measures what it claims to measure / 测验实际测量其所声称要测量的东西的程度
ex: A depression test should actually measure depression, not just sadness
pit: A test can be reliable (consistent) but not valid (e.g., consistent wrong measurement)
note: AP asks types: content, criterion (predictive/concurrent), construct

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.construct-validity
def: The degree to which a test measures an abstract, theoretical concept (construct) / 测验测量抽象理论概念（构念）的程度
ex: An intelligence test has construct validity if it truly measures intelligence, not just test-taking skill
pit: Harder to prove than content or criterion validity; involves building evidence over multiple studies
note: AP often pairs with “operational definition” – construct validity ensures the operational definition matches the construct

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.predictive-validity
def: The ability of a test to forecast future performance or behavior / 测验预测未来表现或行为的能力
ex: SAT scores have predictive validity for college GPA
pit: Correlation rarely perfect; predictive validity coefficients around r = .3-.6 are common
note: AP distinguish from concurrent validity (predicts current status); predictive = future

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.reliability
def: Consistency of measurement results over time or across items / 测量结果的一致性
ex: A reliable IQ test gives similar scores when retaken after a week.
pit: Reliability ≠ validity; a test can be reliable but not measure what it claims.
note: Essential for intelligence tests; often tested with correlation coefficients.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.test-retest-reliability
def: Consistency of scores when the same test is administered twice to the same group / 同组被试在不同时间重复测试得分的一致性
ex: Taking a personality test twice, a month apart, yields nearly identical scores.
pit: Practice effects or time gap too short can inflate reliability; too long may reduce it.
note: AP: correlation between two administrations indicates reliability.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.split-half-reliability
def: Consistency of scores across two halves of a single test / 将测试分成两半，比较两半得分的一致性
ex: Compare odd-numbered items to even-numbered items for the same test.
pit: Must adjust for test length (Spearman-Brown formula) because shortening the test reduces reliability.
note: Used when retesting is impractical; internal consistency measure.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.stereotype-threat
def: Anxiety and underperformance caused by awareness of a negative stereotype about one's group / 因意识到关于自己群体的负面刻板印象而产生的焦虑和表现下降
ex: A female student underperforms on a math test when reminded that "girls are bad at math."
pit: Not about actual ability; it's a situational pressure that impairs performance.
note: Classic AP topic; often linked to IQ test score gaps.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.stereotype-lift
def: Performance boost when a positive stereotype about one's group is made salient / 当自己群体的正面刻板印象被突出时，表现提升
ex: Asian-American students perform better on a math test after being reminded of the "Asians are good at math" stereotype.
pit: Opposite of stereotype threat; both show how stereotypes affect performance.
note: Less common on AP, but important contrast to stereotype threat.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.flynn-effect
def: The observed rise in average IQ scores over generations worldwide / 全球范围内世代间平均智商分数上升的现象
ex: A person scoring 100 in 1950 would be below average by today's norms.
pit: Does not mean people are "smarter" in all ways; likely due to better nutrition, education, environment.
note: AP: used to argue that intelligence is influenced by environmental factors.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.achievement-tests
def: Tests that measure what a person has learned / 测量个人已学知识的测试
ex: A final exam in history class.
pit: Confused with aptitude tests; achievement tests assess past learning, not potential.
note: AP: used to evaluate specific knowledge or skills.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.aptitude-tests
def: Tests that predict a person's future ability to learn or perform / 预测个人未来学习或表现能力的测试
ex: The SAT or ACT.
pit: Not a measure of innate intelligence; can be influenced by preparation.
note: AP: designed to assess potential, not past learning.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.fixed-mindset
def: Belief that abilities are static and cannot change / 认为能力是固定不变的信念
ex: "I'm just not good at math, so I won't try."
pit: Leads to avoiding challenges and giving up easily; contrasts with growth mindset.
note: Carol Dweck's theory; often linked to academic motivation.

@@ ap-psychology.u2.t2-8.growth-mindset
def: Belief that abilities can be developed through effort and learning / 认为能力可以通过努力和学习发展的信念
ex: "If I study harder, I can improve my math skills."
pit: Not just "try harder"; it involves embracing challenges and learning from criticism.
note: AP: associated with higher resilience and achievement.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-1.chronological-development
def: Study of changes over time, often age-based / 按时间年龄研究发展变化
ex: Comparing language ability at 2, 5, and 10 years old
pit: Chronological age ≠ developmental level (e.g., a 6-year-old may read at 8-year-old level)
note: Often contrasted with developmental milestones

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-1.continuous-development
def: Development as a gradual, cumulative process / 发展是平稳累积的过程
ex: Growing taller each year
pit: Confused with "no stages" – continuous doesn't mean uniform rate
note: Contrast with discontinuous; Piaget vs. Vygotsky

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-1.discontinuous-development
def: Development as distinct stages with qualitative shifts / 发展分为质变阶段
ex: Piaget's sensorimotor to preoperational stage
pit: Stages are not abrupt; transitions exist
note: Key for stage theorists (Piaget, Erikson, Kohlberg)

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-1.lifespan-development
def: Development from conception to death, not just childhood / 从受孕到死亡的全过程发展
ex: Studying cognitive changes in older adults
pit: Not only early childhood; includes adolescence, adulthood
note: Baltes' lifespan perspective – multidirectional, plastic

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-1.stability-and-change
def: Debate whether early traits persist (stability) or shift (change) / 早期特质是否持续稳定或改变
ex: Personality at age 5 predicts personality at age 50 (stability)
pit: Both can be true for different traits
note: Often tested with longitudinal vs. cross-sectional studies

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-1.nature-and-nurture
def: Debate between genetic influences (nature) vs. environmental (nurture) / 遗传（自然）与环境（教养）的争论
ex: Twin studies show IQ influenced by both
pit: Nature AND nurture interact, not either-or
note: Epigenetics shows environment affects gene expression

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.teratogens
def: Substances/factors that cause birth defects / 导致出生缺陷的物质或因素
ex: Alcohol → Fetal Alcohol Syndrome
pit: Only harmful during critical periods, not entire pregnancy
note: Know examples: alcohol, drugs, radiation, viruses

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.fine-motor-coordination
def: Control of small muscles (hands, fingers) / 小肌肉（手、手指）协调控制
ex: Using scissors, writing, buttoning
pit: Develops after gross motor; not present at birth
note: Typical milestone: pincer grasp ~9 months

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.gross-motor-coordination
def: Control of large muscles (arms, legs, trunk) / 大肌肉（手臂、腿、躯干）协调控制
ex: Crawling, walking, jumping
pit: Gross motor develops before fine motor
note: Reflexes (e.g., rooting) are not gross motor; voluntary

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.maturation
def: Biologically programmed growth, regardless of practice / 生物预设的成长，不受练习影响
ex: Most babies walk around 12 months without training
pit: Maturation ≠ learning; environment can slightly alter timing
note: Gesell's maturation theory; critical for readiness concepts

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.reflexes
def: Automatic, involuntary responses to stimuli / 自动、非自愿的反应
ex: Infant grasping reflex when palm is touched
pit: Confusing reflexes with learned behaviors; reflexes are innate
note: AP often tests newborn reflexes (e.g., rooting, sucking, Moro)

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.rooting-reflex
def: Infant turns head toward touch on cheek, opens mouth / 婴儿脸颊被触碰时转头张嘴
ex: Baby roots to find nipple for feeding
pit: Mistaking it for voluntary head turning; it disappears around 4 months
note: AP may ask why this reflex is adaptive (helps survival through feeding)

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.visual-cliff
def: Apparatus to test depth perception in infants / 用来测试婴儿深度知觉的装置
ex: Baby hesitates or refuses to crawl over the "deep" side
pit: Assuming it measures fear rather than depth perception
note: Classic study by Gibson & Walk; key for perceptual development

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.critical-periods
def: Specific time when an organism must be exposed to stimuli for normal development / 有机体必须接触刺激才能正常发展的特定时期
ex: Imprinting in geese within hours after hatching
pit: Thinking it’s exactly the same as a sensitive period; critical period is stricter, often irreversible
note: AP may contrast with sensitive period; often appears in language acquisition context

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.sensitive-periods
def: Optimal window when development is most easily influenced, but not strictly required / 发展最易受影响的最佳期，但并非绝对必需
ex: Learning a second language more easily before age 7
pit: Confusing with critical period; sensitive period is more flexible
note: AP may ask which is more rigid (critical period)

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.imprinting
def: Rapid, early learning that creates attachment to moving objects / 快速早期学习，形成对移动物体的依恋
ex: Lorenz’s goslings followed him as first moving object seen
pit: Thinking imprinting is learned like a skill; it’s innate and occurs in a critical period
note: AP often references Lorenz’s study; distinguish from mammalian attachment

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.growth-spurt
def: Rapid increase in height and weight during puberty / 青春期身高体重的快速增长
ex: Girls often spurt between ages 10–14, boys 12–16
pit: Assuming it affects all body parts equally; hands/feet grow first
note: AP may link to timing differences between sexes

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.puberty
def: Period of sexual maturation and physical changes leading to reproduction / 性成熟和生殖相关的身体变化期
ex: Onset of menstruation in girls, sperm production in boys
pit: Confusing puberty with adolescence; puberty is physical, adolescence includes psychosocial
note: AP may test hormonal changes (e.g., increase in testosterone/estrogen)

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.primary-sex-characteristics
def: Body structures directly involved in reproduction (e.g., ovaries, testes, genitals) / 直接参与生殖的身体结构
ex: Growth of penis during puberty
pit: Confusing with secondary sex characteristics; primary are reproductive organs
note: AP may ask to differentiate from secondary; appear with puberty

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.secondary-sex-characteristics
def: Non-reproductive sexual features that develop at puberty / 青春期出现的非生殖性征
ex: Breast development, facial hair, voice deepening
pit: Thinking they are essential for reproduction; they are not directly necessary
note: AP often pairs with primary sex characteristics in a comparison question

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.menarche
def: The first menstrual period / 女性初潮
ex: A girl experiences her first period around age 12-13.
pit: Often confused with puberty onset; menarche is one specific event within puberty.
note: AP may ask: "Which event marks the beginning of female reproductive capacity?" → menarche.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.spermarche
def: The first ejaculation / 男性首次射精
ex: A boy experiences his first ejaculation, often during sleep (nocturnal emission).
pit: Do not confuse with puberty onset; spermarche is a specific milestone.
note: AP may test as counterpart to menarche in male development.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-2.menopause
def: The cessation of menstruation, marking the end of reproductive years / 绝经
ex: A woman in her late 40s or early 50s stops having periods for 12 consecutive months.
pit: Often mistakenly thought to happen suddenly; it is a gradual process (perimenopause).
note: AP may link to hormonal changes and aging, not a disorder.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.schemas
def: Mental frameworks that organize and interpret information / 图式（心理认知结构）
ex: A child has a "dog" schema: four legs, furry, barks. Seeing a cat may initially be assimilated as "dog".
pit: Students mix "schema" with "script" (sequence of events). Schema is broader.
note: AP loves asking: "How do schemas influence perception or memory?" – they can lead to false memories.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.assimilation
def: Interpreting new experiences in terms of existing schemas / 同化（将新信息纳入已有图式）
ex: A toddler calls a horse a "doggy" because it fits the four‑legged animal schema.
pit: Opposite of accommodation; test traps ask which process fits a scenario where schema doesn't change.
note: AP cue: "Fitting new info into existing mental boxes" → assimilation.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.accommodation
def: Modifying existing schemas to incorporate new information / 顺应（调整图式以容纳新信息）
ex: The toddler learns "horse" is a different animal and creates a new schema.
pit: Students reverse assimilation and accommodation. Remember: accommodate = adjust.
note: AP often pairs with assimilation; identify which is happening when schema changes.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.sensorimotor-stage
def: Piaget’s first stage (birth–2 years); knowledge through senses and actions / 感知运动阶段
ex: A baby shakes a rattle to hear noise, learns object permanence (peek‑a‑boo).
pit: Object permanence is the key achievement; do not confuse with later stages.
note: AP asks: "At what stage does a child develop object permanence?" → sensorimotor.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.preoperational-stage
def: Piaget’s second stage (2–7 years); symbolic thinking but lacks logical operations / 前运算阶段
ex: A child uses a stick as a sword, but fails conservation tasks (e.g., same amount of water in different shaped glasses).
pit: Egocentrism (inability to take another's perspective) is a hallmark; do not confuse with "selfishness".
note: AP classic: conservation failure, egocentrism (Three Mountain Task), animism.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.concrete-operational-stage
def: Piaget’s third stage (7–11 years); logical thinking about concrete events / 具体运算阶段
ex: A child can sort objects by height and weight, understands conservation, but struggles with abstract/hypothetical problems.
pit: They can think logically only about tangible, concrete situations, not abstract ideas.
note: AP tests: conservation mastered, reversibility, classification. No abstract reasoning yet.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.formal-operational-stage
def: Piaget’s final stage (12+ years); abstract and hypothetical reasoning / 形式运算阶段
ex: A teenager can solve "if‑then" hypothetical problems, think about justice, love, and future possibilities.
pit: Not everyone reaches this stage; many adults remain in concrete operations. Also, it's not achieved at a fixed age.
note: AP asks: "Which stage allows systematic scientific reasoning?" → formal operational.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.object-permanence
def: Understanding that objects exist even when not seen / 物体即使看不见也存在的认知
ex: Baby looks for a toy after it’s hidden under a blanket
pit: Confuse with “out of sight, out of mind” – that’s lack of object permanence
note: Key milestone in sensorimotor stage (Piaget, ~8–12 months)

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.mental-symbols
def: Using words, images, or gestures to represent something absent / 用语言、图像或手势代表不在场的事物
ex: Child says “ball” while pretending a round block is a ball
pit: Not just “thinking” – it’s the ability to use one thing to stand for another
note: Emerges in preoperational stage; enables language and pretend play

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.pretend-play
def: Acting out scenarios and roles, often using mental symbols / 通过角色扮演和想象模拟场景
ex: Child pretends a banana is a phone and talks into it
pit: Don’t confuse with simple imitation – pretend play is self‑initiated and symbolic
note: Indicator of developing mental symbols and theory of mind; preoperational

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.conservation
def: Awareness that quantity stays the same despite changes in shape or arrangement / 认识到数量不因外形或排列改变而改变
ex: Water poured from a short, wide glass into a tall, narrow glass – child says same amount
pit: Typical mistake: focus on one dimension (height) and ignore width
note: Mastered in concrete operational stage (~7–11 years); classic Piagetian task

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.reversibility
def: Ability to mentally reverse or undo an action / 能在思维中逆转或取消一个操作
ex: Knowing that if you pour water back, it will be the same as before
pit: Not just “memory” but logical understanding that operations can be undone
note: Develops with conservation in concrete operational stage

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.animism
def: Belief that inanimate objects have feelings, thoughts, or life / 认为无生命物体有感情、思想或生命
ex: Child says “The sun is sad because it’s hiding behind a cloud”
pit: Don’t confuse with personification in literature – animism is a cognitive limitation
note: Characteristic of preoperational thought (Piaget)

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.egocentrism
def: Difficulty taking another’s perspective; assuming others see/think the same / 难以采纳他人视角，认为别人所见所想与自己相同
ex: Child covers their eyes and thinks others can’t see them (hide‑and‑seek)
pit: Not selfishness – it’s a cognitive limitation, not a personality trait
note: Classic three‑mountains task (Piaget); preoperational stage

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.theory-of-mind
def: Ability to attribute mental states – beliefs, desires, intentions – to oneself and others / 理解自己与他人有不同心理状态（信念、欲求、意图）的能力
ex: False‑belief task: child knows another person will look for a toy where they left it, not where it was moved
pit: Closely related but NOT identical to empathy; it’s about understanding beliefs, not feelings
note: Develops around age 4; tested via false‑belief; linked to autism spectrum

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.systematic-thinking
def: Methodical, logical approach to problem‑solving, considering all possibilities / 有条理、逻辑地解决问题，考虑所有可能性
ex: In pendulum problem, testing one variable at a time (length, weight, push)
pit: Not just “thinking step by step” – it requires generating and testing hypotheses
note: Hallmark of formal operational stage (Piaget, ~age 12+)

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.abstract-thinking
def: Thinking about concepts, ideas, and possibilities not tied to concrete reality / 思考脱离具体现实的概念、观念和可能性
ex: Discussing justice, love, or hypothetical situations (“What if humans had wings?”)
pit: Don’t confuse with “creative thinking” – abstract thinking is about non‑concrete content
note: Emerges in formal operational stage; enables advanced reasoning and philosophy

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.hypothetical-thinking
def: The ability to reason about possibilities not yet experienced / 对未经历的可能性进行推理的能力
ex: "If I drop this glass, it might break" / 思考“如果我扔掉杯子会怎样”
pit: Often confused with abstract thinking; hypothetical is specifically about possibilities / 易与抽象思维混淆；假设性思维特指可能性
note: Key for Piaget's formal operational stage / 皮亚杰形式运算阶段重点

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.scaffolding-as-it-pertains-to-vygotsky
def: Guidance that is adjusted as a learner gains skill / 根据学习者能力调整的指导支持
ex: A teacher gives hints on a math problem, then removes hints as student improves / 老师先提示解题思路，逐步撤去帮助
pit: Not the same as just helping; it's temporary and fades / 不是简单帮助，是临时且渐退的支架
note: Often paired with ZPD; "I do, we do, you do" / 常与ZPD一起考：“我做，我们做，你做”

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.zone-of-proximal-development
def: The gap between what a learner can do alone and with help / 学习者独立能完成与在帮助下能完成的差距
ex: A child can solve 2-digit subtraction alone but needs help with 3-digit / 孩子能独自做两位数减法，三位数需帮助
pit: Don't confuse with developmental stage; it's task-specific / 别与发展阶段混淆；它针对具体任务
note: Central to Vygotsky; must know that "assisted performance" is key / 维果斯基核心概念；“辅助表现”是关键

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.crystallized-intelligence
def: Accumulated knowledge and verbal skills; increases with age / 积累的知识和语言能力；随年龄增长
ex: Knowing the capital of France or vocabulary / 知道法国首都或词汇量
pit: Often tested as “factual knowledge” vs fluid / 常考“事实知识” vs 流体智力
note: Continue improving throughout life; Cattell-Horn theory / 终生增长；卡特-霍恩理论

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.fluid-intelligence
def: Ability to solve novel problems, use logic in new situations; declines with age / 解决新颖问题、在新情境中用逻辑的能力；随年龄下降
ex: Solving a puzzle you've never seen / 解一个从未见过的谜题
pit: Not the same as creativity; it's about speed/adaptive reasoning / 不等于创造力；关乎速度和适应性推理
note: Peaks in early adulthood; often contrasted with crystallized / 成年早期达峰；常与晶体智力对比

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-4.dementia
def: A decline in cognitive function severe enough to interfere with daily life / 认知功能严重下降，影响日常生活
ex: Alzheimer's disease causing memory loss and confusion / 阿尔茨海默症导致记忆丧失和混乱
pit: Not a normal part of aging; distinct from occasional forgetfulness / 不是正常衰老；区别于偶尔健忘
note: Know types (Alzheimer's, vascular) and that it's irreversible / 了解类型（阿尔茨海默、血管性）且不可逆

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-5.phonemes
def: Smallest units of sound that distinguish meaning in a language / 语言中区分意义的最小声音单位
ex: /b/ and /p/ – "bat" vs "pat" / 例如/b/和/p/区分“bat”和“pat”
pit: Not letters; it's sounds, and English has ~44 phonemes / 不是字母，是音素；英语约44个
note: Part of language's sound system; test on basic unit of speech / 语言声音系统部分；考言语基本单位

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-5.morphemes
def: Smallest units of meaning in a language / 语言中最小意义单位
ex: "un-" in "unhappy" and "happy" are two morphemes / “un-”和“happy”是两个语素
pit: Not the same as phonemes; morphemes carry meaning, phonemes do not / 与音素不同；语素有意义，音素无意义
note: Can be a whole word (run) or affix (-er); test on "meaning unit" / 可以是整词或词缀；考“意义单位”

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-5.semantics
def: The meaning of words and sentences / 词汇和句子的含义
ex: Knowing that "rose" is a flower, not a verb in "She rose up" / 知道“rose”可以指花，动词时是“起立”
pit: Often confused with syntax (sentence structure) / 常与句法（句子结构）混淆
note: Tested as understanding of meaning, not grammar rules / 考意义理解，非语法规则

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-5.grammar
def: The set of rules that govern how sentences are formed in a language / 语言中构成句子的规则体系
ex: "I walked" is correct; "I walk" tense difference / “I walked”正确；时态差异
pit: Not just "correct vs incorrect"; includes syntax and morphology / 不只对错；包括句法和形态
note: Broad term; may include syntax on exam / 广义词；考试可能包含句法

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-5.syntax
def: The set of rules that govern sentence structure in a language / 语法：规定句子结构的规则
ex: "The dog bit the man" vs "The man bit the dog" – meaning changes due to word order
pit: Students often confuse syntax (sentence structure) with grammar (broader rules including morphology)
note: AP may ask how syntax affects meaning or language acquisition stages

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-5.cooing
def: Early vowel-like sounds (e.g., "oooh", "aaah") produced by infants around 2-3 months / 咕咕声：婴儿约2-3个月时发出的类似元音的声音
ex: A 2-month-old says "coo" when smiling at parent
pit: Cooing is not babbling; babbling includes consonants
note: Often appears in language development timeline questions

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-5.babbling
def: Repetitive consonant-vowel combinations (e.g., "ba-ba", "da-da") beginning around 4-6 months / 咿呀学语：约4-6个月开始重复辅音-元音组合
ex: A 6-month-old repeatedly says "ma-ma-ma" without meaning
pit: Babbling is universal; even deaf infants babble with gestures
note: Key milestone; becomes more language-specific by 10 months

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-5.one-word-stage
def: Stage around 12-18 months where children use single words to convey whole sentences ("holophrastic speech") / 单词句阶段：约12-18个月，用一个词表达整句意思（全句式言语）
ex: Child says "milk" to mean "I want milk"
pit: These are not just labels; they carry intent (e.g., "up" = pick me up)
note: Often tested as the first meaningful vocabulary explosion

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-5.telegraphic-speech
def: Two-word phrases typical around 18-24 months, omitting function words (e.g., "want cookie") / 电报式言语：约18-24个月，省略功能词的双词短语
ex: "Daddy go" for "Daddy is going"
pit: Telegraphic speech still follows correct word order (syntax)
note: Signals understanding of basic syntax; content words preserved

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-5.overgeneralization-of-language-rules
def: Applying grammatical rules too broadly (e.g., "goed" or "runned") / 过度规则化：过度泛化语法规则（如把go的过去式说成goed）
ex: Child says "I goed to the park" instead of "went"
pit: This shows rule learning, not just imitation; it is evidence of cognitive process
note: Classic evidence for nativist theory (Chomsky) and cognitive development

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.ecological-systems-theory
def: Bronfenbrenner's theory that development is influenced by multiple nested environmental systems / 生态系统理论：布伦芬布伦纳提出发展受多重嵌套环境系统影响
ex: A child's development is shaped by family (micro), school-parent connection (meso), parent's job (exo), and cultural values (macro)
pit: Not just one system; all layers interact (especially micro and meso)
note: AP often asks to identify levels from a scenario

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.microsystem
def: Immediate, direct interactions (family, school, peers) / 微系统：最直接接触的环境（家庭、学校、同伴）
ex: A child's daily interactions with parents at home
pit: Microsystem is not just one setting; includes all face-to-face relationships
note: Innermost layer of Bronfenbrenner's model

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.mesosystem
def: Connections between microsystems (e.g., home-school link) / 中系统：微系统之间的连接（如家庭与学校的联系）
ex: Parent-teacher conferences that affect child's learning
pit: Mesosystem is the interaction, not the settings themselves
note: Often tested as "interaction between microsystems"

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.exosystem
def: External environments that indirectly influence development (e.g., parents' workplace) / 外系统：间接影响发展的外部环境（如父母的工作场所）
ex: A parent's job loss affecting family stress and child's mood
pit: Child is not directly in the exosystem, but it still impacts them
note: The "indirect layer" – not experienced firsthand

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.macrosystem
def: The outermost layer of Bronfenbrenner's ecological system, encompassing cultural values, laws, and customs that indirectly affect a child's development. / 布朗芬布伦纳生态系统的最外层，包括文化价值观、法律和习俗，间接影响儿童发展。
ex: A country's policy on parental leave influences how much time a parent can spend with a newborn.
pit: Confusing macrosystem with exosystem (exosystem involves direct institutional influence, macrosystem is broader cultural context).
note: AP FRQ may ask to identify the macrosystem in a scenario describing cultural norms or laws.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.chronosystem
def: The dimension of time in Bronfenbrenner's model, referring to changes in life events and historical context over a person's lifespan. / 布朗芬布伦纳模型中的时间维度，指生命历程中生活事件和历史背景的变化。
ex: The impact of the Great Depression on a child's economic security as they grow up.
pit: Thinking chronosystem is only about age; it includes historical events and life transitions.
note: AP often pairs chronosystem with macrosystem to discuss how societal changes affect development.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.authoritarian-parenting
def: A parenting style characterized by high demands and low responsiveness; strict rules with little warmth or explanation. / 高要求低回应的教养方式，规则严格，缺乏温暖和解释。
ex: "Because I said so" without any discussion.
pit: Confusing with authoritative (authoritarian is rigid, authoritative is warm but firm).
note: AP usually associates authoritarian parenting with children who are obedient but have lower self-esteem.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.authoritative-parenting
def: A parenting style with high demands and high responsiveness; sets clear boundaries while being warm and encouraging independence. / 高要求高回应的教养方式，设定明确界限，同时温暖并鼓励独立。
ex: Explaining rules, listening to child's viewpoint, but enforcing consequences.
pit: Authoritative is the "ideal" style; avoid mixing with authoritarian.
note: AP research shows authoritative parenting is linked to positive outcomes like high self-esteem and academic success.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.permissive-parenting
def: A parenting style with low demands and high responsiveness; indulgent, few rules, high warmth. / 低要求高回应的教养方式，放任，规则少，温暖高。
ex: Allowing a child to stay up as late as they want.
pit: Permissive is not "neglectful" (neglectful is uninvolved parenting). Permissive is warm but lacks structure.
note: AP may contrast permissive with authoritative on outcomes like self-regulation (permissive children often lack self-control).

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.attachment-styles
def: Patterns of emotional bond between infant and caregiver, typically assessed via the Strange Situation; includes secure, avoidant, anxious/ambivalent, and later disorganized. / 婴儿与照顾者之间的情感依恋模式，通常通过陌生情境评估，包括安全型、回避型、焦虑/矛盾型，后来加入混乱型。
ex: A child who explores confidently with caregiver present is likely secure.
pit: Attachment styles are not fixed personality traits; they can change with experience.
note: AP requires knowing Mary Ainsworth's Strange Situation and the three original styles (secure, avoidant, anxious).

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.secure-attachment
def: An attachment style where the infant uses the caregiver as a safe base to explore, shows distress at separation, and is easily comforted upon reunion. / 婴儿将照顾者作为安全基地探索，分离时苦恼，重聚时易被安抚。
ex: In Strange Situation, a secure child plays while mother is present, cries when she leaves, and greets her happily when she returns.
pit: Do not assume "secure" means never crying; secure children do show distress but recover quickly.
note: AP emphasizes secure attachment as optimal, linked to better social-emotional development.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.insecure-attachment
def: A broad category of attachment styles where the infant does not have a trusting, secure bond; includes avoidant, anxious/ambivalent, and disorganized. / 婴儿未建立信任安全的依恋关系的统称，包括回避型、焦虑/矛盾型和混乱型。
ex: A child who ignores the caregiver's departure and avoids them on return is showing insecure-avoidant.
pit: Insecure is not just one type; know the subtypes.
note: AP FRQ might ask to compare insecure and secure attachment behaviors in the Strange Situation.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.avoidant-attachment
def: An insecure attachment style where the infant shows little distress at separation and ignores or avoids the caregiver upon reunion. / 一种不安全的依恋风格，婴儿在分离时很少苦恼，重聚时忽略或回避照顾者。
ex: In Strange Situation, the child plays independently, doesn't cry when mother leaves, and turns away when she returns.
pit: Avoidant children may appear independent but actually lack deep emotional connection.
note: Often associated with caregivers who are unresponsive or rejecting.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.anxious-attachment
def: An insecure attachment style (also called anxious-ambivalent) where the infant is clingy, extremely distressed at separation, and both seeks and resists contact upon reunion. / 一种不安全的依恋风格（也称焦虑-矛盾型），婴儿黏人，分离时极度痛苦，重聚时既寻求接触又抗拒。
ex: Child cries hysterically when mother leaves, but when she returns, they arch away or hit her.
pit: Do not confuse with secure; anxious children are not easily comforted and show ambivalence.
note: AP often correlates anxious attachment with unpredictable caregiver responsiveness.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.disorganized-attachment
def: Inconsistent, confused, or contradictory behavior toward caregiver, often due to abuse or trauma / 混乱型依恋：对照顾者表现矛盾、困惑的行为，常源于虐待或创伤
ex: Infant freezes or rocks when caregiver returns after separation
pit: Confused with avoidant; key is lack of consistent strategy (odd, dazed behavior)
note: Rare but high-risk; appears in Strange Situation as most insecure type.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.separation-anxiety
def: Distress when separated from caregiver, peaking around 8–14 months / 分离焦虑：与照顾者分离时的痛苦，8–14个月达高峰
ex: Baby cries when parent leaves room
pit: Not just stranger anxiety; focus on departure, not unfamiliar people
note: Key sign of attachment forming; diminishes with object permanence.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.temperament
def: Biologically based pattern of emotional reactions and self-regulation / 气质：以生物学为基础的情绪反应和自我调节模式
ex: “Easy” baby smiles often, adapts quickly; “difficult” baby fusses, irregular routines
pit: Not the same as personality (personality includes experience); temperament is inborn
note: Thomas & Chess: easy, difficult, slow-to-warm-up. Goodness of fit matters.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.parallel-play
def: Children play side by side with similar toys but do not interact / 平行游戏：儿童并肩玩类似玩具但不互动
ex: Two toddlers each build with blocks near each other, ignoring each other’s play
pit: Not solitary (alone) or cooperative (interacting); it’s a bridge stage
note: Common in ages 2–3; typical of Parten’s play stages.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.imaginary-audience
def: Belief that others are constantly watching and judging one’s appearance/behavior / 假想观众：认为他人时刻注视并评判自己的外表或行为
ex: Teen feels everyone notices a small pimple; avoids going to school
pit: Confused with personal fable; imaginary audience is about being watched, fable about uniqueness
note: Part of adolescent egocentrism (Elkind); peaks in early adolescence.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.personal-fable
def: Belief that one’s own experiences are unique, special, and not subject to universal rules / 个人神话：认为自己经历独特非凡，不受普遍规则约束
ex: “I won’t get pregnant even if I have unprotected sex” or “No one understands me”
pit: Opposite: imaginary audience is external focus (being watched); fable is internal (I’m special)
note: Fuels risk-taking; declines with mature prefrontal cortex.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.social-clock
def: Culturally prescribed timing of major life events (marriage, career, parenthood) / 社会时钟：文化规定的重大生活事件的时间表（结婚、工作、生子）
ex: Feeling “behind” if not married by 30 in a traditional society
pit: Not the same as biological clock (aging); it’s social norms about age-appropriate milestones
note: Norms vary by culture; violations can cause social pressure.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.emerging-adulthood
def: Period from ~18–25 where identity exploration, instability, and self-focus dominate; not fully adult / 初显成年期：18–25岁，以身份探索、不稳定、自我关注为特点，尚未完全成年
ex: College student living in dorms, changing majors, feeling “in-between”
pit: Not just adolescence; it’s a distinct stage in industrialized societies (Arnett)
note: Key features: identity exploration, instability, feeling in-between, self-focused, possibilities.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.stage-theory-of-psychosocial-development-erikson
def: Eight lifespan stages each requiring resolution of a psychological crisis; successful resolution builds a virtue / 埃里克森心理社会发展理论：八个阶段，每阶段需解决心理危机；成功建立品质
ex: Stage 1: Trust vs. Mistrust → hope; Stage 5: Identity vs. Role Confusion → fidelity
pit: Do not recite stages in order without knowing the conflict’s outcome leads to virtue
note: Know all 8 stages by name, age range, and resulting virtue. AP often tests order or matching.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.trust-and-mistrust
def: Erikson’s first stage (infancy): develop trust if needs are consistently met; mistrust if unreliable / 信任对不信任：埃里克森第一阶段（婴儿期）：需求一致满足则信任，不可靠则不信任
ex: Responsive feeding and comfort → infant trusts world; neglect → mistrust
pit: Mistrust is not permanent; later experiences can change it, but early foundation matters
note: Virtue = hope. Corresponds to Freud’s oral stage.

@@ autonomy-and-shame-and-doubt
def: Erikson's second stage (1-3 yrs): toddlers assert independence; success → autonomy, failure → shame/doubt. / 埃里克森第二阶段（1-3岁）：幼儿主张独立；成功→自主，失败→羞耻/怀疑。
ex: A child insists on dressing themselves. / 孩子坚持自己穿衣。
pit: Confusing with "trust vs. mistrust" (infant stage). / 易与“信任vs不信任”（婴儿期）混淆。
note: AP asks for age range or outcome of successful resolution. / AP常考年龄范围或成功解决的结果。

@@ initiative-and-guilt
def: Erikson's third stage (3-5 yrs): children assert power over environment; success → initiative, failure → guilt. / 埃里克森第三阶段（3-5岁）：儿童对环境施加控制；成功→主动，失败→内疚。
ex: A child starts a game with friends. / 孩子主动和朋友玩游戏。
pit: Confusing with "autonomy" (self-control) vs. "initiative" (goal-directed action). / 混淆“自主”（自我控制）与“主动”（目标导向行动）。
note: AP links to play and social interactions. / AP与游戏和社交互动关联。

@@ industry-and-inferiority
def: Erikson's fourth stage (6-12 yrs): children learn competence through tasks; success → industry, failure → inferiority. / 埃里克森第四阶段（6-12岁）：通过任务学习能力；成功→勤奋，失败→自卑。
ex: A child excels at school projects. / 孩子在学校项目中表现出色。
pit: Not about social comparison with peers (that's later). Focus on skill mastery. / 并非关于同伴比较（那是后期），重点是技能掌握。
note: AP often pairs with school/academic context. / AP常与学校/学业情境结合。

@@ identity-and-role-confusion
def: Erikson's fifth stage (adolescence): teens explore roles to form self-identity; success → identity, failure → role confusion. / 埃里克森第五阶段（青少年期）：探索角色以形成自我认同；成功→身份，失败→角色混乱。
ex: A teen tries different hobbies and beliefs. / 青少年尝试不同爱好和信念。
pit: Not the same as Marcia's identity statuses—Erikson's stage is broader. / 不等于Marcia的身份状态——埃里克森阶段更广。
note: AP central for adolescence; can link to Marcia's statuses. / AP青春期核心；可联系Marcia的身份状态。

@@ intimacy-and-isolation
def: Erikson's sixth stage (young adulthood): forming close relationships; success → intimacy, failure → isolation. / 埃里克森第六阶段（成年早期）：建立亲密关系；成功→亲密，失败→孤独。
ex: A young adult commits to a romantic partner. / 年轻成人与伴侣承诺关系。
pit: Must have secure identity first before true intimacy. / 真正的亲密需先有稳定的身份认同。
note: AP tests the order: identity before intimacy. / AP考顺序：身份先于亲密。

@@ generativity-and-stagnation
def: Erikson's seventh stage (middle adulthood): contributing to next generation; success → generativity, failure → stagnation. / 埃里克森第七阶段（中年期）：为下一代做贡献；成功→繁衍，失败→停滞。
ex: Mentoring a junior colleague. / 指导年轻同事。
pit: Not just having children—includes teaching, volunteering. / 不仅指生育，也包括教导、志愿服务。
note: AP may ask for middle adulthood stage or examples of generativity. / AP可能问中年阶段或繁衍的例子。

@@ integrity-and-despair
def: Erikson's eighth stage (late adulthood): reflecting on life; success → integrity (acceptance), failure → despair (regret). / 埃里克森第八阶段（老年期）：反思人生；成功→整合（接纳），失败→绝望（悔恨）。
ex: An older adult looks back with satisfaction. / 老年人满意地回顾过去。
pit: Not about physical decline—focus on life review. / 并非身体衰退，而是人生回顾。
note: AP tests as final stage; often paired with wisdom. / AP作为最终阶段，常与智慧关联。

@@ adverse-childhood-experiences-aces
def: Potentially traumatic events before age 18 (e.g., abuse, neglect, household dysfunction); linked to long-term health/behavioral issues. / 18岁前潜在创伤事件（如虐待、忽视、家庭功能失调）；与长期健康/行为问题相关。
ex: A child witnessing domestic violence. / 儿童目睹家庭暴力。
pit: Not all ACEs cause same outcomes—resilience factors matter. / 并非所有ACE导致相同结果——韧性因素很重要。
note: AP asks for correlation with later physical/mental health. / AP考与后期身心健康的关联。

@@ achievement-adolescent-identity-development
def: Marcia's identity status: after exploration and commitment; secure identity. / 马西亚身份状态：经过探索和承诺后；稳固的身份认同。
ex: A teen chooses a career after researching and committing to it. / 青少年研究后承诺选择职业。
pit: Different from "identity foreclosure" (commitment without exploration). / 不同于“身份早闭”（未探索就承诺）。
note: AP contrasts with other three statuses (moratorium, foreclosure, diffusion). / AP对比其他三种状态（延缓、早闭、扩散）。

@@ diffusion-adolescent-identity-development
def: Marcia's identity status: no exploration and no commitment; apathetic. / 马西亚身份状态：无探索且无承诺；漠然。
ex: A teen has no career plans and doesn't care. / 青少年没有职业规划且不在意。
pit: Confusing with "moratorium" (exploring but not committed). / 易与“延缓”（探索中但未承诺）混淆。
note: AP tests which status is least mature. / AP考哪种状态最不成熟。

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.foreclosure-adolescent-identity-development
def: Commitment without exploration; adopting parents’ or society’s identity prematurely. / 未经探索即承诺；过早采纳父母或社会的身份。
ex: A teen becomes a doctor because their parents are doctors, without considering other careers.
pit: Confused with identity diffusion (no commitment). Foreclosure has commitment but no exploration.
note: AP FRQ: Label foreclosure when an individual commits to an identity without exploring options.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.moratorium-adolescent-identity-development
def: Active exploration without commitment; a period of trying different roles. / 积极探索但未承诺；尝试不同角色的时期。
ex: A college student changes majors multiple times, experimenting with interests.
pit: Moratorium ≠ identity crisis (crisis is the exploration itself). Moratorium is the process, not a negative state.
note: AP often contrasts moratorium with foreclosure and identity achievement.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.racial-ethnic-identity
def: Sense of belonging to a racial or ethnic group and the attitudes/feelings associated. / 对种族或民族群体的归属感及相关态度与情感。
ex: A Chinese American teen explores their heritage and feels pride in cultural traditions.
pit: Not the same as simple labeling; involves exploration and commitment like other identities.
note: AP may ask how racial-ethnic identity develops similarly to Marcia’s identity statuses.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.sexual-orientation
def: Enduring pattern of emotional, romantic, or sexual attraction to others. / 对他人的情感、浪漫或性吸引的持久模式。
ex: A person identifies as gay, straight, bisexual, or asexual.
pit: Sexual orientation is not the same as gender identity. Gender identity is about self, orientation is about attraction.
note: AP focuses on understanding that orientation is a normal variation, not a disorder.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.religious-identity
def: One’s sense of belonging to a religious group and internalization of its beliefs. / 对宗教团体的归属感及对其信仰的内化。
ex: A teen raised in a Muslim family actively explores and then commits to Islamic practices.
pit: Religious identity can change over time; not necessarily fixed from childhood.
note: AP cue: identity statuses apply to religious identity (foreclosure, moratorium, achievement, diffusion).

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.occupational-identity
def: Commitment to a career or work role after exploring options. / 探索后对职业或工作角色的承诺。
ex: After volunteering and interning, a person chooses to become a nurse.
pit: Occupational identity is not just having a job; it involves personal investment and future planning.
note: Often used as a classic example of Marcia’s identity statuses.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.familial-identity
def: Sense of self derived from family roles, expectations, and relationships. / 从家庭角色、期望和关系中获得的自我认知。
ex: Seeing oneself as a responsible older sibling or a caregiver for aging parents.
pit: Familial identity may conflict with other identities (e.g., independence vs. family duty).
note: AP rarely tests this specifically but appears in broader identity formation discussions.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-6.possible-selves
def: Images of what one might become in the future (hoped-for, feared, expected). / 对自己未来可能成为的样子的想象（期望的、害怕的、预期的）。
ex: A student has a hoped-for self as a successful entrepreneur and a feared self as unemployed.
pit: Possible selves are not just goals; they include feared selves that motivate avoidance.
note: AP link: possible selves influence motivation and behavior (e.g., feared self drives study).

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.behavioral-perspective
def: View that behavior is learned through associations, reinforcements, and punishments. / 认为行为通过联想、强化和惩罚习得的观点。
ex: A child learns to fear dogs after being bitten (association).
pit: Behavioral perspective ignores internal thoughts; it focuses only on observable behavior.
note: AP foundational perspective; contrast with cognitive or biological perspectives.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.classical-conditioning
def: Learning by association of an involuntary response with a new stimulus. / 通过将非自愿反应与新刺激关联来学习。
ex: Pavlov’s dog salivates to a bell because bell was paired with food.
pit: Confused with operant conditioning (voluntary behavior). Classical is involuntary reflexes.
note: AP FRQ: Identify UCS, UCR, CS, CR. Common trap: swapping CS and UCS.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.association
def: A link between two events or stimuli / 两个事件或刺激之间的联系
ex: Pavlov's dog linking bell to food / 巴甫洛夫的狗将铃声与食物联系起来
pit: "Association" is the general process; do not confuse with conditioned stimulus specifically / 别混淆为条件刺激本身
note: Foundational concept for classical conditioning / 经典条件作用的基础概念

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.acquisition
def: The initial learning stage where a conditioned response is established / 建立条件反应的初始学习阶段
ex: Dog starts salivating to bell after multiple pairings / 狗在多次配对后开始对铃声流口水
pit: Acquisition requires repeated pairing; one trial may not be enough / 一次配对通常不够，需多次
note: Occurs during the pairing of CS and US / 发生在条件刺激与无条件刺激配对时

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.associative-learning
def: Learning that two events occur together / 学习两个事件同时发生
ex: Learning that a flashing light predicts a shock / 学会闪光预示电击
pit: Includes both classical and operant conditioning; not just one / 包括经典和操作性条件作用，不只是其中之一
note: Broad category; AP may ask to distinguish from non-associative learning / 常考与无关联学习（如习惯化）的区别

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.unconditioned-stimulus (US)
def: A stimulus that naturally and automatically triggers a response / 自然自动引发反应的刺激
ex: Food in Pavlov's experiment / 巴甫洛夫实验中的食物
pit: US is unlearned; not the bell (CS) / 无条件刺激是天生产生的，不是铃声
note: Always paired with UR; neutral at start / 总是与无条件反应配对，一开始是中性刺激

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.unconditioned-response (UR)
def: The natural, automatic response to the US / 对无条件刺激的自然自动反应
ex: Salivation to food / 对食物的唾液分泌
pit: UR is not learned; it is the same as CR in form but not in origin / 无条件反应非习得，与条件反应形式相同但来源不同
note: Do not confuse with conditioned response / 注意与条件反应区分

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.conditioned-stimulus (CS)
def: A previously neutral stimulus that, after pairing with US, triggers a conditioned response / 原先中性刺激，与无条件刺激配对后引发条件反应
ex: The bell in Pavlov's experiment / 巴甫洛夫实验中的铃声
pit: CS starts as neutral; becomes learned trigger / 条件刺激最初中性，通过配对获得引发能力
note: Must be paired with US for acquisition / 须与无条件刺激配对才能习得

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.conditioned-response (CR)
def: The learned response to the CS / 对条件刺激习得的反应
ex: Salivation to the bell / 对铃声的唾液分泌
pit: CR is often similar to UR but elicited by CS alone / 条件反应常与无条件反应相似，但由条件刺激单独引发
note: CR may be weaker than UR / 条件反应可能比无条件反应弱

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.extinction
def: The diminishing of a conditioned response when the CS is presented without the US / 条件刺激出现但无无条件刺激时，条件反应逐渐减弱
ex: Dog stops salivating to bell after repeated bell-only trials / 多次只响铃声后狗不再流口水
pit: Extinction does not erase learning; it's inhibition / 消退不是遗忘，而是抑制
note: Often tested as the decrease in CR / 常考为条件反应下降

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.spontaneous-recovery
def: The reappearance of a previously extinguished conditioned response after a pause / 消退后休息一段时间，条件反应再次出现
ex: After extinction, dog salivates to bell next day / 消退后第二天狗对铃声又流口水
pit: Spontaneous recovery is temporary and weaker / 自发恢复是暂时的且较弱
note: Indicates extinction is not unlearning / 表明消退不是彻底消除学习

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.stimulus-discrimination
def: The ability to distinguish between a CS and other similar stimuli that do not signal a US / 区分条件刺激与其他不预示无条件刺激的类似刺激的能力
ex: Dog salivates to specific bell tone but not to a similar tone / 狗只对特定音调的铃声流口水，对类似音调不反应
pit: Opposite of generalization; AP may ask to compare / 与泛化相反，常考比较
note: Learned through differential conditioning / 通过分化条件作用习得

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.stimulus-generalization
def: Tendency to respond to stimuli similar to the CS / 对与条件刺激相似的刺激产生反应的趋势
ex: Dog conditioned to salivate to a bell also salivates to a similar tone
pit: Confusing with discrimination – generalization is responding to similar stimuli, not different ones
note: AP often asks: Little Albert generalized fear to white fluffy objects

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.higher-order-conditioning
def: A neutral stimulus becomes a CS after pairing with an established CS / 中性刺激通过与已有条件刺激配对而成为条件刺激
ex: Dog salivates to bell (CS1); then pairing light with bell makes light (CS2) also trigger salivation
pit: Think of it as "second-level" conditioning; the new stimulus never directly pairs with the US
note: Know it can create complex chains of associations

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.counterconditioning
def: Replacing an unwanted response to a stimulus with a desired one / 用期望的反应替代对刺激的不良反应
ex: Pairing a feared spider (CS) with relaxation (new CR) to reduce fear
pit: Not the same as extinction – counterconditioning uses a new response, not just removal of US
note: Often used in systematic desensitization therapy

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.taste-aversion
def: Learned avoidance of a food after one bad experience, even if illness is delayed / 一次糟糕经历后学会回避某种食物，即使疾病延迟出现
ex: Getting sick after eating sushi; now you avoid sushi even if the illness was from a virus
pit: The delay between CS (taste) and US (illness) can be hours – unusual for classical conditioning
note: AP classic example: Garcia's rats avoided sweet water after radiation-induced nausea

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.one-trial-conditioning
def: Learning occurs after a single pairing of CS and US / 仅一次CS-US配对后就产生学习
ex: Taste aversion often happens after one meal makes you sick
pit: Not all conditioning needs many trials; some associations form instantly (especially biological)
note: Often overlaps with taste aversion – a key exception to gradual conditioning

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.one-trial-learning
def: Learning that occurs in a single exposure, not requiring repetition / 仅一次接触就学会，无需重复
ex: Remembering where you parked after one glance (if salient)
pit: Often confused with one-trial conditioning – but one-trial learning is broader (includes observation, insight)
note: AP may ask: "Which type of learning happens instantly?" – taste aversion is an example

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.biological-preparedness
def: Innate tendency to learn certain associations more easily due to survival value / 先天倾向更易学会某些对生存有价值的联系
ex: Humans easily learn to fear snakes/spiders, but not flowers
pit: Not the same as instinct – it's a predisposition in learning, not a fixed behavior
note: Key for taste aversion: we are prepared to avoid bitter/sour tastes (poison cues)

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-7.habituation
def: Decreased response to a repeated, non-threatening stimulus / 对重复出现的无害刺激反应减弱
ex: Not noticing the sound of a fan after a few minutes
pit: Confusing with sensory adaptation (receptor fatigue) – habituation is a central nervous system learning process
note: AP loves: Habituation is the simplest form of learning

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.operant-conditioning
def: Learning through consequences (reinforcement/punishment) of voluntary behavior / 通过行为结果（强化/惩罚）进行的学习，行为是自愿的
ex: Rat presses lever → gets food; presses more often
pit: Confusing with classical conditioning (involuntary reflexes vs. voluntary actions)
note: Know the difference: operant = behavior operates on environment; classical = stimulus elicits response

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.reinforcement
def: Any consequence that increases the likelihood of a behavior / 任何增加行为发生可能性的结果
ex: Giving a child candy for cleaning room → child cleans more often
pit: Reinforcement is defined by effect, not by pleasantness – negative reinforcement is not punishment
note: AP trap: "Positive" means adding, "Negative" means removing (not good/bad)

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.punishment
def: An event that decreases the behavior it follows / 惩罚：跟随行为后出现、减少该行为的事件
ex: Giving a child extra chores for talking back / 孩子顶嘴后增加家务
pit: Punishment ≠ negative reinforcement; punishment decreases behavior, negative reinforcement increases it / 惩罚不等于负强化，惩罚减少行为，负强化增加行为
note: FRQ often asks to distinguish punishment from reinforcement

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.law-of-effect
def: Behaviors followed by satisfying consequences are more likely repeated; unsatisfying ones less / 效果律：带来满意后果的行为更可能重复，带来不满的则更少
ex: A cat escaping a puzzle box faster after getting food / 猫逃出迷箱后得到食物，下次更快
pit: Thorndike’s law is the foundation of operant conditioning, not classical / 桑代克的定律是操作性条件反射的基础，非经典性
note: Historical root; may appear in compare/contrast with Skinner

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.superstitious-behavior
def: Behavior repeated because it was accidentally reinforced / 迷信行为：因偶然强化而重复的行为
ex: A pigeon turning in circles before pecking because food was given once / 鸽子转圈后啄食，因某次偶然获得食物
pit: It is not truly causal; the reinforcement was coincidental / 并非真正因果，强化是巧合
note: Skinner’s superstition experiment; common multiple-choice example

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.learned-helplessness
def: Passive giving up after repeated unavoidable negative events / 习得性无助：经历多次无法逃避的负面事件后被动放弃
ex: Dogs that received unavoidable shocks later didn’t try to escape / 被电击且无法逃避的狗后来不尝试逃脱
pit: It is a learned response, not a personality trait / 是习得的反应，非人格特质
note: Seligman’s research; links to depression

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.positive-reinforcement
def: Adding a pleasant stimulus to increase a behavior / 正强化：增加愉快刺激以增加行为
ex: Giving a child candy for completing homework / 孩子完成作业后给糖果
pit: “Positive” means adding, not good; reinforcement always increases behavior / “正”指增加，非“好”，强化一定增加行为
note: Most common operant concept; distinguish with negative reinforcement

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.primary-reinforcers
def: Innately reinforcing stimuli that satisfy biological needs / 初级强化物：满足生理需求的天生强化物
ex: Food, water, warmth / 食物、水、温暖
pit: They do not require learning; unlike secondary reinforcers / 不需要学习，与次级强化物不同
note: Often contrasted with secondary in FRQ

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.secondary-reinforcer
def: Learned reinforcer through association with a primary reinforcer / 次级强化物：通过与初级强化物关联而习得
ex: Money, praise, grades / 钱、表扬、成绩
pit: They are conditioned; power depends on history / 是条件化的，力量依赖历史
note: Also called conditioned reinforcers; token economy uses them

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.reinforcement-discrimination
def: Responding only to specific stimuli that signal reinforcement is available / 强化辨别：只对能获得强化的特定刺激做出反应
ex: A rat presses lever only when a red light is on / 老鼠只在红灯亮时按压杠杆
pit: Discrimination is learned; not the same as generalization / 辨别是习得的，不同于泛化
note: Part of stimulus control; can appear with discriminative stimuli

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.reinforcement-generalization
def: Responding to stimuli similar to those present during reinforcement / 强化泛化：对与强化时相似刺激也做出反应
ex: A child who learned to say “please” at home also says it at school / 在家学会说“请”的孩子在学校也会说
pit: Generalization can lead to over‑responding; discrimination training reduces it / 泛化可能过度反应，辨别训练减少之
note: Opposite of discrimination; tested together

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.shaping
def: Gradually reinforcing behaviors that approach a desired target behavior / 塑造：逐步强化趋近目标行为的反应
ex: Training a mouse to press a lever first by rewarding any movement toward it / 训练老鼠按压杠杆，先奖励任何靠近动作
pit: Shaping uses successive approximations; not the same as chaining / 塑造用连续逼近，不同于连锁
note: Used for complex behaviors; Skinner box classic example

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.instinctive-drift
def: Tendency for learned behavior to revert to innate behavior patterns over time / 习得行为随时间退化为本能行为模式的倾向
ex: A raccoon trained to drop coins into a box begins to rub and wash them instead / 浣熊经训练将硬币投入盒子，后来却开始搓洗硬币
pit: Confuse with extinction – instinctive drift is not loss of learning but interference from instinct / 易与消退混淆——本能漂移不是学习消失，而是本能的干扰
note: AP may pair with Breland & Breland’s “misbehavior of organisms” / AP常与Breland和Breland的“有机体的不当行为”结合

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.negative-reinforcement
def: Increasing a behavior by removing an aversive stimulus / 通过移除厌恶刺激来增加行为
ex: Turning off a loud alarm by buckling your seatbelt → future buckling increases / 系安全带关掉刺耳警报→未来系安全带行为增加
pit: Confuse with punishment – negative reinforcement strengthens behavior, punishment weakens it / 易与惩罚混淆——负强化增强行为，惩罚减弱行为
note: AP often tests “negative reinforcement vs. punishment” / AP常考“负强化与惩罚”对比

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.reinforcement-schedules
def: Patterns that determine when a behavior is reinforced / 决定行为何时得到强化的模式
ex: Continuous reinforcement (every time) vs. partial reinforcement (not every time) / 连续强化（每次）VS 部分强化（不是每次）
pit: Think only one schedule – there are four distinct types / 误以为只有一种模式——实际有四种不同类型
note: AP loves comparing the four schedules and their effects on response rate & extinction / AP喜欢比较四种强化程式对反应率和消退的影响

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.continuous-reinforcement
def: Reinforcing the desired behavior every time it occurs / 每次期望行为出现都给予强化
ex: Giving a dog a treat every time it sits on command / 每次狗按指令坐下都给零食
pit: Faster to learn but easier to extinguish – leads to “partial reinforcement extinction effect” awareness / 学习快但消退也快——需注意“部分强化消退效应”
note: AP may ask: which schedule leads to fastest initial learning? Continuous / AP可能问：哪种程式初始学习最快？连续强化

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.partial-reinforcement
def: Reinforcing the desired behavior only some of the time / 仅有时强化期望行为
ex: Slot machine pays out randomly – gambler keeps pulling lever / 老虎机随机出奖——赌徒持续拉杆
pit: Confuse “partial” with “intermittent” – same concept / 将“部分”与“间歇”混淆——同一概念
note: AP emphasizes that partial reinforcement produces greater resistance to extinction / AP强调部分强化产生更强的消退抵抗力

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.fixed-interval
def: Reinforcement given after a specific amount of time has passed / 固定时间间隔后给予强化
ex: Checking mail daily at 10 AM because delivery is guaranteed at that time / 每天上午10点查信箱，因为此时一定送信
pit: Produces a scalloped graph – low response just after reinforcement, high just before / 产生扇形图——强化后反应低，前高
note: AP cues: scalloped pattern; low response after reinforcement / AP提示：扇形模式；强化后反应低

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.variable-interval
def: Reinforcement given after unpredictable amounts of time / 不可预测的时间间隔后给予强化
ex: Pop-up quiz – you study regularly because you never know when the next quiz will be / 随机测验——因不知下次何时考试而持续学习
pit: Confuse with fixed interval – but here response rate is steady, not scalloped / 易与固定间隔混淆——但此处反应率稳定，无扇形
note: AP often links to “steady, moderate response rate” / AP常联系“稳定、中等反应率”

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.fixed-ratio
def: Reinforcement given after a specific number of responses / 固定次数的反应后给予强化
ex: Buy 10 coffees, get 1 free – punch card / 买10杯咖啡获1杯免费——打孔卡
pit: Immediately after reinforcement, there’s a brief pause (post-reinforcement pause) / 强化后有短暂暂停（强化后停顿）
note: AP test: “after 5 correct answers, get reward” indicates fixed ratio / AP题：“5次正确回答后给奖励”提示固定比率

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.variable-ratio
def: Reinforcement given after an unpredictable number of responses / 不可预测的反应次数后给予强化
ex: Slot machine – you never know how many pulls until win / 老虎机——不知拉多少次才赢
pit: Produces highest response rate and greatest resistance to extinction / 产生最高反应率和最强消退抵抗力
note: AP: variable ratio is the most powerful and hardest to extinguish / AP：可变比率最强且最难消退

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-8.scalloped-graph
def: Graph showing a pattern of responding in fixed-interval schedules – low right after reinforcement, increasing as time for next reinforcement approaches / 固定间隔程式下的反应模式图——强化后反应低，随下次强化时间临近增加
ex: Student studies little right after exam, then crams near next exam – graph looks like scallops / 考试后学习少，临近下次考试突击——图形像扇贝
pit: Don’t confuse with fixed-ratio graph – FR has a brief pause, then high steady rate / 勿与固定比率图混淆——固定比率有短暂停顿后高稳率
note: AP may show a graph and ask “which schedule?” – scalloped = FI / AP可能给图问“哪种程式？”——扇贝形=固定间隔

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-9.social-learning-theory
def: Learning by observing and imitating others, emphasizing cognitive processes. / 通过观察和模仿他人学习，强调认知过程。
ex: A child watches a parent tie shoes, then tries tying their own.
pit: Confusing it with simple imitation—SLT includes attention, retention, reproduction, motivation.
note: Key theorists: Bandura, Bobo doll study.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-9.vicarious-conditioning
def: Learning through observing consequences of others' actions. / 通过观察他人行为的后果来学习。
ex: Seeing a classmate get praised for raising a hand makes you raise yours.
pit: Thinking it requires direct experience; VC is purely observational.
note: Often tested as part of observational learning.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-9.modeling
def: Imitating a specific behavior displayed by a model. / 模仿榜样展示的具体行为。
ex: A teen copies a celebrity’s hairstyle.
pit: Overlapping with social learning—modeling is the specific imitation act.
note: Four conditions: attention, retention, reproduction, motivation.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-9.insight-learning
def: Sudden realization of a solution; "aha!" moment. / 突然领悟解决方案的“啊哈！”时刻。
ex: Kohler's chimp stacking boxes to reach bananas.
pit: Confusing with trial-and-error; insight is abrupt, not gradual.
note: Associated with Kohler, Gestalt psychology.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-9.latent-learning
def: Learning that occurs but is not demonstrated until motivation appears. / 发生但直到有动机时才表现出来的学习。
ex: Tolman's rats learned a maze but only ran quickly when rewarded.
pit: Thinking it's unconscious learning; it's simply unperformed.
note: Key study: Tolman's latent learning experiment.

@@ ap-psychology.u3.t3-9.cognitive-maps
def: Mental representation of spatial layout or relationships. / 空间布局或关系的心理表征。
ex: Drawing a floor plan of your home from memory.
pit: Assuming it's only visual; can be abstract (e.g., concept maps).
note: Tolman's rats formed cognitive maps of mazes.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.attributions
def: Explanations we create for why people behave as they do. / 我们对他人行为原因的解释。
ex: Deciding a friend was late because they’re careless.
pit: Confusing with attitude; attributions are causal explanations.
note: Key distinction: internal vs. external.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.dispositional-attributions
def: Explaining behavior as due to internal traits or personality. / 将行为归因于内在特质或人格。
ex: "He failed because he’s lazy."
pit: Overlooking situational factors; leads to fundamental attribution error.
note: Also called internal attribution.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.situational-attributions
def: Explaining behavior as due to external circumstances. / 将行为归因于外部情境。
ex: "He failed because the test was unfair."
pit: Overusing it as an excuse; can lead to self-serving bias.
note: Opposite of dispositional attribution.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.explanatory-style
def: Habitual way of explaining events (optimistic vs. pessimistic). / 解释事件的惯常方式（乐观 vs. 悲观）。
ex: Pessimist: "I failed because I’m stupid" (stable, global, internal).
pit: Confusing with attribution itself; style is a pattern.
note: Links to learned helplessness and depression.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.optimistic-explanatory-style
def: Attributing positive events to internal, stable, global causes and negative events to external, unstable, specific causes / 将积极事件归因于内在、稳定、全局因素，消极事件归因于外在、不稳定、具体因素
ex: A student who gets an A says "I'm smart" (internal/stable/global), but fails a quiz says "The test was tricky" (external/unstable/specific)
pit: May confuse with "optimism" in general; note it's about explanatory style for specific events
note: AP FRQ often asks to apply this to depression or resilience

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.pessimistic-explanatory-style
def: Attributing negative events to internal, stable, global causes and positive events to external, unstable, specific causes / 将消极事件归因于内在、稳定、全局因素，积极事件归因于外在、不稳定、具体因素
ex: A student who fails says "I'm stupid" (internal/stable/global), but gets an A says "The test was easy" (external/unstable/specific)
pit: Not just "pessimism"; linked to learned helplessness and depression
note: Classic AP question: "Explain how a pessimistic explanatory style can lead to depression"

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.actor-observer-bias
def: Tendency to attribute own actions to situational factors, others' actions to dispositional factors / 将自己的行为归因于情境因素，将他人的行为归因于性格因素
ex: You trip because "the sidewalk was uneven"; others trip because "they are clumsy"
pit: Often confused with fundamental attribution error – actor-observer includes self vs other, not just overestimating disposition
note: Mention asymmetry: "I am situational, they are dispositional"

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.fundamental-attribution-error
def: Tendency to overestimate dispositional factors and underestimate situational factors when explaining others' behavior / 解释他人行为时高估性格因素、低估情境因素
ex: Seeing someone cut in line, you think "they're rude" (disposition) rather than "they're in a hurry" (situational)
pit: Unlike actor-observer, this focuses only on attributions about others
note: Classic AP example: failing to notice situational pressures in Milgram's obedience study

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.self-serving-bias
def: Tendency to take credit for successes (internal attribution) and blame failures on external factors / 将成功归因于自身（内在归因），将失败归咎于外部因素
ex: Winning a game: "I practiced hard"; losing: "The referee was biased"
pit: Not the same as self-enhancement; it's specifically about attribution for outcomes
note: AP often contrasts with self-effacing bias in collectivist cultures

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.internal-locus-of-control
def: Belief that one's own actions determine outcomes / 相信自己的行为决定结果
ex: A student believes studying hard will lead to good grades
pit: Don't confuse with self-efficacy (belief in ability to succeed); locus is about control over outcomes
note: May be tested with Rotter's concept; linked to higher motivation and achievement

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.external-locus-of-control
def: Belief that outcomes are determined by outside forces (luck, fate, others) / 相信结果由外部力量（运气、命运、他人）决定
ex: A student thinks grades depend on the teacher's mood or luck
pit: Not the same as situational attribution; it's a general belief pattern
note: Associated with learned helplessness; AP may ask to compare with internal locus

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.mere-exposure-effect
def: Repeated exposure to a stimulus increases liking for it / 反复接触某一刺激会提高对其的好感
ex: Hearing a song many times makes you like it more, even if you disliked it initially
pit: Works best with neutral/positive stimuli; exposure to negative stimuli may increase dislike
note: AP MCQ often uses novel stimuli (faces, nonsense syllables) to test this

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.self-fulfilling-prophecy
def: A belief or expectation that influences behavior in a way that makes the belief come true / 信念或期望影响行为，最终使该信念成真
ex: A teacher believes a student is smart, treats them differently, student performs better
pit: Not just "negative expectations" – can be positive too; must involve behavioral mechanism
note: Classic example: Rosenthal & Jacobson "Pygmalion in the classroom"

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-1.social-comparison
def: Evaluating oneself by comparing to others / 通过与他人比较来评价自己
ex: A student compares test scores to classmates to judge their own ability
pit: Two types: upward (to better) and downward (to worse); both affect self-esteem differently
note: AP may ask to explain upward/downward comparison in context of self-concept

@@ upward-social-comparison
def: Comparing oneself to others who are perceived as better / 将自己与更优秀的人比较
ex: Feeling inadequate after scrolling through influencers' perfect photos on social media / 看到网红完美照片后感到自卑
pit: Can motivate improvement but often leads to envy and lower self-esteem / 可能激励进步但常引发嫉妒和自尊降低
note: AP FRQ might ask how upward comparison affects self-concept in social media context

@@ downward-social-comparison
def: Comparing oneself to others who are perceived as worse / 将自己与更差的人比较
ex: Feeling relieved about your own test score after seeing a classmate's lower score / 看到同学低分后对自己的成绩感到宽慰
pit: Boosts self-esteem temporarily but can lead to complacency / 暂时提升自尊但可能导致自满
note: Often contrasted with upward comparison in AP questions on social cognition

@@ relative-deprivation
def: Perception that one has less than others one feels entitled to compare with / 认为自己比参照群体拥有的少
ex: A worker earning $50k feels deprived when colleagues earn $60k, but not when comparing to national average / 同事挣6万时觉得不公平，但对比全国平均则无此感
pit: Not actual deprivation but perceived inequality; can fuel protest or revolution / 并非实际匮乏，而是感知不公；可引发抗议或革命
note: Common AP link to social movements and frustration-aggression theory

@@ stereotype
def: Generalized (often oversimplified) belief about a group of people / 对某群体的概括性（常过度简化）信念
ex: "All Asians are good at math" / “所有亚洲人数学都好”
pit: Stereotypes can be positive or negative but both distort reality / 刻板印象有积极或消极之分，但都扭曲现实
note: AP asks to distinguish stereotype from prejudice (attitude) and discrimination (behavior)

@@ prejudice
def: Negative attitude or judgment toward a group and its members / 对某群体及其成员的负面态度或判断
ex: Refusing to eat at a restaurant because of the ethnicity of the owner / 因店主种族拒绝去其餐厅
pit: Prejudice is an attitude (ABC: affect), not behavior / 偏见是一种态度（情感成分），不是行为
note: Often tested alongside discrimination; remember ABC model: Affect (prejudice), Behavior (discrimination), Cognition (stereotype)

@@ discrimination
def: Unjustified negative behavior toward a group or its members / 对某群体及其成员的不公正负面行为
ex: Not hiring a qualified applicant because of their gender / 因性别不录用合格申请人
pit: Discrimination is behavior; can occur without prejudice (e.g., institutional) / 歧视是行为，可能在没有偏见的情况下发生（如制度性歧视）
note: AP FRQ may ask for examples of each: stereotype → prejudice → discrimination

@@ implicit-attitudes
def: Unconscious, automatic attitudes that influence behavior without awareness / 无意识、自动的态度，影响行为而不被察觉
ex: A person who consciously supports equality may still unconsciously associate negative words with minority groups on an IAT / 有意识支持平等的人可能在IAT中无意识地将负面词与少数群体关联
pit: Implicit ≠ explicit; they can conflict; IAT measures them / 内隐≠外显；可能冲突；IAT测试内隐态度
note: AP may reference IAT (Implicit Association Test) as measurement tool

@@ ethnocentrism
def: Belief that one's own culture/ethnic group is superior; judging others by one's own standards / 认为自己的文化/种族优越，以自身标准评判他人
ex: Thinking your country's food is "normal" and others' food is "weird" / 认为本国食物“正常”，他国食物“奇怪”
pit: Different from prejudice; ethnocentrism is about cultural comparison / 不同于偏见；民族中心主义涉及文化比较
note: Common AP example: in-group bias extended to cultural level

@@ just-world-phenomenon
def: Tendency to believe that people get what they deserve (good things happen to good people, bad to bad) / 倾向认为好人得好报，恶人得恶报
ex: Blaming a crime victim for "having been in the wrong place" rather than acknowledging random misfortune / 责怪受害者“走错地方”而非承认厄运
pit: Leads to victim-blaming; serves to reassure observer's sense of security / 导致谴责受害者；让观察者获得安全感
note: AP often pairs with hindsight bias in questions about blaming victims

@@ out-group-homogeneity-bias
def: Tendency to see members of an out-group as more similar to each other than they are, while seeing in-group as diverse / 认为外群体成员彼此更相似，而内群体则更多样
ex: "They all look alike" when referring to another race, but easily distinguishing friends of one's own race / “他们都长得一样”，但能分辨同种族朋友
pit: Does not mean out-group is actually homogeneous; perception bias / 并非外群体真的同质，而是感知偏差
note: AP may ask to contrast with in-group bias; remember "out-group = all same, in-group = diverse"

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-2.in-group-bias
def: Tendency to favor one's own group over others / 内群体偏差：偏爱自己所属群体的倾向
ex: Preferring your own sports team's players even when stats are equal
pit: Confused with out-group homogeneity; in-group bias is about favoritism, not perception
note: Paired with out-group homogeneity; test often cites social identity theory

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-2.belief-perseverance
def: Clinging to initial beliefs even after evidence disconfirms them / 信念固着：即使证据相反仍坚持原有信念
ex: Believing a stock will rise despite repeated losses
pit: Confused with confirmation bias; belief perseverance is about holding after disproof
note: Classic false-feedback study on suicide potential; often tests irrationality

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-2.confirmation-bias
def: Seeking and interpreting evidence that confirms preexisting beliefs / 确认偏差：寻找并解释支持已有信念的证据
ex: Only reading news from sources that agree with your political view
pit: Not the same as belief perseverance; confirmation bias is about search, not maintenance
note: Common in memory and reasoning topics; be ready to identify in scenarios

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-2.cognitive-dissonance
def: Psychological discomfort from conflicting attitudes, beliefs, or behaviors / 认知失调：态度、信念或行为矛盾时的心理不适感
ex: Smoking despite knowing health risks; rationalizing “I’ll quit soon”
pit: Confused with justification; key is internal inconsistency, not external pressure
note: Festinger’s classic paradigm; often tied to insufficient justification effect

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-2.cognitive-load
def: Amount of mental effort currently being used in working memory / 认知负荷：工作记忆中正在使用的心理努力量
ex: Solving a complex math problem while listening to loud music increases load
pit: Not intelligence; it's about task demand and resource capacity
note: Linked to dual-process models (System 1/2); high load may reduce self-control

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.social-norms
def: Unwritten rules of behavior accepted by a group or society / 社会规范：群体或社会中不成文的行为规则
ex: Standing quietly in an elevator facing forward
pit: Confused with social roles; norms are general expectations, roles are specific positions
note: Foundation for conformity studies; be ready to name examples

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.social-influence-theory
def: Broad theory that behavior is shaped by real or imagined pressure from others / 社会影响理论：行为受真实或想象的他者压力影响的理论
ex: Asch’s line study shows how group pressure alters answers
pit: Not a single named theorist; it’s an umbrella encompassing conformity, compliance, obedience
note: Includes normative and informational influence; test often asks to identify the type

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.normative-social-influence
def: Conforming to gain social approval or avoid rejection / 规范性社会影响：为获得社会认可或避免排斥而顺从
ex: Laughing at a joke you don’t find funny because everyone else does
pit: Confused with informational influence; normative is about fitting in, not being correct
note: Asch’s study; results in public compliance without private acceptance

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.informational-social-influence
def: Conforming because we believe others have more accurate knowledge / 信息性社会影响：因相信他人更正确而顺从
ex: Looking at others in a fire drill to decide the safest exit
pit: Often tested in ambiguous situations; not about approval but about correctness
note: Sherif’s autokinetic effect study; leads to private acceptance

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.persuasion
def: Process of changing attitudes through deliberate communication / 说服：通过有意识的沟通改变态度的过程
ex: A political advertisement using emotional appeals
pit: Confused with coercion; persuasion is voluntary and involves reasoning or emotion
note: Central vs. peripheral route (Elaboration Likelihood Model); both routes tested

@@ id: elaboration-likelihood-model
def: A dual-process theory explaining how persuasion occurs via two routes: central (careful thinking) or peripheral (superficial cues) / 双加工理论，解释说服通过中央路径（仔细思考）或外周路径（表面线索）发生
ex: A voter carefully analyzing a candidate's policy (central) vs. voting for a charismatic candidate (peripheral) / 选民仔细分析候选人政策（中央） vs. 因魅力投票（外周）
pit: Students sometimes think the two routes are mutually exclusive, but they can co-occur / 学生有时认为两条路径互斥，但可共存
note: AP FRQ often asks which route leads to lasting attitude change (central) / 常考哪条路径产生持久态度改变（中央）

@@ id: central-route
def: Persuasion that occurs when people think carefully about arguments and evidence / 当人们仔细思考论据和证据时发生的说服
ex: A consumer reading detailed product reviews before purchasing a laptop / 消费者购买前细读产品详细评论
pit: Requires motivation and ability, so not always used / 需要动机和能力，并非总被使用
note: Leads to stronger, longer-lasting attitude change / 产生更强、更持久的态度改变

@@ id: peripheral-route
def: Persuasion based on superficial cues like attractiveness, credibility, or emotions / 基于吸引力、可信度或情绪等表面线索的说服
ex: Buying a product because a celebrity endorses it / 因名人代言而购买产品
pit: Attitude change is often temporary and less resistant to counterarguments / 态度改变通常是暂时的，较难抵抗反论
note: Often tested as contrast to central route in AP MC / AP选择题常对比中央路径

@@ id: halo-effect
def: A cognitive bias where a positive impression in one area influences perception in other areas / 认知偏差：某一方面的积极印象影响对其他方面的看法
ex: Assuming a handsome person is also kind and intelligent / 假设一个英俊的人也善良聪明
pit: Not limited to physical attractiveness; can apply to any positive trait / 不限于外貌，任何积极特质都可能
note: Common in person perception and impression formation questions / 常见于人际知觉和印象形成题

@@ id: foot-in-the-door-technique
def: A compliance strategy where a small request is made first to increase agreement with a larger request later / 先提小要求，以增加后续大要求同意的策略
ex: Asking someone to sign a petition, then later ask for a donation / 先请人签请愿书，再请求捐款
pit: The initial request must be reasonable and related / 初始要求需合理且相关
note: Works due to self-perception or consistency principle / 基于自我感知或一致性原理

@@ id: door-in-the-face-technique
def: A compliance strategy where a large, unreasonable request is made first, and after refusal, a smaller, reasonable request is made / 先提过大不合理要求，拒绝后提较小合理要求
ex: Asking "Can you volunteer every day?" then "Can you volunteer once?" / 问“能每天做志愿者吗？”再问“能做一次吗？”
pit: The contrast effect makes the second request seem more reasonable / 对比效应使第二个请求显得更合理
note: Often confused with foot-in-the-door; test may ask to distinguish / 易混淆，考试可能要求区分

@@ id: conformity
def: Adjusting one's behavior or thinking to match a group standard / 调整行为或思维以符合群体标准
ex: Lining up at a crosswalk because others do, even if no cars / 即使没车也因他人而排队等红灯
pit: Can be due to informational (wanting to be correct) or normative (wanting to be liked) social influence / 源于信息性（想正确）或规范性（想被喜欢）社会影响
note: Asch's line study is classic example; know factors that reduce conformity / 经典实验阿希线段研究；了解减少从众的因素

@@ id: obedience
def: Following direct orders from an authority figure / 服从权威人物的直接命令
ex: Milgram's experiment where participants gave shocks to a learner when ordered / 米尔格拉姆实验中参与者按命令对学习者施电击
pit: Obedience differs from conformity: obedience is direct command, conformity is peer pressure / 服从与从众不同：服从是直接命令，从众是同伴压力
note: Milgram study key; factors like proximity of authority and victim affect rates / 米尔格拉姆研究关键；权威和受害者接近程度影响服从率

@@ id: individualism
def: A cultural value emphasizing personal goals, independence, and self-reliance / 强调个人目标、独立和自力更生的文化价值观
ex: In the U.S., people often prioritize personal achievement over group harmony / 在美国，人们常将个人成就置于群体和谐之上
pit: Not the same as selfishness; it's a cultural dimension / 不等于自私；是文化维度
note: Contrast with collectivism on AP cross-cultural questions / AP跨文化题中与集体主义对比

@@ id: collectivism
def: A cultural value emphasizing group goals, interdependence, and social harmony / 强调群体目标、相互依赖和社会和谐的文化价值观
ex: In many East Asian cultures, decisions are made considering family or community impact / 在许多东亚文化中，决策考虑家庭或社区影响
pit: Does not mean lack of individual identity; group is central but individual exists / 并非缺乏个人身份；群体为中心，但个人仍存在
note: Often paired with individualism in AP FRQ about cultural influences on behavior / AP FRQ常与个人主义配对考查文化对行为的影响

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.multiculturalism
def: The coexistence of diverse cultural groups within a society, emphasizing respect and equal value for all cultures. / 多元文化共存并相互尊重、平等对待的社会状态。
ex: A school celebrating holidays from many cultures (Diwali, Lunar New Year, Christmas).
pit: Confusing with assimilation, where minorities adopt majority culture.
note: Often appears in questions about reducing prejudice through exposure.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.group-polarization
def: The tendency for group discussion to strengthen members' initial attitudes, making them more extreme. / 群体讨论使成员原有态度更极端的现象。
ex: A jury initially leaning guilty becomes strongly convinced of guilt after deliberation.
pit: Not the same as groupthink (which suppresses dissent for harmony); polarization intensifies, not silences.
note: Key for explaining why like-minded groups become more radical.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.groupthink
def: The mode of thinking in a cohesive group that prioritizes harmony and consensus over realistic appraisal of alternatives. / 群体为了维护一致而忽视客观评价、压制异议的思维模式。
ex: NASA managers ignoring safety warnings before the Challenger disaster because everyone agreed.
pit: Confusing with conformity (groupthink is a specific group decision-making flaw, not just any conformity).
note: AP frq often asks for symptoms (illusion of invulnerability, self-censorship).

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.diffusion-of-responsibility
def: The tendency for individuals to feel less personal responsibility to act when others are present. / 当有他人在场时，个人感到责任分散而更少采取行动。
ex: Bystanders not helping a person having a seizure because each assumes someone else will.
pit: Not the same as social loafing (which is about reduced effort on a task, not inaction in an emergency).
note: Key component of bystander effect; often paired with pluralistic ignorance.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.social-loafing
def: The tendency to exert less effort when working in a group than when working alone. / 在集体任务中个人付出比独自时更少的努力。
ex: A student contributing less to a group project because others will pick up the slack.
pit: Confusing with diffusion of responsibility (social loafing is about effort; diffusion is about responsibility for action).
note: Reduced when individual contributions are identifiable or task is challenging.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.deindividuation
def: Loss of self-awareness and personal identity in a group, leading to reduced self-restraint and increased impulsive behavior. / 在群体中自我意识丧失，导致行为更冲动、更少自我约束。
ex: Rioters vandalizing property while wearing masks, feeling anonymous.
pit: Not simply "being in a crowd"; requires anonymity and arousal.
note: Often linked to mob behavior and online trolling.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.social-facilitation
def: The tendency to perform simple or well-learned tasks better when others are present, but complex tasks worse. / 他人在场提高简单任务表现、降低复杂任务表现的现象。
ex: A skilled musician plays better in front of an audience; a beginner stumbles.
pit: Confusing with social loafing (facilitation is about performance change due to arousal, not effort reduction).
note: Remember the Yerkes-Dodson law connection: arousal enhances dominant response.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.false-consensus-effect
def: The tendency to overestimate the extent to which others share our beliefs, attitudes, and behaviors. / 高估他人与自己持相同观点或行为的倾向。
ex: A heavy drinker assuming most college students drink as much as they do.
pit: Not the same as false uniqueness (underestimating others' positive traits).
note: Common in AP social cognition items; think "everyone thinks like me."

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.superordinate-goals
def: Shared goals that unite opposing groups, requiring cooperation to achieve. / 使对立群体必须合作才能实现的共同目标。
ex: Two rival student clubs working together to plan a successful school fundraiser.
pit: Not just any common goal; must override conflict and require interdependence.
note: Sherif's Robbers Cave experiment; key strategy to reduce intergroup hostility.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.social-traps
def: A situation where individuals pursue short-term self-interest, leading to long-term collective harm. / 个人追求短期利益导致长期集体损害的局面。
ex: Overfishing by multiple fishermen, depleting the ocean for everyone.
pit: Confusing with tragedy of the commons (social trap is a broader psychological term).
note: AP can frame as prisoners' dilemma or resource depletion; solution: rules or communication.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.industrial-organizational-i-o-psychologists
def: Psychologists who apply psychological principles to improve workplace productivity, satisfaction, and organizational behavior. / 工业组织心理学家：应用心理学原理提升工作场所生产力、满意度和组织行为。
ex: An I/O psychologist redesigns a company’s hiring tests to reduce bias and increase job performance.
pit: Students often confuse I/O with clinical psychology; I/O focuses on work behavior, not mental health treatment.
note: FRQ may ask how I/O principles reduce turnover or improve teamwork.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.burnout
def: State of physical, emotional, and mental exhaustion caused by prolonged stress or overwork, often leading to reduced performance. / 职业倦怠：由长期压力或过度工作导致的身心疲惫状态，常伴随效率下降。
ex: A nurse works 12-hour shifts for months, feels drained, cynical about patients, and doubts her ability.
pit: Burnout is not just “being tired”; it includes depersonalization and reduced personal accomplishment.
note: Often linked to lack of control, reward, or community in workplace.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.altruism
def: Unselfish behavior that benefits others without expectation of personal gain. / 利他主义：不求个人回报、纯粹帮助他人的无私行为。
ex: Jumping into a river to save a stranger, even if you might drown.
pit: Altruism vs. prosocial behavior: altruism has no external reward; prosocial includes any helpful act (even if paid). True altruism is debated.
note: Exam may contrast altruism with egoistic helping.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.prosocial-behavior
def: Any action intended to help others, regardless of motive. / 亲社会行为：任何有意帮助他人的行为，不论动机。
ex: Donating money to charity for a tax deduction is prosocial but not purely altruistic.
pit: All altruism is prosocial, but not all prosocial is altruistic (e.g., helping for reward).
note: Often tested with bystander effect and diffusion of responsibility.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.social-debt
def: The obligation to reciprocate a favor or help received from others. / 社会债务：因接受他人帮助而产生的回报义务。
ex: If a coworker covers your shift, you feel you owe them a favor later.
pit: Social debt is not about monetary debt; it’s psychological obligation.
note: Underlies the reciprocity norm; may appear in cooperation scenarios.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.social-reciprocity-norm
def: Expectation that people will help those who have helped them in return. / 互惠规范：人们应当回报曾帮助过自己的人。
ex: You receive a free sample from a store, then feel pressured to buy something.
pit: Reciprocity norm is about returning favors, not just general kindness.
note: Used in compliance strategies (e.g., “door-in-the-face” technique).

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.social-responsibility-norm
def: Expectation that people should help others who are dependent or in need, without expectation of return. / 社会责任规范：人们应当帮助那些依赖或需要帮助的人，不图回报。
ex: Stopping to help an elderly person cross the street, even if you don’t know them.
pit: Unlike reciprocity norm, this norm applies even when you cannot be repaid.
note: Often applies to helping strangers in emergencies.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.bystander-effect
def: Phenomenon where individuals are less likely to help in an emergency when other people are present. / 旁观者效应：他人在场时个体更不愿在紧急情况下提供帮助。
ex: A person collapses on a busy street; fewer people help than if only one bystander was there.
pit: The effect is due to diffusion of responsibility and pluralistic ignorance, not apathy.
note: Classic research by Darley & Latané; key for FRQ on helping behavior.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.situational-variables
def: Environmental factors that influence behavior, such as number of bystanders, ambiguity of situation, or time pressure. / 情境变量：影响行为的环境因素，如旁观者人数、情境模糊性、时间压力等。
ex: In a smoke-filled room, people are less likely to report it if others remain calm (ambiguity).
pit: Situational variables are different from dispositional (personality) variables; exam often contrasts them.
note: Key to understanding bystander effect and conformity.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-3.attentional-variables
def: Factors that affect whether a person notices an event, such as distraction, focus, or cognitive load. / 注意变量：影响个体是否注意到某事件的因素，如分心、注意力集中程度或认知负荷。
ex: A person wearing headphones is less likely to notice a car accident nearby.
pit: Attentional variables are a subset of situational variables specifically about noticing.
note: Explains why helping decreases when people are preoccupied.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.psychodynamic-theory
def: Personality theory emphasizing unconscious drives, conflicts, and childhood experiences / 强调无意识驱力、冲突及童年经历的人格理论
ex: Freud’s iceberg model: conscious mind is tip; unconscious holds repressed urges
pit: Not just Freud—includes neo-Freudians like Jung, Adler, Horney
note: Know that psychodynamic is broader than Freud’s psychoanalysis; AP often contrasts with humanistic

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.unconscious-processes
def: Mental activities outside conscious awareness that influence behavior / 意识之外影响行为的心理活动
ex: Slip of the tongue (Freudian slip) revealing hidden thought
pit: Confusing with nonconscious (e.g., breathing) – unconscious is repressed, dynamic
note: Core of psychodynamic theory; test may ask how it differs from cognitive unconscious

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.ego-defense-mechanisms
def: Unconscious strategies the ego uses to reduce anxiety from conflicts / 自我缓解冲突焦虑的无意识策略
ex: Using rationalization to justify a failure
pit: All defense mechanisms operate unconsciously – not deliberate coping
note: AP loves matching examples to specific mechanisms; know subtypes

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.denial
def: Refusing to accept reality to avoid anxiety / 拒绝接受现实以避免焦虑
ex: Smoker insisting “I won’t get lung cancer”
pit: Not simply lying – person genuinely believes it
note: Often first defense; paired with addiction scenarios

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.displacement
def: Shifting an impulse from a threatening target to a safer one / 将冲动从危险对象转向安全对象
ex: Angry at boss, yells at spouse instead
pit: Different from sublimation (healthy, socially acceptable)
note: Common “kick the dog” example on AP

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.projection
def: Attributing one’s own unacceptable feelings to others / 将自己的不可接受感受归咎于他人
ex: Cheater accuses partner of cheating
pit: Not same as empathic projection (good guess)
note: Classic “pot calling the kettle black”

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.rationalization
def: Creating logical excuses for unreasonable behavior / 为不合理行为编造逻辑借口
ex: Student blames teacher for failing after not studying
pit: Confusing with denial – rationalization explains, denial ignores
note: Often includes “sour grapes” or “sweet lemon”

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.reaction-formation
def: Behaving opposite to true, anxiety-provoking feelings / 表现出与真实焦虑感受相反的行为
ex: Homophobic person had/has same-gender attraction
pit: Not ordinary hypocrisy – unconscious reversal
note: Extreme, exaggerated opposite behavior is clue

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.regression
def: Retreating to an earlier stage of development under stress / 压力下退回到更早发展阶段
ex: Adult throwing a tantrum like a child
pit: Not always childish – any earlier behavior pattern
note: Think “temporary backslide” under stress

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.repression
def: Blocking threatening memories from conscious awareness / 将威胁性记忆阻拦在意识之外
ex: Forgetting a traumatic event but anxiety remains
pit: Not “suppression” (deliberate); repression is automatic
note: Freud’s most basic defense; foundation for other mechanisms

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.sublimation
def: Defense mechanism where unacceptable impulses are channeled into socially acceptable behaviors / 将不被接受的冲动转化为社会认可行为的心理防御机制
ex: Aggressive urges channeled into playing competitive sports / 将攻击冲动转化为竞技运动
pit: Often confused with displacement (which redirects to a different target); sublimation transforms the impulse itself / 常与"替代"混淆；升华是转化冲动本身而非目标
note: Freud's most "healthy" defense mechanism; key example on AP essays / 弗洛伊德最"健康"的防御机制，AP论述题常见

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.projective-tests
def: Personality assessments using ambiguous stimuli to uncover unconscious thoughts and feelings / 通过模糊刺激揭示无意识想法和感受的人格测验
ex: Rorschach inkblot test, Thematic Apperception Test (TAT) / 罗夏墨迹测验、主题统觉测验
pit: Low reliability and validity; critics say they lack scientific rigor / 信效度较低，批评者认为缺乏科学严谨性
note: Strongly associated with psychodynamic theory; AP may ask for examples and limitations / 与精神动力学理论紧密相关，AP可能要求举例并说明局限

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.preconscious-mind
def: Level of consciousness containing thoughts and memories that can be easily brought to awareness / 包含可轻易被唤回意识的想法和记忆的意识层面
ex: Your phone number, what you ate for breakfast / 你的电话号码、早餐吃了什么
pit: Confused with unconscious (repressed, inaccessible); preconscious is recallable / 易与无意识（被压抑、无法触及）混淆；前意识可回忆
note: Freud's topographic model: conscious → preconscious → unconscious / 弗洛伊德地形模型：意识→前意识→无意识

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.unconscious-mind
def: Reservoir of thoughts, memories, and desires outside of conscious awareness that influence behavior / 意识之外影响行为的思想、记忆和欲望的储存库
ex: Repressed childhood trauma affecting adult relationships / 被压抑的童年创伤影响成年后人际关系
pit: Cannot be directly observed; inferred from slips, dreams, free association / 无法直接观察，通过口误、梦境、自由联想推断
note: Central concept in psychoanalysis; AP often tests with defense mechanisms / 精神分析核心概念，AP常与防御机制一起考查

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.humanistic-psychology
def: Perspective emphasizing inherent goodness, free will, and self-actualization / 强调人性本善、自由意志和自我实现的心理观
ex: Maslow's hierarchy of needs, Rogers' person-centered therapy / 马斯洛需求层次、罗杰斯人本疗法
pit: Criticized for being too optimistic and unscientific; concepts hard to measure / 被批评过于乐观且不科学；概念难以测量
note: Third force after behaviorism and psychoanalysis; AP contrast with deterministic views / 行为主义和精神分析之后的第三势力；AP强调与决定论观点的对比

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.unconditional-regard
def: Acceptance and love given without conditions, regardless of behavior / 无条件给予的接纳和爱，不因行为表现而改变
ex: A therapist's nonjudgmental acceptance of a client's feelings / 治疗师对来访者感受的非评判性接纳
pit: Not the same as permissiveness; Rogers still set limits but maintained regard / 不等于放任；罗杰斯仍设限但保持尊重
note: Key for fostering self-actualization in Rogers' theory; AP may contrast with conditional regard / 罗杰斯理论中促进自我实现的关键，AP常与有条件关注对比

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-4.self-actualizing-tendency
def: Innate drive to fulfill one's potential and become the best version of oneself / 实现自身潜能、成为最佳自我的先天动力
ex: A person pursuing creative expression, personal growth, and meaning / 一个人追求创造性表达、个人成长和意义
pit: Confused with self-actualization (the end state); tendency is the drive / 易与自我实现（终点状态）混淆；倾向是驱动力
note: Central to both Maslow and Rogers; AP focus on humanistic view of motivation / 马斯洛和罗杰斯的核心概念；AP关注人本主义动机观

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.social-cognitive-theory
def: Personality theory emphasizing learning and cognition in social context, with reciprocal influence / 强调社会情境中学习与认知相互作用的人格理论
ex: Bandura's Bobo doll study showing observational learning of aggression / 班杜拉波波玩偶研究展示攻击行为的观察学习
pit: Underestimates unconscious and emotional factors; criticized as too mechanical / 低估无意识和情感因素；被批评过于机械
note: Bandura's key contribution; AP often combines with reciprocal determinism / 班杜拉重要贡献；AP常与交互决定论结合

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.reciprocal-determinism
def: Mutual influence among behavior, internal factors (thoughts/feelings), and environment / 行为、内在因素（思想/情感）和环境三者相互影响
ex: A confident student (cognition) participates in class (behavior), gains praise (environment), boosting confidence / 自信的学生参与课堂，获得表扬，进一步增加自信
pit: Not one-way cause; all three factors constantly interact / 不是单向因果；三者持续互动
note: Bandura's model; AP may ask to explain a scenario using all three components / 班杜拉模型；AP可能要求用三个成分解释情景

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.self-concept
def: All beliefs, thoughts, and feelings about oneself; one's sense of identity / 关于自我的一切信念、想法和感受；自我认同感
ex: "I am a hardworking and friendly person" / "我是一个勤奋友善的人"
pit: Not the same as self-esteem (evaluation); self-concept is descriptive / 不同于自尊（评价性）；自我概念是描述性的
note: Key in Rogers' humanistic theory; incongruence between self-concept and ideal self leads to anxiety / 罗杰斯人本主义关键概念；自我概念与理想自我不一致导致焦虑

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.self-efficacy
def: Belief in one's ability to succeed in specific situations or accomplish a task / 对自己在特定情境中成功能力的信念
ex: A student who believes she can ace an exam studies harder and performs better
pit: Don't confuse with self-esteem; self-efficacy is task-specific, not global evaluation
note: Core of Bandura's social-cognitive theory; key for predicting behavior

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.self-esteem
def: Overall subjective sense of personal worth or value / 对自身整体价值的感受
ex: Feeling good about yourself after receiving praise
pit: Not the same as self-efficacy (which is task-specific); high self-esteem ≠ high achievement
note: Frequent FRQ contrast with self-efficacy; influenced by feedback and success

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.trait-theories
def: Approaches that describe personality as a set of stable, enduring characteristics / 将人格描述为一组稳定、持久特征的学说
ex: Allport's cardinal, central, secondary traits; Cattell's 16PF
pit: Trait theories describe, not explain; don't confuse with type theories (e.g., Type A/B)
note: Basis for Big Five; test often asks to distinguish trait vs. social-cognitive

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.big-five-theory
def: Five broad dimensions of personality: openness, conscientiousness, extraversion, agreeableness, neuroticism (OCEAN) / 人格五大维度：开放性、尽责性、外向性、宜人性、神经质（OCEAN）
ex: Someone high in conscientiousness is organized and reliable
pit: Neuroticism = emotional instability; note "emotional stability" is the opposite pole
note: Most empirically supported trait model; FRQ classic

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.agreeableness
def: Tendency to be cooperative, compassionate, and trusting vs. suspicious and antagonistic / 合作、有同情心、信任 vs. 怀疑、对立
ex: A person who volunteers and avoids arguments
pit: High agreeableness is not same as low extraversion; distinct dimension
note: One of Big Five; high = friendly, low = critical

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.extraversion
def: Tendency to be sociable, outgoing, and energetic vs. reserved and solitary / 外向、社交活跃 vs. 内向、独处
ex: Someone who enjoys parties and meeting new people
pit: Extraversion is a spectrum; "ambiversion" exists but not on AP
note: Opposite is introversion; linked to positive emotion

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.conscientiousness
def: Tendency to be organized, disciplined, and dependable vs. careless and impulsive / 有条理、自律、可靠 vs. 粗心、冲动
ex: A student who always meets deadlines and keeps a tidy workspace
pit: Not same as agreeableness; conscientiousness predicts academic/work success
note: Strongest Big Five predictor of life outcomes

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.openness-to-experience
def: Tendency to be imaginative, curious, and open-minded vs. conventional and cautious / 富有想象力、好奇、开放 vs. 传统、谨慎
ex: Someone who loves trying new foods and traveling to unfamiliar places
pit: Not same as intelligence; correlates with creativity
note: Often highest in artists and innovators

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.emotional-stability
def: Tendency to be calm, secure, and resilient vs. anxious, moody, and vulnerable (low neuroticism) / 情绪稳定、平静、有韧性 vs. 焦虑、情绪化（低神经质）
ex: A person who stays composed during a crisis
pit: On Big Five, "emotional stability" is the opposite of neuroticism; test may use either
note: High stability = low neuroticism; linked to mental health

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.personality-inventories
def: Standardized questionnaires that assess multiple personality traits, often using self-report / 标准化问卷，通过自我报告评估多种人格特质
ex: MMPI-2, NEO-PI, 16PF
pit: Vulnerable to social desirability bias and faking; not projective tests (like Rorschach)
note: MMPI used for clinical diagnosis; Big Five inventories common in research

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-5.factor-analysis
def: A statistical technique used to identify clusters of related items (factors) that underlie a set of test scores or traits. / 将大量相关变量归纳为少数几个潜在因素（特质）的统计方法。
ex: Giving a big personality test and finding that extraversion, sociability, and talkativeness all load on one factor.
pit: Factor analysis does not prove the existence of a trait; it only identifies statistical patterns.
note: Often tested as how trait theorists (e.g., Eysenck, Big Five) identify basic dimensions.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.drive-reduction-theory
def: Theory that motivated behavior arises from physiological needs creating a drive that pushes an organism to reduce that drive. / 生理需要产生驱力，驱力推动行为以降低不适感的理论。
ex: Eating when hungry reduces the hunger drive.
pit: Does not explain why we eat when not hungry (e.g., dessert after a full meal) or engage in risky behavior.
note: Anchor concept for understanding biological motivation; compare with incentives and arousal theory.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.homeostasis
def: The body’s tendency to maintain a stable internal environment (e.g., temperature, blood sugar). / 机体维持内部环境稳定（如体温、血糖）的倾向。
ex: Sweating to cool down when hot.
pit: Often confused with a fixed set point; homeostasis involves dynamic equilibrium.
note: Key to drive-reduction theory; the "ideal state" that drive reduction aims to restore.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.arousal-theory
def: Theory that people are motivated to maintain an optimal level of arousal (alertness, stimulation). / 人们被驱动去达到最佳唤醒水平（警觉、刺激）的理论。
ex: Seeking excitement when bored, or relaxing when overstimulated.
pit: Does not require a physiological need or drive reduction; arousal can be sought for its own sake.
note: Contrast with drive-reduction; often paired with Yerkes-Dodson Law.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.optimal-level-of-arousal
def: The degree of arousal (alertness or stimulation) that leads to the best performance for a given task. / 使某项任务表现最佳的唤醒（警觉或刺激）程度。
ex: A moderate arousal level for an exam; higher arousal for a simple physical task.
pit: It varies per person and per task – not a single universal level.
note: Connect to Yerkes-Dodson Law; test asks "what level works best?"

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.yerkes-dodson-law
def: Principle that performance increases with arousal up to an optimal point, then decreases; simple tasks need higher arousal, complex tasks need lower arousal. / 唤醒水平过低或过高都损害表现；简单任务需要较高唤醒，复杂任务需要较低唤醒的原则。
ex: A calm state helps solve a hard math problem; high energy helps sprint.
pit: Traps: “always medium arousal” is wrong; it depends on task difficulty.
note: Classic inverted-U graph; AP may ask to identify the relationship.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.self-determination-theory
def: Theory that motivation is driven by three innate needs: autonomy, competence, and relatedness. / 人类动机源于自主、胜任和归属三种内在需要的理论。
ex: Enjoying a hobby because you chose it (autonomy) and get good at it (competence) with friends (relatedness).
pit: Not just about intrinsic vs. extrinsic; it explains what sustains intrinsic motivation.
note: Frequently tested as a counterpoint to extrinsic rewards; focus on the three needs.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.intrinsic-motivation
def: Motivation driven by internal rewards such as interest, enjoyment, or personal satisfaction. / 因兴趣、乐趣或个人满足感而行动的动机。
ex: Reading a book because you love the story.
pit: Confusing with "doing something for a grade" – that’s extrinsic if external reward is primary.
note: AP likes to test how extrinsic rewards can undermine intrinsic motivation (overjustification effect).

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.extrinsic-motivation
def: Motivation driven by external rewards or pressures, such as money, grades, praise, or avoiding punishment. / 因外部奖励或压力（金钱、分数、表扬、避免惩罚）而行动的动机。
ex: Studying only to get an A.
pit: Not always bad; it can be effective, but may reduce intrinsic interest over time.
note: Paired with intrinsic on AP; remember the overjustification effect.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.incentive-theory
def: Theory that behavior is motivated by the pull of external rewards (incentives) and the push of avoiding punishments. / 行为受外部奖励（诱因）的吸引和惩罚的推动的理论。
ex: Working overtime for a bonus.
pit: Different from drive-reduction (which is push from internal need); incentive is pull from external stimulus.
note: Often compared with drive-reduction; test asks which explains behavior when no physiological need exists.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.instincts
def: Innate, fixed patterns of behavior that are species-typical and not learned. / 先天、固定的行为模式，为物种特有，非习得。
ex: Salmon swimming upstream to spawn. / 鲑鱼逆流产卵。
pit: Instincts are rare in humans; most behaviors are influenced by learning. / 人类本能极少，多数行为受学习影响。
note: AP cue: Know that instinct theory is not a primary explanation for human motivation; used more in animal behavior. / AP提示：本能理论并非人类动机主要解释，更多用于动物行为。

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.lewin-s-motivational-conflicts-theory
def: Kurt Lewin’s theory that conflicts arise when competing motivations push or pull an individual, classified as approach-approach, avoidance-avoidance, and approach-avoidance. / 库尔特·勒温的理论：当竞争性动机推拉个体时产生冲突，分为双趋、双避、趋避冲突。
ex: Choosing between studying for an exam or attending a party (approach-approach). / 在准备考试和参加派对之间选择（双趋）。
pit: The theory also includes multiple approach-avoidance (e.g., two goals each with pros and cons). / 理论还包括多重趋避冲突（如两个目标各有优缺点）。
note: AP cue: Be able to identify each type from a scenario. / AP提示：能从情境中辨别每种冲突。

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.approach-approach-conflicts
def: Conflict between two desirable options; choosing one excludes the other. / 在两个想要的选择之间冲突；选一个就会失去另一个。
ex: Deciding between two favorite desserts. / 在两种最爱的甜点间选择。
pit: Usually the easiest conflict to resolve, but can be stressful if equally attractive. / 通常最容易解决，但若同样吸引也会带来压力。
note: AP cue: Recognize that it involves positive goals. / AP提示：识别涉及正面目标。

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.approach-avoidance-conflicts
def: Conflict in which a single goal has both attractive and unattractive aspects. / 同一目标既有吸引又有排斥方面的冲突。
ex: Wanting to adopt a pet (joy) but dreading the responsibility (cost/time). / 想养宠物（快乐）但害怕责任（花费/时间）。
pit: These are the most difficult to resolve and often cause indecision. / 此类最难解决，常导致犹豫不决。
note: AP cue: Look for mixed feelings about one option. / AP提示：查找对同一选项的矛盾感受。

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.avoidance-avoidance-conflicts
def: Conflict between two undesirable options; must choose the lesser of two evils. / 在两个不想要的选择之间冲突；必须两害相权取其轻。
ex: Choosing between a boring job and a stressful job. / 在无聊工作和压力工作之间选择。
pit: People may try to escape entirely (avoid both). / 人们可能试图完全逃避（两者都避开）。
note: AP cue: Identify when both options are negative. / AP提示：识别两个选项均为负面。

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.sensation-seeking-theory
def: Zuckerman’s theory that individuals differ in their need for varied, novel, complex, and intense experiences. / 祖克曼的理论：个体对多样、新颖、复杂和强烈体验的需求不同。
ex: High sensation-seekers enjoy skydiving; low sensation-seekers prefer safe activities. / 高感觉寻求者喜欢跳伞；低感觉寻求者偏好安全活动。
pit: Not the same as “thrill seeking” alone; includes boredom susceptibility, disinhibition, etc. / 不单指“寻求刺激”，还包括易厌倦、去抑制等。
note: AP cue: Recognize it as a personality trait related to motivation. / AP提示：将其视为与动机相关的人格特质。

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.thrill-seeking
def: One dimension of sensation seeking: desire for exciting, risky activities. / 感觉寻求的一个维度：对刺激、冒险活动的渴望。
ex: Bungee jumping, fast driving. / 蹦极、高速驾驶。
pit: Thrill seeking is a component, not the whole theory. / 寻求刺激只是一个组成部分，非整个理论。
note: AP cue: Often tested as part of sensation seeking. / AP提示：常作为感觉寻求的一部分考察。

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.adventure-seeking
def: Similar to thrill seeking; seeking novel, unusual, and dangerous experiences. / 类似于寻求刺激；寻求新奇、不寻常和危险体验。
ex: Hiking in remote wilderness alone. / 独自在偏远荒野徒步。
pit: May overlap with thrill seeking; AP may use them interchangeably. / 可能与寻求刺激重叠；AP考试中可能互换使用。
note: AP cue: Not a separate technical term; part of sensation seeking. / AP提示：非独立术语，属感觉寻求部分。

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.disinhibition
def: Tendency to seek social and sexual release through activities like drinking, spending, or unconventional sex. / 通过饮酒、挥霍或非传统性行为来寻求社交和性释放的倾向。
ex: Going to wild parties, excessive gambling. / 参加狂野派对、过度赌博。
pit: “Disinhibition” in this context is about sensation seeking, not classic disinhibition (e.g., in frontal lobe damage). / 此处的“去抑制”指感觉寻求，非经典的去抑制（如额叶损伤）。
note: AP cue: One of four sensation-seeking subscales (with thrill/adventure seeking, experience seeking, boredom susceptibility). / AP提示：感觉寻求四个子量表之一（寻求刺激/冒险、寻求经验、易厌倦）。

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.boredom-susceptibility
def: Aversion to repetitive or routine experiences; easily bored and seeks change. / 厌恶重复或常规体验；容易厌倦并寻求变化。
ex: Switching jobs frequently because of monotony. / 因单调而频繁换工作。
pit: High boredom susceptibility can lead to risk-taking to alleviate monotony. / 高易厌倦性可能导致冒险以缓解单调。
note: AP cue: Another subscale of sensation seeking; linked to low tolerance for routine. / AP提示：感觉寻求的另一个子量表；与对常规的低容忍相关。

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.hunger
def: The physiological state of needing food, triggered by cues like low blood sugar or empty stomach. / 饥饿：由低血糖或空腹等信号触发的需要进食的生理状态。
ex: Feeling hungry after skipping breakfast.
pit: Hunger is not solely due to stomach contractions; hormones like ghrelin also play a major role.
note: Often tested with drive-reduction theory and the role of the hypothalamus.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-6.satiety
def: The feeling of being full and no longer needing to eat. / 饱腹感：感到吃饱了、不再需要进食的感觉。
ex: Stopping eating after a large meal.
pit: Satiety is not immediate; it takes about 20 minutes for signals to reach the brain.
note: Key concept for understanding obesity and eating disorders.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-7.affect
def: The broad range of feelings that humans experience, including emotions and moods. / 情感：人类体验到的广泛感受，包括情绪和心境。
ex: Feeling happy, sad, or anxious.
pit: Affect is often confused with mood; affect is more immediate and intense, while mood is longer-lasting.
note: Distinguish from emotion; affect is the umbrella term.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-7.physiological-experiences
def: Bodily responses during emotion, such as increased heart rate, sweating, or trembling. / 生理体验：情绪中的身体反应，如心跳加快、出汗或颤抖。
ex: Racing heart when scared.
pit: The same physiological arousal can be present in different emotions (e.g., fear and excitement).
note: Important for James-Lange theory: emotion follows physiological arousal.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-7.cognitive-experiences
def: The mental interpretation and labeling of a situation that contributes to emotion. / 认知体验：对情境的心理解释和标记，影响情绪。
ex: Thinking “this is dangerous” leads to fear.
pit: Cognition can occur before or after physiological arousal; different theories disagree.
note: Key to Schachter-Singer two-factor theory: arousal + cognitive label = emotion.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-7.cognitive-label
def: The mental interpretation given to physiological arousal in a specific context, shaping which emotion is felt. / 认知标签：在特定情境下对生理唤醒的心理解释，决定感受到哪种情绪。
ex: In Schachter-Singer study, arousal + angry confederate = anger; arousal + happy confederate = euphoria.
pit: Cognitive label is not just naming the emotion; it’s the interpretation of the cause.
note: Essential for understanding two-factor theory and misattribution of arousal.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-7.facial-feedback-hypothesis
def: The idea that facial expressions can influence emotional experience. / 面部反馈假说：面部表情可以影响情绪体验。
ex: Smiling makes you feel happier.
pit: It does not say that facial expressions are the sole cause of emotion, but they contribute.
note: Often tested with studies where participants hold a pen in their teeth (smile) vs. lips (pout).

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-7.broaden-and-build-theory-of-emotion
def: Positive emotions broaden thought-action repertoires and build lasting personal resources. / 情绪拓展-建构理论：积极情绪能拓宽思维-行动库，并建立持久的个人资源。
ex: Joy encourages play, which builds social bonds; interest encourages exploration, which builds knowledge.
pit: This theory does not apply to negative emotions, which narrow focus.
note: Proposed by Barbara Fredrickson; key for understanding the function of positive emotions.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-7.cognitive-appraisal
def: The process by which a person evaluates a situation and its relevance to their well-being, influencing emotional response. / 认知评价：个体评估情境及其与自身福祉相关性的过程，影响情绪反应。
ex: Appraising a snake as dangerous leads to fear; appraising it as harmless leads to calm.
pit: Appraisal is not the same as cognitive label; appraisal occurs earlier, label is later.
note: Central to Lazarus’s cognitive-mediational theory; primary and secondary appraisal.

@@ ap-psychology.u4.t4-7.display-rules
def: Cultural norms that dictate how and when emotions should be expressed. / 表现规则：决定何时以及如何表达情绪的文化规范。
ex: In some cultures, men are taught not to cry in public.
pit: Display rules affect expression, not the emotion itself.
note: Important for understanding cross-cultural differences in emotional expression.

@@ emotional-elicitors
def: Triggers that evoke specific emotions / 引发特定情绪的刺激
ex: Seeing a snake elicits fear.
pit: Confusing elicitors with the emotion itself; they are cues.
note: Know which elicitor leads to which emotion.

@@ health-psychology
def: Study of how psychological factors affect health and illness / 研究心理因素如何影响健康与疾病
ex: How stress impacts immune function.
pit: Not limited to mental illness; includes physical health.
note: Often tied to stress and coping models.

@@ stress
def: Body's response to demands (stressors) / 身体对需求（压力源）的反应
ex: Feeling overwhelmed before an exam.
pit: Confusing stress (response) with stressors (cause).
note: Distinguish from eustress vs. distress.

@@ hypertension
def: Chronic high blood pressure / 慢性高血压
ex: Often linked to chronic stress.
pit: Thinking it's purely physical; stress plays a key role.
note: Classic example of stress-related illness.

@@ immune-suppression
def: Reduced immune function due to stress / 因压力导致的免疫系统功能下降
ex: Students get sick more often during finals.
pit: Confusing with autoimmune disorders.
note: Core concept in psychoneuroimmunology.

@@ stressors
def: Events or conditions that cause stress / 引起压力的事件或条件
ex: Major life changes, daily hassles.
pit: Not distinguishing stressors from stress response.
note: Categorized as acute or chronic.

@@ eustress-motivating
def: Positive stress that motivates growth / 积极压力，激发成长
ex: Excitement before a performance.
pit: Thinking all stress is bad.
note: Key to distinguish from distress.

@@ distress-debilitating
def: Negative stress that impairs functioning / 消极压力，损害功能
ex: Chronic anxiety causing health problems.
pit: Overlapping with anxiety disorders.
note: Focus on health outcomes.

@@ adverse-childhood-experiences-aces
def: Traumatic events before age 18 affecting health / 18岁前创伤事件影响健康
ex: Abuse, neglect, household dysfunction.
pit: Not only physical abuse; includes emotional.
note: High ACEs linked to chronic disease.

@@ general-adaptation-syndrome-gas
def: Selye's three-stage stress response: alarm, resistance, exhaustion / 塞利的三阶段压力反应：警觉、抵抗、衰竭
ex: Immediate alarm, then coping, then burnout.
pit: Skipping stages or confusing order.
note: Classic AP question on stages.

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-1.alarm-reaction-phase
def: The first stage of Selye's GAS; immediate sympathetic nervous system activation / 塞利一般适应综合征第一期：交感神经立刻激活（警觉反应）
ex: Hearing a loud bang; heart rate spikes, adrenaline surges / 听到巨响后心跳加速、肾上腺素激增
pit: Confusing “alarm” with long-term stress; it’s the initial shock / 易误作长期压力，实为初始瞬间反应
note: AP cue – GAS stage sequence (alarm → resistance → exhaustion)

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-1.resistance-phase
def: Second GAS stage; body copes adaptively but resources are depleted / 一般适应综合征第二期：身体尝试适应，但资源逐渐消耗
ex: After exam week, you function but feel tired and irritable / 考试周后仍能学习，但易怒、疲惫
pit: Thinking resistance is stress-free; actually high arousal continues / 误以为无压力，实则持续高唤醒
note: AP cue – opposite of exhaustion; if stress persists → exhaustion phase

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-1.flight-flight-freeze-response
def: The body’s automatic response to threat: fight, flight, or freeze / 对威胁的自动反应：战斗、逃跑或僵住
ex: Seeing a snake: you either attack, run, or stand still / 见蛇：攻击、逃跑或呆立不动
pit: Missing “freeze” in the classic fight-or-flight; freeze is adaptive / 遗漏“僵住”，实为适应性反应
note: AP cue – sympathetic activation; parasympathetic later restores balance

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-1.exhaustion-phase
def: Third GAS stage; resources depleted leading to illness, burnout / 一般适应综合征第三期：资源耗尽，引发疾病或倦怠
ex: Chronic work stress leads to high blood pressure / 长期工作压力导致高血压
pit: Not just feeling tired; it’s pathological / 不只是累，是病理状态
note: AP cue – final stage; linked to psychophysiological disorders

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-1.tend-and-befriend-theory
def: Female typical stress response: nurture children (tend) & seek social support (befriend) / 女性典型压力反应：照料孩子（照料）并寻求社会支持（交友）
ex: In crisis, women call friends; men often isolate / 危机时女性打电话给朋友，男性常独处
pit: Assumed universal; but shaped by culture & oxytocin / 误认为普遍，实则受文化和催产素影响
note: AP cue – alternative to fight-or-flight; linked to oxytocin

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-1.problem-focused-coping
def: Directly changing the stressor or its impact / 直接改变压力源或其影响
ex: You study harder after failing a test / 考试失败后加倍学习
pit: Confused with emotion‑focused; problem‑focused acts on cause / 与情绪导向混淆——问题导向针对原因
note: AP cue – effective when controllable; often paired with emotion‑focused

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-1.emotion-focused-coping
def: Managing emotional distress, not the stressor itself / 管理情绪痛苦，不改变压力源
ex: Meditation after a breakup / 分手后冥想
pit: Seen as inferior; but essential when stressor is uncontrollable / 被视为低级，实则不可控时必需
note: AP cue – includes denial, reappraisal, support seeking

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.positive-psychology
def: Scientific study of human flourishing & strengths / 研究人类幸福与优势的科学
ex: Researching gratitude interventions or character strengths / 研究感恩干预或性格优势
pit: Not “positive thinking” only; includes meaning, resilience / 不只是积极思考，包含意义、韧性
note: AP cue – Martin Seligman; contrasts with disease model

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.well-being
def: Positive state; includes life satisfaction, positive emotions, purpose / 积极状态：生活满意、积极情绪、人生意义
ex: Having close relationships and feeling your work matters / 拥有亲密关系且感觉工作有意义
pit: Equating with happiness only; well‑being is multidimensional / 等同于快乐——幸福是多元的
note: AP cue – hedonic (pleasure) vs. eudaimonic (meaning)

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.resilience
def: Ability to bounce back from adversity / 从逆境中恢复的能力
ex: A child from poverty who becomes successful / 贫困孩子最终成功
pit: Not just “being tough”; involves support & coping skills / 不只是“坚强”，需要支持和应对技能
note: AP cue – modifiable; can be built through therapy & habits

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.positive-emotions
def: Pleasant emotional states that broaden thinking and build resources / 积极情绪：拓宽思维并建立资源的愉悦情绪状态
ex: Joy, interest, contentment
pit: Not just happiness; includes many positive feelings
note: Fredrickson's broaden-and-build theory

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.gratitude
def: Appreciation for what one has / 感恩：对所拥有事物的欣赏
ex: Thanking a friend for help
pit: Not just saying thanks; involves deep feeling
note: Linked to higher well-being

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.positive-subjective-experiences
def: Internal positive states like joy, flow, or contentment / 主观积极体验：如喜悦、心流或满足等内在积极状态
ex: Feeling absorbed in a hobby
pit: Not same as objective success
note: Core of positive psychology

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.subjective-well-being
def: Self-reported happiness and life satisfaction / 主观幸福感：自我报告的快乐与生活满意度
ex: Rating life as 8/10
pit: Not just absence of negative emotions
note: Often called "happiness" in research

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.signature-strengths
def: Your top personal character strengths (VIA classification) / 标志性优势：个人最突出的品格优势（VIA分类）
ex: Curiosity, kindness, perseverance
pit: Not skills; are moral traits
note: Using them boosts well-being

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.virtues
def: Broad core moral qualities valued across cultures (wisdom, courage, humanity, justice, temperance, transcendence) / 美德：跨文化珍视的广泛核心道德品质（智慧、勇气、人道、正义、节制、超越）
ex: Wisdom includes creativity and curiosity
pit: Not the same as strengths; virtues umbrella strengths
note: Part of VIA classification

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.positive-objective-experiences
def: External positive life events or circumstances / 客观积极经历：外部积极生活事件或环境
ex: Winning an award, good health
pit: Less impact on happiness than subjective view
note: Hedonic adaptation reduces effect

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.happiness
def: Often used interchangeably with subjective well-being; a state of positive affect and life satisfaction / 幸福：常与主观幸福感互换；积极情绪与生活满意的状态
ex: Feeling joyful and satisfied with life
pit: Not just smiling; includes meaning
note: Two traditions: hedonic (pleasure) vs eudaimonic (meaning)

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.categories-of-virtues-wisdom-courage-humanity-justice-temperance-transcendence
def: Six broad virtue categories from positive psychology (each contains multiple character strengths) / 美德类别：积极心理学中的六大美德范畴（每类含多种品格优势）
ex: Justice includes leadership, fairness, teamwork
pit: Do not memorize all strengths; know categories
note: Rooted in cross-cultural research

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-2.posttraumatic-growth
def: Positive psychological change experienced after a struggle with highly challenging life circumstances / 创伤后成长：在应对极困难生活挑战后经历的积极心理变化
ex: Greater appreciation for life after a loss
pit: Not the same as resilience (bouncing back) – it’s growth beyond baseline
note: Common domains: relationships, personal strength, new possibilities

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.dysfunction
def: Behavior or mental process that disrupts daily life and impairs normal functioning / 行为或心理过程扰乱日常生活，损害正常功能
ex: A person with OCD unable to leave home due to repeated hand-washing rituals / 强迫症患者因反复洗手仪式无法出门
pit: Dysfunction alone does not define disorder; must cause distress or harm / 仅功能失调不足以定义障碍，还需导致痛苦或伤害
note: Part of the "4 Ds" (Dysfunction, Distress, Deviance, Danger) used to define psychological disorders / 用于定义心理障碍的“四D”之一

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.distress
def: Negative emotional state or suffering caused by a condition / 由某种状况引起的负面情绪状态或痛苦
ex: Severe anxiety that prevents a student from taking exams / 严重焦虑导致学生无法参加考试
pit: Distress must be significant; temporary sadness is not a disorder / 痛苦须显著，短暂悲伤不算障碍
note: Key criterion for a mental disorder; see also "maladaptive" / 心理障碍的关键标准；另见“适应不良”

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.deviation-from-the-social-norm
def: Behavior that differs from what is accepted or expected in a society / 与社会接受或期望的行为相偏离
ex: Hearing voices when no one is speaking (hallucination) / 无人说话时听到声音（幻觉）
pit: Not all deviations are disorders (e.g., genius, eccentricity) / 并非所有偏离都是障碍（如天才、古怪）
note: Used cautiously; cultural norms vary widely / 谨慎使用；文化规范差异巨大

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.cultural-societal-norms
def: Shared rules and expectations of behavior within a specific culture or society / 特定文化或社会中共享的行为规则和期望
ex: In some cultures, hearing ancestors' advice is normal, not pathological / 在某些文化中，听到祖先的建议是正常的，非病态
pit: What is normal in one culture may be abnormal in another; avoid ethnocentrism / 一种文化中的正常可能被另一种视为异常；避免种族中心主义
note: DSM-5 emphasizes cultural context in diagnosis / DSM-5 强调诊断中的文化背景

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.stigma
def: Negative attitudes and beliefs that discredit and marginalize people with mental disorders / 贬低并边缘化心理障碍患者的负面态度和信念
ex: Believing someone with depression is "just lazy" / 认为抑郁症患者“只是懒惰”
pit: Stigma can prevent people from seeking help / 污名化可能阻止人们寻求帮助
note: Can lead to discrimination; AP exam often links to treatment barriers / 可导致歧视；AP考试常联系治疗障碍

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.racism
def: Prejudice and discrimination based on race or ethnicity / 基于种族或民族的偏见和歧视
ex: Assuming a person of color is more dangerous and calling police unfairly / 假设有色人种更危险并不公平报警
pit: Implicit bias is also a form of racism / 内隐偏见也是种族主义的一种形式
note: Can affect mental health diagnosis and treatment disparities / 可影响心理健康诊断和治疗差异

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.sexism
def: Prejudice and discrimination based on gender, typically against women / 基于性别的偏见和歧视，通常针对女性
ex: Believing that women are too emotional to be good leaders / 认为女性过于情绪化而不适合领导
pit: Can be overt or subtle (e.g., microaggressions) / 可明显或隐性（如微攻击）
note: Related to gender bias in diagnosis (e.g., histrionic vs. antisocial) / 与诊断中的性别偏见相关（如表演型 vs. 反社会型）

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.ageism
def: Prejudice and discrimination based on age, typically against older adults / 基于年龄的偏见和歧视，通常针对老年人
ex: Assuming all elderly people have dementia when they forget something / 当老人忘记某事时假设其患有痴呆症
pit: Can also affect youth (e.g., assuming teenagers are irresponsible) / 也可影响年轻人（如认为青少年不负责任）
note: May lead to underdiagnosis of mental disorders in elderly / 可能导致老年人心理障碍诊断不足

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.discrimination
def: Unfair treatment of individuals based on their group membership / 基于个人所属群体而给予的不公平对待
ex: Refusing to rent an apartment to someone with a mental illness / 拒绝将公寓租给有心理障碍的人
pit: Discrimination is behavior, prejudice is attitude; not always conscious / 歧视是行为，偏见是态度；不一定有意识
note: Often results from stigma; protected by laws like ADA / 常源于污名化；受ADA等法律保护

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.diagnostic-and-statistical-manual-of-mental-disorders-dsm
def: The official classification system for mental disorders, used by clinicians and researchers / 用于临床和研究的精神障碍官方分类系统
ex: DSM-5-TR lists criteria for major depressive disorder / DSM-5-TR列出重性抑郁障碍的诊断标准
pit: DSM is descriptive, not explanatory; does not cover every cultural variation / DSM是描述性的，非解释性；未涵盖所有文化差异
note: Updated regularly; current version is DSM-5-TR (2022). AP exam asks about its purpose and limitations / 定期更新；当前版本为DSM-5-TR（2022年）。AP考试会问其目的和局限性

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.international-classification-of-mental-disorders-icd
def: A global diagnostic system for mental disorders published by WHO / 世界卫生组织发布的全球精神疾病诊断系统
ex: ICD-11 codes like “6A20” for schizophrenia / 例如 ICD-11 中“6A20”代表精神分裂症
pit: Often confused with DSM; ICD is WHO, DSM is APA / 容易与DSM混淆；ICD属WHO，DSM属APA
note: AP mentions ICD as alternative to DSM; focus on comparison / AP提到ICD是DSM的替代方案，注意比较两者

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.eclectic-approach
def: Combining multiple perspectives to treat disorders / 结合多种视角治疗心理障碍
ex: Using medication (biological) and CBT (cognitive) together / 同时使用药物（生物学）和认知行为疗法
pit: Not just “using everything”; must be thoughtfully integrated / 不是“什么都用”，须有整合的逻辑
note: AP questions often test which perspectives are combined / AP常考哪些视角被结合使用

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.behavioral-perspective
def: Views disorders as learned through conditioning and observation / 认为障碍是通过条件作用和观察学习得来的
ex: A phobia of dogs after being bitten (classical conditioning) / 被狗咬后产生恐惧症（经典条件作用）
pit: Ignores thoughts and biology; purely environmental / 忽略思维和生物学，纯粹环境论
note: AP compare with cognitive perspective; know therapies (exposure) / AP对比认知视角；熟知疗法（如暴露疗法）

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.maladaptive-learned-associations
def: Harmful connections between stimuli and responses learned via experience / 通过经验习得的刺激与反应之间的有害联结
ex: Fear of all cars after a car accident / 车祸后害怕所有汽车
pit: Not just any association – must be harmful or dysfunctional / 不是任何联结，必须是有害或功能失调的
note: Key in behavioral explanations of anxiety disorders / 是行为解释焦虑障碍的关键

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.humanistic-perspective
def: Emphasizes self-actualization blocked by conditions of worth / 强调自我实现被价值条件所阻碍
ex: Eating disorder due to extreme need for parental approval / 因极度需要父母认可而患进食障碍
pit: Overly optimistic; hard to test scientifically / 过于乐观，难以科学验证
note: Rarely tested alone; often paired with Rogers’ therapy / 很少单独考，常与罗杰斯疗法一起出题

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.cognitive-perspective
def: Focuses on faulty thinking patterns (e.g., negative schemas) as cause of disorders / 关注错误思维模式（如消极图式）是障碍成因
ex: Depression from interpreting failure as “I’ll always fail” / 将失败解释为“我总失败”导致抑郁
pit: Confused with behavioral; cognitive is about thoughts, not reinforcement / 与行为视角混淆；认知关注思想，而非强化
note: AP common for depression & anxiety; know cognitive triad / AP常见于抑郁和焦虑；熟知“认知三角”

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.psychodynamic-perspective
def: Disorders stem from unconscious conflicts and childhood experiences / 障碍源于无意识冲突和童年经历
ex: OCD as a reaction to repressed aggressive impulses / 强迫症作为对压抑攻击冲动的反应
pit: Hard to test empirically; often seen as outdated / 难以实证检验，常被认为过时
note: AP focuses on defense mechanisms and psychosexual stages / AP关注防御机制和性心理发展阶段

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.evolutionary-perspective
def: Disorders are maladaptive extensions of evolved survival mechanisms / 障碍是进化适应机制的不良延伸
ex: Social anxiety originally helped avoid group rejection / 社交焦虑原本为避免群体排斥
pit: Can be seen as just-so stories; hard to prove / 可能成为“故事解释”，难以证明
note: AP rarely tests; know as a modern perspective / AP很少考，了解为现代视角之一

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.sociocultural-perspective
def: Emphasizes how culture, poverty, discrimination affect mental health / 强调文化、贫困、歧视对心理健康的影响
ex: Higher depression rates in stigmatized minority groups / 被污名化的少数群体抑郁率更高
pit: Not just “environment”; includes norms and social expectations / 不仅是环境，还包括规范和社会期望
note: AP compares with biological; know culture-bound syndromes / AP与生物学视角对比；熟知特定文化综合征

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.biological-perspective
def: Explains disorders through genetics, brain structure, neurotransmitter imbalances / 从遗传、脑结构、神经递质失衡解释障碍
ex: Schizophrenia linked to high dopamine levels / 精神分裂症与多巴胺水平过高有关
pit: Overlooks psychological and social factors / 忽略心理和社会因素
note: AP frequent; know specific neurotransmitters (serotonin, dopamine) / AP高频；熟知特定神经递质（血清素、多巴胺）

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.biopsychosocial-model
def: A model sees disorders as interactions of biological, psychological, social factors / 生物心理社会模型认为障碍是生物、心理、社会因素相互作用结果
ex: Depression from genetic vulnerability (bio) + negative thinking (psych) + poverty (social) / 抑郁来自遗传易感性（生物）+消极思维（心理）+贫困（社会）
pit: Not just listing factors; emphasize their interaction / 不仅是列出因素，强调三者互动
note: Contrasts with medical model; holistic explanation / 与医学模型对比；整体解释

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-3.diathesis-stress-model
def: Disorders develop when a predisposition (diathesis) is triggered by stress / 素质被压力触发时产生障碍
ex: Genetic schizophrenia risk + major life stress → disorder onset / 精神分裂症遗传风险+重大生活压力→发病
pit: Diathesis can be genetic, psychological, or biological / 素质可为遗传、心理或生物
note: Explains why not all at-risk individuals develop disorders / 解释为何有风险者不一定发病

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.neurodevelopmental-disorders
def: Disorders appearing early in development, affecting brain function and behavior / 发育早期出现、影响大脑功能和行为
ex: ADHD, autism spectrum disorder / 注意缺陷多动障碍、自闭症谱系障碍
pit: Not only intellectual disabilities; includes ADHD, ASD / 不限于智力障碍，包括ADHD、ASD
note: Diagnosed in childhood; often persist into adulthood / 儿童期诊断，常持续至成年

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.attention-deficit-hyperactivity-disorder-adhd
def: Neurodevelopmental disorder with inattention, hyperactivity, impulsivity / 以注意力不集中、多动、冲动为特征的神经发育障碍
ex: Child can’t stay seated, interrupts, easily distracted / 不能静坐、打断他人、易分心的儿童
pit: Not just lack of discipline; brain-based disorder / 不是缺乏管教，大脑相关的障碍
note: Treatments: behavioral therapy & stimulant meds / 治疗：行为疗法和兴奋剂药物

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.autism-spectrum-disorder-asd
def: Neurodevelopmental disorder with social communication deficits & repetitive behaviors/interests / 社交沟通缺陷和重复行为/兴趣的神经发育障碍
ex: Avoids eye contact, delayed speech, lines up toys / 避免眼神接触、语言发育迟缓、排列玩具
pit: It’s a spectrum; severity varies widely / 是谱系障碍，严重程度差异大
note: Early intervention improves outcomes; Asperger’s now under ASD / 早期干预改善预后；阿斯伯格现归入ASD

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.schizophrenic-spectrum-disorders
def: Range of psychotic disorders including schizophrenia & schizoaffective disorder / 包括精神分裂症和分裂情感障碍的精神病性障碍谱系
ex: Schizophrenia with hallucinations and delusions / 伴有幻觉和妄想的精神分裂症
pit: Not one disorder; spectrum includes related conditions / 不止一种障碍，谱系包括相关疾病
note: Key positive symptoms: hallucinations, delusions, disorganized speech / 关键阳性症状：幻觉、妄想、言语紊乱

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.delusions
def: False beliefs held despite contradictory evidence / 尽管有相反证据仍坚持的错误信念
ex: Belief that FBI monitors via TV / 认为FBI通过电视监控
pit: Different from hallucinations (sensory); delusions are cognitive / 不同于幻觉（感觉），妄想是认知性的
note: Common in psychosis; types: grandiose, persecutory / 常见于精神病；类型：夸大、被害等

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.hallucinations
def: False sensory experiences without external stimulus / 无外部刺激的虚假感官体验
ex: Hearing voices not present (auditory) / 幻听
pit: Not only visual; can be auditory, tactile, etc. / 不限于视觉，可听觉、触觉等
note: Auditory hallucinations most common in schizophrenia / 幻听在精神分裂症中最常见

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.disorganized-thinking
def: Incoherent, illogical thought processes, often in schizophrenia / 不连贯、不合逻辑的思维过程，常见于精神分裂症
ex: “I’m here because I’m a butterfly” (loose associations) / “我在这因为我是一只蝴蝶”（联想松散）
pit: Manifests in speech; assessed by disorganized speech / 通过言语表现，以言语紊乱评估
note: Positive symptom of schizophrenia / 精神分裂症的阳性症状

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.disorganized-speech
def: Incoherent speech with topic switches or illogicality, reflecting disorganized thinking / 不连贯、话题转换或不合理的言语，反映思维紊乱
ex: “Sky is blue, but my shoe is dreams, so I must fly” (word salad) / “天空蓝，鞋是梦，所以我必须飞”（词语沙拉）
pit: Not just fast talking; breakdown in logical connection / 不只是快，逻辑连接断裂
note: Positive symptom; may include neologisms / 阳性症状；可包括新语症

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.disorganized-motor-behavior
def: Inappropriate or bizarre motor movements (e.g., rocking, grimacing) / 不合理或怪异的运动行为（如摇晃、做鬼脸）
ex: A patient suddenly freezes mid-step for hours
pit: Not just "hyperactivity" – includes underactivity too
note: Key symptom of schizophrenia; often paired with catatonia

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.negative-symptoms
def: Absence or reduction of normal functions / 正常功能的缺失或减少
ex: Flat affect, social withdrawal, anhedonia
pit: Confusing with depression; negative = missing, not bad
note: Harder to treat than positive symptoms; AP exam loves this distinction

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.positive-symptoms
def: Presence of abnormal behaviors or experiences / 异常行为或体验的出现
ex: Hallucinations, delusions, word salad
pit: "Positive" does not mean good; it means added
note: Respond better to antipsychotics; classic schizophrenia signs

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.delusions-of-persecution
def: False belief that one is being targeted/harmed by others / 坚信自己被迫害或伤害
ex: Believing the FBI is following you everywhere
pit: Confusing with paranoia – but this is a specific delusion type
note: Most common delusion type in schizophrenia

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.delusions-of-grandeur
def: False belief of possessing great power, fame, or identity / 坚信自己拥有巨大的权力、名声或身份
ex: Thinking you are Jesus or a secret billionaire
pit: Not just "high self-esteem"; it's extreme and false
note: Common in both schizophrenia and bipolar mania

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.word-salad
def: Jumbled, incoherent speech with words randomly combined / 语词杂拌，词语随机组合，言语混乱
ex: "Colorless green ideas sleep furiously"
pit: Not same as pressured speech (bipolar) – no logical connection
note: A form of disorganized speech; hallmark of schizophrenia

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.catatonia
def: Motor dysfunction ranging from stupor to excited agitation / 运动功能障碍，从木僵到兴奋激动
ex: Maintaining a bizarre pose for hours then suddenly flailing
pit: Catatonia = motor symptoms, not just "freezing"
note: Can occur in mood disorders too, but classic in schizophrenia

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.flat-affect
def: Lack of emotional expression (voice tone, facial expression) / 情感平淡，缺乏情绪表达（语调、面部表情）
ex: Patient describes tragedy with blank face and monotone voice
pit: Not "having no emotions" – just not expressing them
note: Negative symptom; often confused with depression

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.catatonic-stupor
def: Complete immobility and unresponsiveness to environment / 完全不动，对环境无反应
ex: Patient sits frozen, staring, does not blink or speak
pit: Not coma – person is aware but cannot move/speak
note: Subcategory of catatonia; AP may ask to distinguish from waxy flexibility

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.dopamine-hypothesis
def: Excess dopamine activity in brain causes positive symptoms of schizophrenia / 大脑中多巴胺活动过度导致精神分裂症的阳性症状
ex: Antipsychotics block dopamine receptors and reduce hallucinations
pit: Not all symptoms (negative symptoms involve other neurotransmitters)
note: Classic biological explanation for schizophrenia; AP exam favorite

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.depressive-disorders
def: Mood disorders characterized by persistent sadness and loss of interest / 以持续悲伤和兴趣丧失为特征的心境障碍
ex: A person feeling hopeless and exhausted for weeks, unable to enjoy hobbies
pit: Confusing depressive disorders with normal sadness—must meet duration/severity criteria
note: Know the difference between major depressive and persistent depressive disorders on AP exam

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.major-depressive-disorder
def: Severe depressive episodes lasting at least 2 weeks, with five or more symptoms / 重度抑郁发作持续至少两周，出现五或以上症状
ex: Loss of appetite, insomnia, worthlessness, inability to concentrate, suicidal thoughts
pit: Don’t forget “change from previous functioning” and “not due to substances”
note: Classic AP example; distinguish from persistent depressive disorder by duration/intensity

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.persistent-depressive-disorder
def: Milder but chronic depression lasting at least 2 years (1 year in children) / 较轻但慢性抑郁，持续至少两年（儿童为一年）
ex: Feeling “down” most days for years, low energy, poor self-esteem, but still functioning
pit: Often confused with major depressive disorder—key is chronicity (2 years) vs. episodic severity
note: Previously called dysthymia; know the timeline difference for AP

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.bipolar-disorders
def: Mood disorders involving both depressive and manic/hypomanic episodes / 同时有抑郁和躁狂/轻躁狂发作的心境障碍
ex: A person cycles between weeks of deep depression and days of extreme euphoria/irritability
pit: Not just mood swings—episodes are distinct and cause impairment
note: Bipolar I and II are subtypes; distinguish mania vs. hypomania

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.cycling
def: Alternating between depressive and manic/hypomanic episodes / 在抑郁和躁狂/轻躁狂发作之间交替
ex: Two months of depression, then one week of mania, then back to depression
pit: Rapid cycling (4+ episodes/year) is a specifier, not a separate disorder
note: AP focuses on the pattern of mood episodes; don’t confuse with cyclothymia

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.mania
def: Distinct period of abnormally elevated, expansive, or irritable mood, lasting at least 1 week / 持续至少一周的异常高涨、膨胀或易怒情绪
ex: Grandiose plans, talking rapidly, sleeping little, reckless spending
pit: Mania causes significant impairment or hospitalization; hypomania does not
note: Mania defines Bipolar I; know 3+ symptoms (inflated self-esteem, decreased need for sleep, pressured speech, etc.)

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.depression
def: Major depressive episode in bipolar disorder; symptoms same as major depressive disorder / 双相障碍中的重性抑郁发作；症状与重性抑郁障碍相同
ex: In bipolar disorder, the “low” phase includes hopelessness, fatigue, and suicidal thoughts
pit: Don’t assume depression only occurs in unipolar disorders—it’s also part of bipolar
note: Bipolar depression vs. unipolar depression: AP may test that both have similar depressive symptoms

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.bipolar-i-disorder
def: At least one manic episode; depressive episodes common but not required / 至少一次躁狂发作；抑郁发作常见但非必需
ex: A person experiences a week of mania (e.g., spending sprees, grandiose delusions) and later depression
pit: A single manic episode is enough for diagnosis; hypomania does not count
note: Mania is the hallmark; differentiate from Bipolar II by presence of full mania

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.bipolar-ii-disorder
def: At least one hypomanic episode and one major depressive episode; no full mania / 至少一次轻躁狂发作和一次重性抑郁发作；无完整躁狂
ex: Periods of mild euphoria and increased productivity alternating with severe depression
pit: Hypomania is less severe and shorter (≥4 days) than mania; no psychosis/hospitalization
note: AP trap: Bipolar II is not “milder” but has hypomania instead of mania; depressive episodes are often more prominent

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.anxiety-disorders
def: Disorders marked by excessive fear, anxiety, and related behavioral disturbances / 以过度恐惧、焦虑和相关行为紊乱为特征的障碍
ex: Panic attacks, social avoidance, constant worry for months
pit: Anxiety is normal; disorder requires distress/impairment and persistence (e.g., 6+ months)
note: Know the major types (GAD, panic, phobias, social anxiety) and their DSM-5 criteria

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.specific-phobia
def: Marked fear or anxiety about a specific object or situation (e.g., flying, heights) / 对特定对象或情境的显著恐惧或焦虑
ex: Avoiding an elevator because of fear of enclosed spaces
pit: Distinguish from normal fear – phobia causes significant distress/impairment
note: AP exam – often distinguishes specific phobia from agoraphobia and social anxiety

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.acrophobia
def: Specific phobia of heights / 恐高症
ex: Refusing to climb stairs with a glass railing
pit: May be confused with dizziness or vertigo, but acrophobia is primarily psychological fear
note: Classic example of a specific phobia on AP exams

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.arachnophobia
def: Specific phobia of spiders / 蜘蛛恐惧症
ex: Screaming and running from a small spider in the corner
pit: Not every dislike is a phobia – must cause avoidance and major distress
note: Commonly used as an illustrative example of specific phobia

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.agoraphobia
def: Fear of being in situations from which escape might be difficult or help unavailable (e.g., crowds, open spaces) / 对难以逃脱或无法获得帮助的情境的恐惧（如人群、空旷场所）
ex: Being unable to leave home alone for months
pit: Often pairs with panic disorder – but agoraphobia can exist alone
note: AP may test that agoraphobia is not simply “fear of open spaces”

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.panic-disorder
def: Recurrent unexpected panic attacks and persistent fear of future attacks / 反复且意外的惊恐发作，并持续担心未来再次发作
ex: Having sudden racing heart, trembling, fear of dying, then worrying about when it will happen next
pit: Panic attacks can occur in other disorders; panic disorder requires worry about attacks or their consequences
note: Must distinguish from a single panic attack

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.panic-attack
def: Abrupt surge of intense fear or discomfort that peaks within minutes, with physical and cognitive symptoms / 突然爆发的强烈恐惧或不适，几分钟内达高峰，伴生理及认知症状
ex: Palpitations, chills, nausea, feeling of choking
pit: Panic attacks can be expected (e.g., in phobia) or unexpected; they are not a disorder by themselves
note: AP may ask: panic attack ≠ panic disorder

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.ataque-de-nervios
def: Cultural syndrome (Latinx) involving intense emotional upset, screaming, shaking, fainting, sometimes aggression / 拉丁裔文化中的“神经发作”，表现为强烈情绪失控、尖叫、发抖、昏厥
ex: A woman after a family argument suddenly falls to the ground and cannot speak
pit: Often misdiagnosed as panic disorder without considering cultural context
note: AP emphasizes cultural variation in mental disorders

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.social-anxiety-disorder
def: Marked fear of social situations due to possible scrutiny by others, leading to avoidance / 因担心被他人评判而显著害怕社交情境，导致回避
ex: Avoiding eating in public or giving a speech
pit: Not just “shyness” – must cause significant functional impairment
note: AP exam – compare with specific phobia (fear of object vs. social evaluation)

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.taijin-kyofusho
def: Japanese culture-bound syndrome: fear of offending or embarrassing others (e.g., blushing, eye contact) / 日本文化特有的对人恐惧症：担心冒犯或让他人尴尬（如脸红、眼神接触）
ex: A man stays home because he fears his eye contact will make others uncomfortable
pit: Unlike social anxiety (fear for oneself), focuses on harming others
note: AP exam uses this as an example of cultural influence on symptom expression

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.generalized-anxiety-disorder-gad
def: Chronic, excessive worry about numerous events or activities for at least 6 months, hard to control / 持续6个月以上对多种事情过度担忧，难以控制
ex: Worrying daily about job security, health, finances, and minor tasks
pit: Not “just worrying a lot” – must cause distress/impairment, and is not focused on one specific threat
note: AP often tests that GAD has no specific trigger (vs. phobia)

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.obsessive-compulsive-and-related-disorders
def: A group of disorders characterized by unwanted, repetitive thoughts and/or actions. / 以不想要的、重复的想法和/或行为为特征的一组障碍。
ex: OCD, hoarding disorder, body dysmorphic disorder belong here.
pit: Students often confuse these with anxiety disorders; note that OCD has its own category in DSM-5.
note: Recognize that OCD is no longer classified under anxiety disorders in DSM-5.

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.obsessions
def: Persistent, intrusive, unwanted thoughts or urges that cause distress. / 持续侵入、不想要的想法或冲动，引起痛苦。
ex: Fear of contamination despite no exposure.
pit: Distinguish from worries; obsessions are irrational and ego-dystonic.
note: Obsessions are thoughts; compulsions are behaviors (e.g., washing hands).

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.compulsions
def: Repetitive behaviors or mental acts performed to reduce anxiety caused by obsessions. / 为减轻由强迫观念引起的焦虑而重复的行为或心理活动。
ex: Hand washing 20 times a day to neutralize contamination fear.
pit: Compulsions are not done for pleasure; they are anxiety-driven.
note: Compulsions temporarily reduce anxiety, but reinforce the obsession.

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.obsessive-compulsive-disorder
def: A disorder with obsessions and/or compulsions that are time-consuming and impair daily life. / 具有耗时且损害日常生活的强迫观念和/或强迫行为的障碍。
ex: Checking locks 50 times before leaving home.
pit: Not all repetitive habits are OCD; must cause significant distress.
note: Lifetime prevalence ~2%; treated with ERP therapy and SSRIs.

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.hoarding-disorder
def: Persistent difficulty discarding possessions, regardless of their value, leading to clutter that impairs living spaces. / 持续难以丢弃物品（无论其价值），导致杂乱妨碍生活空间。
ex: Accumulating old newspapers for years until rooms are unusable.
pit: Not simply being messy; hoarding causes functional impairment.
note: Often co-occurs with OCD but is a distinct disorder.

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.dissociative-disorders
def: Disorders involving a disruption in consciousness, memory, identity, or perception. / 涉及意识、记忆、身份或知觉分裂的障碍。
ex: Dissociative amnesia, dissociative identity disorder.
pit: Dissociation can occur in PTSD too; these disorders are primary.
note: Often linked to severe trauma.

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.dissociation
def: A mental separation from one's normal consciousness, memory, or sense of identity. / 精神上与正常意识、记忆或身份感的分隔。
ex: "Zoning out" while driving; feeling unreal.
pit: Not always pathological; mild dissociation is common.
note: Pathological dissociation is involuntary and disruptive.

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.dissociative-amnesia
def: Inability to recall important personal information, usually after trauma or stress, not due to ordinary forgetting. / 无法回忆重要个人信息，通常由创伤或压力引起，非普通遗忘。
ex: Forgetting whole weeks after a car accident.
pit: Not the same as "forgetting" from brain injury; it's psychological.
note: Often selective; may involve fugue (wandering).

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.dissociative-identity-disorder
def: A disorder with two or more distinct personality states (alters) that recurrently take control of behavior, with gaps in memory. / 以两个或更多不同人格状态（交替人格）反复控制行为并有记忆空白为特征的障碍。
ex: "Sybil" case; a person shifts between child and adult personalities.
pit: Controversial; some argue it's iatrogenic or culture-bound.
note: Almost always linked to severe childhood trauma.

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.trauma-and-stressor-related-disorders
def: Disorders triggered by exposure to traumatic or stressful events. / 由暴露于创伤或应激事件引发的障碍。
ex: PTSD, acute stress disorder, adjustment disorder.
pit: PTSD requires specific criteria: re-experiencing, avoidance, negative mood, arousal.
note: Trauma can be direct or witnessed; not all stress leads to disorder.

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.hypervigilance
def: A state of heightened alertness, constantly scanning for threats. / 高度警觉，持续扫描威胁的状态。
ex: A PTSD survivor checking every room before sitting down. / 创伤后应激障碍幸存者检查每个房间后才坐下。
pit: Often confused with paranoia; hypervigilance has a known trigger, paranoia involves irrational beliefs. / 常与偏执混淆；高度警觉有已知诱因，偏执涉及非理性信念。
note: Key symptom of PTSD and anxiety disorders. / 创伤后应激障碍和焦虑障碍的关键症状。

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.flashbacks
def: Vivid, involuntary re-experiencing of a traumatic event as if it were happening now. / 生动、非自愿地重新体验创伤事件，仿佛正在发生。
ex: A car crash survivor hearing a screech and seeing the accident replay. / 车祸幸存者听到刺耳声，脑中重现事故画面。
pit: Not just a memory; flashbacks feel immediate and real. / 不仅是记忆，闪回感觉即时而真实。
note: Core intrusive symptom of PTSD. / 创伤后应激障碍的核心闯入症状。

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.insomnia
def: Chronic difficulty falling or staying asleep. / 慢性入睡或维持睡眠困难。
ex: Lying awake for hours worrying about stressors. / 躺数小时不眠，担心压力源。
pit: Occasional poor sleep is not insomnia; must be frequent and impairing. / 偶尔睡不好不是失眠；需频繁且受损。
note: Can be primary or comorbid with PTSD, depression. / 可原发或与创伤后应激障碍、抑郁共病。

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.emotional-detachment
def: Feeling disconnected from one’s own emotions or from other people. / 感觉与自己情绪或他人脱节。
ex: A trauma survivor describing events without any feeling. / 创伤幸存者无感情地描述事件。
pit: Different from dissociation (depersonalization/derealization); detachment is more interpersonal/emotional. / 不同于解离（人格解体/现实解体）；情感疏离更多是人际/情绪方面。
note: Common in PTSD and some personality disorders. / 常见于创伤后应激障碍和某些人格障碍。

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.hostility
def: Persistent anger, aggression, or irritability. / 持续的愤怒、攻击性或易激惹。
ex: A person with PTSD shouting at a perceived minor provocation. / 创伤后应激障碍患者对微小刺激大吼大叫。
pit: Not just normal anger; chronic hostility impairs relationships. / 不仅是正常愤怒；慢性敌意损害人际关系。
note: Associated with PTSD and antisocial personality disorder. / 与创伤后应激障碍和反社会人格障碍相关。

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.posttraumatic-stress-disorder
def: A disorder after exposure to trauma, with intrusion, avoidance, negative mood, and arousal symptoms lasting >1 month. / 创伤后出现的障碍，包括闯入、回避、负性情绪和警觉性增高症状，持续超过1个月。
ex: A veteran with nightmares, avoiding crowds, and being easily startled. / 退伍军人出现噩梦、回避人群、易受惊吓。
pit: Not everyone who experiences trauma develops PTSD; symptoms must cause significant distress/impairment. / 不是每个经历创伤的人都患创伤后应激障碍；症状需引起显著痛苦/损害。
note: Key categories: intrusion, avoidance, negative alterations, arousal/reactivity. / 关键分类：闯入、回避、负性改变、警觉/反应性。

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.feeding-and-eating-disorders
def: Disturbances in eating behavior that impair physical health or psychosocial functioning. / 损害身体健康或心理社会功能的进食行为紊乱。
ex: Anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa, binge-eating disorder. / 神经性厌食症、神经性贪食症、暴食障碍。
pit: Not just picky eating or dieting; involves psychological criteria. / 不只是挑食或节食；包含心理标准。
note: Includes pica and rumination disorder. / 包括异食癖和反刍障碍。

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.anorexia-nervosa
def: Restriction of energy intake, intense fear of weight gain, and distorted body image. / 能量摄入限制、对体重增加的强烈恐惧、自我体像扭曲。
ex: A person who weighs 85 lbs but believes they are “too fat.” / 体重85磅的人仍认为“太胖”。
pit: Diagnosing requires both restriction and body image distortion; weight alone is insufficient. / 诊断需同时有限制和体像扭曲；仅体重不够。
note: Highest mortality rate of any mental disorder. / 所有精神障碍中死亡率最高。

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.bulimia-nervosa
def: Recurrent binge eating (large amounts with loss of control) followed by inappropriate compensatory behaviors (e.g., vomiting). / 反复暴食（量大伴失控感）后出现不当代偿行为（如呕吐）。
ex: Eating a whole pizza then making oneself vomit. / 吃掉整个披萨后自行催吐。
pit: Individuals often maintain normal or overweight; not just “overeating.” / 患者体重常正常或超重；不仅仅是“暴食”。
note: Often secretive; purging subtypes exist. / 常秘密进行；存在清除亚型。

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.personality-disorders
def: Enduring, inflexible patterns of thinking, feeling, and behaving that cause distress or impairment. / 持久、僵化的思维、情感和行为模式，导致痛苦或损害。
ex: Borderline personality disorder with unstable relationships and intense emotions. / 边缘型人格障碍伴不稳定关系和强烈情绪。
pit: Not just a “difficult personality”; must cause significant functional impairment. / 不仅仅是“难相处的性格”；需导致显著功能损害。
note: Three clusters: A (odd/eccentric), B (dramatic/erratic), C (anxious/fearful). / 三组：A（古怪/怪异）、B（戏剧化/情绪化）、C（焦虑/恐惧）。

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.cluster-a-odd-or-eccentric-cluster
def: A group of personality disorders marked by odd, eccentric behavior, resembling schizophrenia but less severe / 以古怪、异常行为为特征的人格障碍群，类似精神分裂症但较轻
ex: Paranoid, schizoid, schizotypal PDs / 偏执型、分裂样、分裂型人格障碍
pit: Not schizophrenia; lacks psychosis / 非精神分裂症，无精神病性症状
note: AP tip: remember "weird" cluster (A) / 记住“怪异型”簇（A）

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.paranoid-personality-disorder
def: Pervasive distrust and suspicion of others' motives, seen as malevolent / 普遍不信任和怀疑他人动机，认为有恶意
ex: Thinks coworkers plot against them without evidence / 认为同事无证据地密谋对付自己
pit: Not delusional; suspicions are misinterpretations, not fixed false beliefs / 非妄想；怀疑是误解，非固定错误信念
note: AP key: differentiate from paranoid schizophrenia (no hallucinations) / 与偏执型精神分裂症区分（无幻觉）

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.schizoid-personality-disorder
def: Detachment from social relationships and restricted emotional expression / 脱离社会关系，情感表达受限
ex: Prefers solitary activities, indifferent to praise or criticism / 偏好独自活动，对表扬或批评漠不关心
pit: No desire for intimacy; lacks interest, not discomfort / 无亲密需求；缺乏兴趣而非不适
note: AP: contrast with avoidant PD (wants relationships but fears) / 与回避型区分（想但怕）

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.schizotypal-personality-disorder
def: Odd beliefs, magical thinking, unusual perceptions, and social anxiety / 古怪信念、魔法思维、异常感知，伴社交焦虑
ex: Believes in telepathy or sees hidden meanings in daily events / 相信心灵感应或从日常中看出隐藏含义
pit: Closer to schizophrenia but not psychotic; ideas of reference may appear / 接近精神分裂症但非精神病性；可出现牵连观念
note: AP tip: quirky beliefs but no full psychosis; odd speech pattern / 古怪信念但非完全精神病性；言语怪异

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.cluster-b-dramatic-emotional-or-erratic-cluster
def: A group of personality disorders marked by dramatic, emotional, or unpredictable behavior / 以戏剧化、情绪化或不可预测行为为特征的人格障碍群
ex: Antisocial, borderline, histrionic, narcissistic PDs / 反社会型、边缘型、表演型、自恋型
pit: Often confused with mood disorders; these are enduring personality patterns / 常与情绪障碍混淆；此为持久人格模式
note: AP: remember "BAD" cluster (Borderline, Antisocial, Histrionic, Narcissistic) / 记住“BAD”簇

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.antisocial-personality-disorder
def: Disregard for others' rights, lack of remorse or empathy / 漠视他人权利，无懊悔或同理心
ex: Repeated lying, stealing, aggression without guilt / 反复撒谎、偷窃、攻击而无内疚
pit: Must be 18+ with conduct disorder history before 15 / 需18岁以上且15岁前有品行障碍史
note: AP: often labeled "psychopath" but clinically lacks anxiety / 常称“精神病态”，但临床缺乏焦虑

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.histrionic-personality-disorder
def: Excessive emotionality and attention-seeking behavior / 过度情绪化和寻求关注行为
ex: Dresses provocatively, overly dramatic, uncomfortable when not center / 穿着挑逗、过度戏剧化、不当焦点不适
pit: Not just drama; pervasive pattern; easily influenced by others / 不仅是戏剧化；普遍模式；易受他人影响
note: AP: distinguish from narcissistic (craves attention vs. admiration) / 区分：表演型渴求关注；自恋型渴求钦佩

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.narcissistic-personality-disorder
def: Grandiose self-importance, need for admiration, lack of empathy / 夸大自我重要性，需要钦佩，缺乏同理心
ex: Exaggerates achievements, expects special treatment, belittles others / 夸大成就，期待特殊对待，贬低他人
pit: Fragile self-esteem underneath; not just confidence / 底层脆弱自尊；不仅是自信
note: AP: grandiose fantasies; reacts with rage to criticism / 夸大幻想；对批评常反应愤怒

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.borderline-personality-disorder
def: Instability in relationships, self-image, emotions, and impulsivity; fear of abandonment / 人际关系、自我形象、情绪不稳定及冲动；害怕被抛弃
ex: Rapid mood shifts, self-harm (e.g., cutting), feelings of emptiness / 情绪快速波动、自伤（如割伤）、空虚感
pit: Not bipolar; mood swings are reactive to interpersonal stress / 非双相；情绪波动对人际压力反应
note: AP key: chronic emptiness, unstable self-identity; often comorbid with depression / 慢性空虚，自我不稳定；常共病抑郁

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.cluster-c-anxious-or-fearful-cluster
def: A group of personality disorders marked by anxious or fearful behavior / 以焦虑或恐惧行为为特征的人格障碍群
ex: Avoidant, dependent, obsessive-compulsive PDs / 回避型、依赖型、强迫型
pit: Not same as anxiety disorders; lifelong patterns / 非焦虑障碍；终身模式
note: AP tip: remember "worried" cluster (C) / 记住“忧虑型”簇（C）

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.avoidant-personality-disorder
def: A pervasive pattern of social inhibition, feelings of inadequacy, and hypersensitivity to negative evaluation / 广泛性社交抑制、不自信及对负面评价过度敏感的人格障碍
ex: John avoids parties because he fears being criticized or rejected, despite wanting friends
pit: Confused with social anxiety disorder—AP test asks for personality disorder, not acute fear
note: Cluster C, often co-occurs with social anxiety; distinguish from schizoid (no desire for relationships)

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.dependent-personality-disorder
def: A submissive, clingy behavior driven by an excessive need to be taken care of / 因过度依赖他人照顾而表现顺从、黏人的行为模式
ex: Sarah can't make decisions without her partner's approval and fears being left alone
pit: Confused with borderline (intense, unstable relationships) vs. dependent (passive, clingy)
note: Cluster C; focus on “need for nurturance” in diagnostic criteria

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-4.obsessive-compulsive-personality-disorder
def: A pervasive pattern of preoccupation with order, perfectionism, and control / 对秩序、完美和控制过度执着的人格障碍
ex: Tom spends 2 hours arranging his desk symmetrically, delaying his work
pit: NOT the same as OCD (ego-dystonic obsessions/compulsions); OCPD is ego-syntonic and less distressing
note: Cluster C; AP loves contrasting OCPD with OCD—remember “personality disorder” vs “anxiety disorder”

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.evidence-based-interventions
def: Treatments that are supported by rigorous scientific research (e.g., controlled trials) / 基于严格科学实证支持的治疗方法（如对照试验）
ex: CBT for depression is an evidence-based intervention; rebirthing therapy is not
pit: “Evidence-based” ≠ “whatever works for one client”; requires replication
note: AP may ask which therapy is empirically supported; CBT, DBT, and some medications qualify

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.cultural-humility
def: A lifelong commitment to self-reflection, learning from clients’ cultural backgrounds, and balancing power / 终身反思自身文化、向服务对象学习及其文化背景，并平衡权力关系的态度
ex: A therapist asks, “Tell me how your cultural background affects your view of my treatment plan”
pit: Not just “knowing about other cultures” (cultural competence) but ongoing humility and openness
note: AP may contrast with cultural competence; humility emphasizes process, not mastery

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.therapeutic-alliance
def: The collaborative, trusting relationship between therapist and client / 治疗师与来访者之间合作、信任的治疗关系
ex: A client feels safe to share secrets because the therapist listens without judgment
pit: Confused with transference (projecting past onto therapist); alliance is the actual working bond
note: Strong predictor of positive outcome; AP may ask about common factors across therapies

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.psychotropic-medication
def: Drugs that affect mental processes, used to treat psychological disorders / 影响心理过程、用于治疗心理障碍的药物
ex: SSRIs like fluoxetine (Prozac) treat depression by increasing serotonin
pit: Not “cure” but symptom management; can have side effects like weight gain or sexual dysfunction
note: AP may link to biological approach; know major classes (antidepressants, antipsychotics, etc.)

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.nonmaleficence
def: The ethical principle to do no harm / 伦理原则：不造成伤害
ex: A therapist avoids using a controversial technique that might retraumatize a client
pit: Confused with beneficence (do good); nonmaleficence is the “first, do no harm”
note: AP’s ethics questions often test distinguishing nonmaleficence from other ethical principles

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.fidelity
def: The ethical principle of being loyal, responsible, and trustworthy in professional relationships / 伦理原则：对职业关系保持忠诚、负责和值得信赖
ex: A therapist keeps promises to meet at scheduled times and maintains confidentiality
pit: Not the same as “fidelity” in relationships; here it’s about upholding professional commitments
note: AP may list fidelity with integrity and nonmaleficence; know each’s nuance

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.integrity
def: The ethical principle of being honest, fair, and accurate in one’s work / 伦理原则：在专业工作中保持诚实、公正和准确
ex: A psychologist reports research findings truthfully, even if they don’t support the hypothesis
pit: Confused with honesty in general; integrity in ethics includes accuracy, avoiding fraud
note: AP ties integrity to ethical research and clinical practice; expect a scenario about data falsification

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.respect-for-people-s-rights-and-dignity
def: Ethical principle that therapists honor clients' autonomy, privacy, and informed consent / 尊重来访者的自主权、隐私和知情同意的伦理原则
ex: A therapist explains treatment risks before starting therapy
pit: Confusing with confidentiality; rights include more than just privacy
note: Key APA ethical guideline; may appear in ethics questions

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.psychodynamic-therapies
def: Therapies focusing on unconscious conflicts, often through free association and dream analysis / 通过自由联想和梦的分析关注无意识冲突的治疗方法
ex: A client talks freely about childhood to uncover repressed memories
pit: Often confused with psychoanalysis; psychodynamic is broader, less intensive
note: Emphasizes past experiences; MCQs test key techniques

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.free-association
def: Client says whatever comes to mind without censorship to reveal unconscious thoughts / 患者不设限地说出脑海中一切，以揭示无意识想法
ex: "I see a tree... then a rope... reminds me of a swing in my yard..."
pit: Mistaken as random talking; therapist interprets, not just listens
note: Classic psychoanalytic technique; may be compared to projective tests

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.dream-interpretation
def: Analyzing dream content to uncover hidden unconscious desires or conflicts / 分析梦境内容以揭示隐藏的无意识欲望或冲突
ex: Client dreams of falling; therapist suggests fear of losing control
pit: Overfocus on manifest content; latent content is key meaning
note: Freud's "royal road to the unconscious"; often linked to wish fulfillment

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.cognitive-therapies
def: Therapies that identify and change maladaptive thought patterns to improve emotions and behavior / 识别并改变适应不良思维模式以改善情绪和行为的疗法
ex: A depressed person learns to challenge "I'm a failure" thoughts
pit: Confusing with CBT; cognitive therapy is a component of CBT
note: Beck & Ellis; focus on here-and-now thinking, not past

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.cognitive-restructuring
def: Replacing irrational or negative thoughts with more realistic, adaptive ones / 用更现实、适应的想法取代非理性或消极想法
ex: Changing "I must be perfect" to "I can try my best"
pit: Not just "positive thinking"; must be evidence-based
note: Core technique in Beck's cognitive therapy; tests on replacing distortions

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.fear-hierarchies
def: Ranked list of feared situations from least to most anxiety-provoking, used in exposure therapy / 从最不焦虑到最焦虑的恐惧情境列表，用于暴露疗法
ex: For spider phobia: 1) picture of spider → 5) holding a spider
pit: Not the same as systematic desensitization alone; hierarchy is a tool
note: Used with relaxation or exposure; key in behavioral therapy

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.combating-maladaptive-thinking
def: Actively challenging and correcting distorted thoughts that cause distress / 主动挑战并纠正导致痛苦的不合理思维
ex: "Everyone hates me" → "Is that really true? What evidence do I have?"
pit: Not just denying negative feelings; requires rational analysis
note: Cognitive therapy technique; often paired with cognitive distortions list

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.cognitive-triad
def: Negative view of self, world, and future; core of depression (Beck) / 对自我、世界和未来的消极看法；抑郁症核心（贝克）
ex: "I'm worthless" (self) + "Life is unfair" (world) + "Things will never get better" (future)
pit: Only applies to depression, not all disorders
note: Beck's depression model; memorise three components

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.applied-behavior-analysis
def: Using operant conditioning (rewards/punishments) to modify behaviors, often for autism / 运用操作性条件反射（奖励/惩罚）改变行为，常用于自闭症
ex: A child with autism receives a sticker for making eye contact
pit: Confusing with ABA as only for autism; also used in other settings
note: Evidence-based; focuses on measurable behavior change; FR/VR schedules may be tested

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.exposure-therapies
def: Behavioral techniques that reduce fear by repeated exposure to the feared object/situation / 通过反复接触恐惧刺激来降低焦虑的行为疗法
ex: A spider phobic gradually looks at photos, then a real spider in a jar
pit: Exposure ≠ flooding (sudden intense exposure) – both are exposure therapies
note: Often paired with relaxation; key for anxiety disorders on FRQ

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.systematic-desensitization
def: Gradual exposure paired with relaxation to extinguish fear / 在放松状态下逐步接触恐惧事物，消除焦虑
ex: Fear of flying: first imagine plane, then visit airport, then short flight
pit: Must use a fear hierarchy; skipping steps ruins the process
note: Based on counterconditioning; compare with flooding

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.aversion-therapies
def: Pair an undesirable behavior with an unpleasant stimulus to reduce it / 将不良行为与厌恶刺激配对，减少该行为
ex: Alcoholic given nausea-inducing drug when drinking
pit: It does not address underlying causes; may be temporary
note: A type of counterconditioning; used for addictions

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.token-economies
def: Reinforce desired behaviors with tokens exchangeable for rewards / 用可兑换奖励的代币强化良好行为
ex: Psychiatric ward patients earn tokens for making bed, redeem for TV time
pit: Tokens are secondary reinforcers; must be paired with primary reinforcers
note: Operant conditioning in therapy; often on MC

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.biofeedback
def: Use electronic monitoring to gain voluntary control over physiological processes / 利用电子设备监测并学习自主调控生理反应
ex: Relaxation training using a heart rate monitor to lower anxiety
pit: Not control over all bodily functions; requires practice
note: Often paired with relaxation techniques; stress-related disorders

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.cognitive-behavioral-therapies
def: Combines cognitive restructuring with behavioral techniques / 结合认知重建与行为技术，改变思维和行为
ex: For depression: identify negative thoughts + schedule pleasant activities
pit: Not just positive thinking; must change both thoughts and actions
note: CBT is evidence-based; common on FRQ

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.dialectical-behavior-therapy
def: CBT variant that balances acceptance and change, often for borderline personality disorder / 强调接纳与改变的平衡，常用于边缘型人格障碍
ex: Therapist validates client’s emotions while teaching coping skills like distress tolerance
pit: DBT is not just “accept everything”; it also pushes for change
note: Key: “dialectical” = opposite forces; emotion regulation skills

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.rational-emotive-behavior-therapy-rebt
def: Challenge irrational beliefs that cause distress, replacing them with rational ones / 挑战导致痛苦的非理性信念，代之以理性信念
ex: “I must be perfect” → “It’s okay to make mistakes”
pit: REBT is directive, confrontational, not just listening
note: Albert Ellis; ABC model (Activating event, Belief, Consequence)

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.person-centered-therapy
def: Non-directive therapy where therapist provides empathy, genuineness, and unconditional positive regard / 非指导性疗法，治疗师提供共情、真诚和积极关注
ex: Client leads the session; therapist reflects feelings without directing
pit: Therapist does not offer advice or interpretation
note: Carl Rogers; focus on client’s self-healing potential

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.unconditional-positive-regard
def: Complete acceptance of the client without judgment / 无条件接纳客户，不作评判
ex: Therapist respects client’s choices even if harmful, without approving them
pit: Not the same as always agreeing; it’s non-judgmental acceptance
note: Essential for person-centered therapy; builds trust

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.active-listening
def: A therapeutic technique where the therapist listens attentively and empathetically, paraphrasing and reflecting feelings / 治疗师专注共情地倾听，通过释义和反映情感来理解来访者
ex: Therapist says, "It sounds like you felt abandoned when your friend didn't call" / 治疗师说：“听起来朋友没打电话让你感到被抛弃了”
pit: Not just silent hearing; must include active feedback / 不仅是安静听，必须包含积极反馈
note: Often asked as key Rogerian technique with unconditional positive regard / 常作为罗杰斯疗法关键技巧与无条件积极关注一起考

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.group-therapy
def: Therapy conducted with multiple clients together, often led by one or two therapists / 由一位或两位治疗师带领多名来访者共同进行的治疗
ex: A support group for people with social anxiety practicing social skills together / 社交焦虑者一起练习社交技能的支持小组
pit: Not cheaper per session necessarily; benefit is peer support and feedback / 并非每次必然更便宜；优势在于同伴支持与反馈
note: Often compared to individual therapy; mention Yalom's therapeutic factors / 常和个体治疗比较；提及亚隆的治疗因子

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.hypnosis
def: A state of heightened suggestibility and focused attention, used therapeutically for pain control, habit change / 一种高度受暗示性和注意力集中的状态，用于疼痛控制、习惯改变等治疗
ex: A patient with chronic pain learns self-hypnosis to reduce pain perception / 慢性疼痛患者学习自我催眠降低疼痛感知
pit: Not a sleep state; client is not under therapist's control / 不是睡眠状态；来访者并非受治疗师控制
note: Contraindicated for some disorders; effectiveness varies / 对某些障碍禁忌；效果因人而异

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.psychoactive-medication
def: Drugs that affect brain chemistry to treat psychological disorders / 影响大脑化学物质以治疗心理障碍的药物
ex: SSRIs like Prozac for depression / 如治疗抑郁的百忧解（SSRI）
pit: Do not "cure" disorders; manage symptoms / 不能“治愈”障碍，只是控制症状
note: Broad category; know major classes: antidepressants, antianxiety, antipsychotics, lithium / 大类；要认知主要类别：抗抑郁药、抗焦虑药、抗精神病药、锂盐

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.antidepressants
def: Medications that increase neurotransmitter activity (e.g., serotonin, norepinephrine) to relieve depression / 增加神经递质（如5-羟色胺、去甲肾上腺素）活性以缓解抑郁的药物
ex: SSRIs (e.g., Zoloft) block serotonin reuptake / SSRI（如左洛复）阻止5-羟色胺再摄取
pit: Take weeks to work; may increase suicide risk early / 需数周起效；初期可能增加自杀风险
note: Compare with MAOIs (dietary restrictions) and tricyclics / 与MAOI（饮食限制）和三环类比较

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.antianxiety-drugs
def: Medications that reduce anxiety, often by depressing CNS activity (e.g., benzodiazepines) / 通过抑制中枢神经系统活动（如苯二氮䓬类）减轻焦虑的药物
ex: Xanax (alprazolam) used for panic attacks / 阿普唑仑（Xanax）用于惊恐发作
pit: High risk of dependence and tolerance; not first-line for GAD / 高依赖性和耐受性风险；不首选于广泛焦虑障碍
note: Often distractingly called "tranquilizers" / 常被误导称为“镇定剂”

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.lithium
def: A mood stabilizer used primarily for bipolar disorder / 主要用于双相情感障碍的情绪稳定剂
ex: Reduces both manic and depressive episodes / 减少躁狂和抑郁发作
pit: Requires monitoring of blood levels due to narrow therapeutic window / 因治疗窗窄需监测血药浓度
note: Unique: not an antidepressant or antipsychotic; works as salt / 独特：既非抗抑郁药也非抗精神病药；作为盐起作用

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.antipsychotic-medications
def: Drugs that block dopamine receptors to reduce positive symptoms of schizophrenia / 阻断多巴胺受体以减轻精神分裂症阳性症状的药物
ex: Chlorpromazine (Thorazine) for hallucinations / 氯丙嗪（Thorazine）用于幻觉
pit: Do not treat negative symptoms effectively / 对阴性症状效果不佳
note: Atypical antipsychotics (e.g., Clozaril) also affect serotonin; lower side effect risk for EPS / 非典型抗精神病药（如氯氮平）也影响5-羟色胺；降低锥体外系副作用风险

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.tardive-dyskinesia
def: A neurological disorder from long-term antipsychotic use: involuntary facial and limb movements / 长期使用抗精神病药引起的神经系统障碍：不自主的面部和肢体运动
ex: Lip smacking, tongue thrusting, grimacing / 咂嘴、伸舌、做鬼脸
pit: Not immediate; develops after months/years; may be irreversible / 非即刻出现；数月/年后发展；可能不可逆
note: Key side effect of typical antipsychotics; atypical have lower risk / 典型抗精神病药的主要副作用；非典型风险较低

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.psychosurgery
def: Surgical destruction of brain tissue to treat severe psychological disorders (rarely used) / 通过手术破坏脑组织治疗严重心理障碍（极少使用）
ex: Prefrontal lobotomy (historic) or cingulotomy (modern for OCD) / 前额叶切断术（历史）或扣带回切断术（现代用于强迫症）
pit: Not same as psychopharmacology; irreversible and controversial / 不同于精神药理学；不可逆且有争议
note: AP may ask ethical concerns; modern use limited to extreme cases / AP可能问伦理争议；现代仅限于极端病例

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.lesioning
def: Deliberately destroying brain tissue to treat severe psychological disorders / 通过破坏脑组织治疗严重心理障碍
ex: Removing a small part of the amygdala to reduce aggression in extreme cases
pit: Students confuse lesioning with lobotomy; lesioning is more precise and less invasive than older lobotomies
note: AP often asks how lesioning differs from other biological treatments

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.tms-transcranial-magnetic-stimulation
def: Using magnetic fields to stimulate nerve cells in the brain; non-invasive / 用磁场刺激脑神经细胞，无创
ex: Placing a magnetic coil on the scalp over the prefrontal cortex to treat depression
pit: TMS is not the same as ECT; it does not induce seizures and has fewer side effects
note: Common AP question: TMS is a treatment for depression without memory loss

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.electroconvulsive-therapy
def: Brief electrical stimulation of the brain to induce a seizure, used for severe depression / 短暂电刺激诱导癫痫发作，治疗重度抑郁
ex: Used when a patient with severe depression does not respond to medication or therapy
pit: It is not primitive torture; modern ECT is performed under anesthesia and muscle relaxants
note: AP loves to ask about ECT's effectiveness for treatment-resistant depression and its side effect of memory loss

@@ ap-psychology.u5.t5-5.lobotomy
def: Surgical severing of connections in the frontal lobe; historically used for mental illness / 手术切断额叶连接，历史上用于治疗精神疾病
ex: Portuguese neurologist Moniz performed prefrontal lobotomies on agitated patients in the 1940s
pit: Students think lobotomy is still common; it is now considered unethical and very rarely used
note: AP may ask why lobotomies were abandoned (loss of personality, ethics, development of medication)
